{"title_page": "Shoaib Akhtar", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Shoaib Akhtar\n| image = Shoaib Akhtar (13927458981).jpg\n| caption = \n| fullname = Shoaib Akhtar\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|8|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n| country = Pakistan\n| nickname = Rawalpindi Express, Tiger\n| height = 6ft 0in<ref>[https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/30/shoaib-akhtar Shoaib Akhtar's profile] on [[CricBuzz]]</ref>\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast]]\n| role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 1997\u20132011\n| testcap = 150\n| testdebutagainst = West Indies\n| testdebutdate = 29 November\n| testdebutyear = 1997\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| lasttestdate = 8 December\n| lasttestyear = 2007\n| odicap = 123\n| odidebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| odidebutdate = 28 March\n| odidebutyear = 1998\n| lastodiagainst = New Zealand\n| lastodidate = 8 March\n| lastodiyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = England\n| lastT20Idate = 28 December\n| lastT20Iyear = 2010\n| lastT20Iagainst = New Zealand\n| T20Icap = 9\n| odishirt = 14\n| columns = 3\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| runs1 = 544\n| matches1 = 46\n| bat avg1 = 10.07\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/0\n| top score1 = 47\n| deliveries1 = 8,143\n| wickets1 = 176\n| bowl avg1 = 25.69\n| fivefor1 = 12\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 6/11\n| catches/stumpings1 = 12/\u2013\n| matches2 = 163\n| runs2 = 394\n| bat avg2 = 8.95\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 43\n| deliveries2 = 7,764\n| wickets2 = 247\n| bowl avg2 = 24.97\n| fivefor2 = 4\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 6/16\n| catches/stumpings2 = 20/\u2013\n| matches3 = 15\n| runs3 = 21\n| bat avg3 = 7.00\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 8[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 318\n| wickets3 = 19\n| bowl avg3 = 22.73\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 3/38\n| catches/stumpings3 = 2/\u2013\n| date = 8 November\n| year = 2016\n| source = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42655.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Shoaib Akhtar''' ({{audio|Shoaib Akhtar Pronunciation.ogg|pronunciation}}; born 13 August 1975) is a Pakistani cricket commentator, YouTuber, and former cricketer who played all formats of the game over a fourteen year career. He is recognized as the [[Fast bowling|fastest bowler]] in the history of [[cricket]], delivering a world record top speed of 161.3{{nbsp}}km/h (100.23{{nbsp}}mph) in a pool match against England during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/fastest-bowl-of-a-cricket-ball/|title=Fastest delivery of a cricket ball (male)|author=|date=|work=[[Guinness World Records]]|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> Akhtar was nicknamed \"Rawalpindi Express\" and \"Tiger\" as a tribute to his hometown and fast bowling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/25921/shoaib-akhtar-the-legend-the-sensation-the-enigma/|title=Shoaib Akhtar \u2013 the legend, the sensation, the enigma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purbat.com/most-feared-fast-bowlers-cricket/|title=10 Most feared fast bowlers in Cricket history - Purbat.com|date=1 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He is also the first bowler to break the 100&nbsp;mph barrier, doing so twice in his career.\n\nAkhtar made his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in November 1997 as an opening [[fast bowling|fast bowler]] and played his first [[One Day International]] three months later. Akhtar has been involved in several controversies during his career, often accused of unsportsmanlike conduct, despite his commendations for significantly impacting games in Pakistan's favour. Akhtar was sent home during a Test match series in Australia in 2005 for alleged poor attitude. A year later, he was embroiled in a drug scandal after testing positive for the performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]]. However, the ban imposed on him was lifted on appeal. In his latest YouTube video, Akhtar took a dig at Virender Sehwag saying he is very happy that his words are given so much importance and it turns into breaking [https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/shoaib-akhtar-virender-sehwag-hair-money-taunt-youtube-1639242-2020-01-22 news].\n\nIn September 2007, he received a ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |title=PCB bans Shoaib Akhtar for an indefinite period |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614042556/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |archivedate=14 June 2015 }}</ref> On 1 April 2008, Akhtar was banned for five years for publicly criticising the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar gets 5-year ban for foul delivery &#124; It's unfair |publisher=Ibnlive.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403102400/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |archive-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2008, the [[Lahore High Court]] in Pakistan suspended the five-year ban and Akhtar was selected in the 15-man squad for the Twenty20 Quadrangular Tournament in Canada.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/372804.html\n| title = Shoaib in for Canada, not Yousuf\n}}</ref> Pakistani judge [[Rana Bhagwandas]] once stated that Akhtar is a legend of Pakistan cricket.<ref>{{cite web |title=The law is equal for everyone in Pakistan |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/feb/14inter1.htm |author=Rediffnews |quote=I have little interest in cricket. People are crazy about cricket and we feel happy when our country wins. The names of Hanif Mohammad, Imran Khan, Shoaib Akhtar all come to my mind once I think about cricket. These are legends of Pakistani cricket}}</ref> Akhtar retired from international cricket after the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAkhtar was born in a small town in Morgah near [[Rawalpindi]], Pakistan. His father, Mohammad Akhtar, \"from a hardworking economically unprivileged family of the [[Gujjar]] community\", who worked as a night watchman at a petrol station belonging to the [[Attock Refinery Limited|Attock oil refinery]], married his mother, Hameeda [[Awan (tribe)|Awan]], when she was still a teenager, and they had five children: four sons, Shoaib being the fourth after Shahid, Tahir and Obaid, followed by a daughter, Shumaila.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), p. 6</ref>\n\nHe married Rubab Khan on 11 November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haripur: Shoaib Akhtar tie the knot with Rubbabb|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/Cricket/226712-Haripur-Shoaib-Akhtar-tie-the-knot-with-Rubab|publisher=dunyanews.tv|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shoaib Akhtar secretly marries 20-year old Rubab Khan|url=http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|publisher=india.com|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629102747/http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|archivedate=29 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nA good student, Akhtar was admitted to the [[Government College Asghar Mall Rawalpindi|Asghar Mall College]], but disrupted his studies to attend trials for the [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA team]]'s Karachi division to be held in Lahore. Lacking the money for a bus ticket, he waited for the bus to start and got onto the roof.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 42-43</ref> After some struggle, starting his [[List A]] career during the 1993/1994 season and his [[First-class cricket|First-class]] career during the 1994/1995 one, he caught the eye of [[Majid Khan (cricketer, born 1946)|Majid Khan]], then the chief executive of the [[Pakistan Cricket Board|PCB]], and after a good performance for the [[Pakistan A]] team's tour of England, in 1996, he was rewarded his maiden Test cap against the West Indies, in 1997.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 58-59</ref>\n\n==International career==\nConsidering his subsequent high profile in cricket, Akhtar's test career started rather modestly. He was first picked to play on his home ground in Rawalpindi during the 2nd Test of the West Indies 1997/98 tour of Pakistan. He was subsequently included in the tour of South Africa during the winter of 1998, where he played in all three Tests. He was notably the spearhead of a depleted Pakistani bowling attack in the Peshawar Test against the visiting Australians later in 1998, where Mark Taylor scored his famous unbeaten 334 in Australia's first innings. Subsequently, after 8 tests and 16 innings, Akhtar had accumulated only 18 wickets.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/42655.html |title=Player profile: Shoaib Akhtar |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar's run of average performances started in 1999, during a pre-World Cup series against India. It was followed by high-class bowling performances in [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]] and later in the [[1999 Cricket World Cup]].\n\nIn 2002, he was selected for the Pakistan team against [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] and achieved  a small amount of success. However he performed poorly during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]] and after the tournament he was dropped from the Pakistan squad. \nHe was selected back into the Pakistan squad as they had no choice in the 2004 Test match series against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], but struggled in a losing Test series against [[India national cricket team|India]] in 2004. The series ended with a controversy when he left the field citing an injury leading to suspicions by former Pakistan captain, [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]], about his commitment to the team. As a result, his relationship with [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] and former Pakistan coach [[Bob Woolmer]] deteriorated. A medical panel was set up by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] to investigate the nature of his injury, however Pakistan officials dispelled all suspicions.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/140776.html | title = Bone scan puts Akhtar in the clear | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref>\n[[File:Shoaib Akhtar2.jpg|thumb]]\nIn 2005, Akhtar regained his reputation as a fast bowler for his side. Playing in a three Test home series against [[England cricket team|England]], he made a series of impressive bowling performances. His effective use of slower deliveries proved to be unplayable by the English batsmen. Akhtar emerged as the highest wicket taker of the series with seventeen wickets. His comeback was also remarkable as prior to his return, he had been criticised from all corners; such as by the Worcestershire chairman John Elliot for his celebrity attitude and lack of commitment to the team. His performance was also acknowledged by the English captain [[Michael Vaughan]], who remarked \"I thought he (Shoaib) was a big difference between the two teams\".<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/228332.html | title = Vaughan \u2013 Batsmen to blame | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref> He is also known as one of only three bowlers to have ever broken the 100&nbsp;mph barrier in cricket history, with a delivery of 100.2&nbsp;mph, during a one-day international against England in World cup 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/149874.html|title=Blink and you'll miss it|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Struggle for form and consistent injuries (2007\u20132009)===\nOn 29 October 2007, Akhtar made his return to cricket, from his 13 match ban and performed well, taking 4 wickets for 43 runs against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] in the fifth and deciding One Day International series in Lahore in Pakistan. Subsequently, he was included in the 16-man Pakistan squad for the [[Pakistani cricket team in India in 2007\u201308|2007 tour of India]].\n\n===Rehabilitation and final years (2010\u20132011)===\nAkhtar made a return to international cricket albeit in the shorter format of the game. In May 2010, PCB named him in a list of 35 probables for the [[2010 Asia Cup|Asia Cup]]. On 15 June 2010, Akhtar made his return, taking 3 wickets for 28 runs in the first match of the Asia Cup against Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Siddarth|title=Shoaib Akhtar makes a respectable return|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/asia2010/content/story/463287.html|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref> He narrowly missed out a spot in the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]] in place of the injured Umar Gul.\n\nIn July 2010, he was selected for the Twenty20 [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in England in 2010|series against Australia]] but the selectors decided not to play him in the Test squad so that he would not get injured. He was subsequently selected for the ODI and Twenty20 series against [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2010|England in September 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Geo TV|title=Shoaib Akhtar selected for ODI and Twenty20 series against England in September 2010|url=http://geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|publisher=Jang News|accessdate=26 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830183713/http://www.geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|archivedate=30 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar returned to the national side representing the country against England in the Twenty20 International. He bowled an impressive spell and returned with figures of 2 wickets for 23 runs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan bowler Shoaib Akhtar breathes new life into cricket's fast show|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/7985127/Pakistan-bowler-Shoaib-Akhtar-breathes-new-life-into-crickets-fast-show.html|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=6 November 2010|location=London|first=Steve|last=James|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> He continued to bowl well in the ODI series in the absence of regular fast-bowlers, [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] and [[Mohammad Amir]], who were suspended by the International Cricket Council amid allegations of [[Spot-fixing]]. Despite his relatively good bowling form, Pakistani coach [[Waqar Younis]] insisted that the bowling attack must not become reliant on Akhtar, as he is 35 years of age and fitness troubles continue to affect him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shoaib Akhtar can't do miracle at this age: Waqar |url=http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |publisher=Geo.tv |accessdate=6 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024225147/http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |archivedate=24 October 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> Akhtar was selected for the tour of New Zealand and started his campaign off well with 3 wickets on Boxing Day in the first of two Twenty20 Internationals against New Zealand.\n\nAkhtar was selected in Pakistan's 15-man squad to play in the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]] hosted by Bangladesh, India, and Sri Lanka in February to March. During the tournament, he announced that he would retire from international cricket at the end of the World Cup. He was dropped from the squad after group matches and was not included in the quarter final either.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/506599.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar to retire after World Cup |first=Osman |last=Samiuddin |publisher=Cricinfo |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> In September, Akhtar released his autobiography, ''[[Controversially Yours]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |title=Shoaib Akhtar's ''Controversially Yours'' released |publisher=GEO Sports |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=24 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926232325/http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\n===England county cricket===\nAkhtar has played for three English [[county cricket]] clubs: [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in 2001, [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] in 2003 and 2004 and [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in 2005. He did achieve his moments of success, such as taking 5 wickets for 35 runs for Durham against Somerset in the [[National League (cricket)|National League]] in 2003 and claiming 6 wickets for 16 runs in the same competition for Worcestershire against [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] two years later, but he suffered from fitness problems, as well as a perception that he was less than interested in his task. This was particularly the case at Worcestershire: chairman John Elliott said \"Players like that are no good to our club. In fact, Akhtar has been no good for any club he's been at. He's a superstar and just does what he wants.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/current/story/295629.html | title=Dodgy overseas signings | author=Steve Pittard and John Stern | date=24 May 2007 | accessdate=24 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\n===Indian Premier League===\nAkhtar made a successful return to cricket in his first game in the [[Indian Premier League]], playing for the [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] against the [[Delhi Daredevils]]. Defending a low score of 133 runs, Akhtar took four top order wickets which ultimately led to the Daredevils being restricted to 110 runs. He ended with figures of 4 wickets for 11 runs from three overs, a performance which earned him the player of the match award.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/engine/match/336017.html Indian Premier League \u2013 35th match, Kolkata Knight Riders v Delhi Daredevils]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref><ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350889.html Shoaib leads Delhi drubbing]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref> Akhtar denied that he had any point to prove with his performance, stating, \"I just wanted to win the game.\" Knight Riders' captain [[Sourav Ganguly]] also acknowledged Akhtar's performance, \"He came to the country with lots [of things] happening behind him...But he showed a lot of character.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350924.html I have no point to prove \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref>\n\nHe has also played for [[Cyclones of Chittagong]] in Bangladesh's [[Bangladesh NCL (National Cricket League) Twenty20|NCL T20 Bangladesh]].\n\n==Cricket controversies and injuries==\nAkhtar's career has been plagued with injuries, controversies and accusations of poor attitude. After a poor performance in the 2003 Cricket World Cup, he got involved in a verbal conflict with former Pakistan captain and fast bowler [[Waqar Younis]]. Later on Akhtar was sacked along with other players, including Younis. In a triangular series in 2003 held in Sri Lanka, he was caught [[ball tampering]] making him the second player in cricket to be banned on ball tampering charges. The same year he was banned for one Test match and two One Day International matches for abusing South African spin bowler [[Paul Adams (cricketer)|Paul Adams]], during a match against South Africa. In the 2004 home series with India, he struggled with wrist and back injuries, which raised questions about his commitment to the team.\n\nHe was sent back from the 2005 Australia tour with a hamstring injury amid rumours of indiscipline, lack of commitment and attitudinal complaints. He was subsequently fined by the Pakistan Cricket Board for avoiding a late night curfew.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm ABC Sport \u2013 Cricket \u2013 Pakistan's Akhtar fined for Australian disco jaunt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020024458/http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm |date=20 October 2007 }}</ref> The rest of his cricketing career was riddled with ankle and knee injuries which forced him to undergo a surgery in February 2006, until finally he was banned for two years for allegedly using performance-enhancing drugs.\n\nIn November 2006, an officer assigned to the Pakistan team in India, Anil Kaul, alleged that Akhtar had slapped former coach Bob Woolmer following a fight over the music to be played in the team bus on the eve of ICC Champions Trophy. Both Akhtar and Woolmer have strongly denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707151418/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |archivedate=7 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Drug scandal===\nOn 16 October 2006 Akhtar was suspended by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]], along with [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammed Asif]] after they tested positive for a performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/iccct2006/content/current/story/263238.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Asif and Akhtar to return home |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> They were consequently pulled out from the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,20589658-23212,00.html |title=Shoaib returns positive test |date=16 October 2006 |author=Staff writers and wires |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|FOX SPORTS Australia]]}}</ref> Former Pakistan Cricket Board chairman later stated that he had always suspected Akhtar of substance abuse due to his consistent \"reservations\" to drug tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714064906/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |archivedate=14 July 2012 }}</ref> Former Pakistan captain [[Inzamam ul-Haq]] had also previously complained about Akhtar's drug abuse but was not reported to the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://paktribune.com/news/index.shtml?158859 |title=Pakistan News Service \u2013 PakTribune |publisher=Paktribune.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Akhtar immediately declared his innocence and he declined knowingly taking any performance-enhancing drugs. In a statement issued to the press, he claimed that he could never cheat teammates or opponents.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6054724.stm | work=BBC News | title=Shocked Shoaib protests innocence | date=16 October 2006 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> During a hearing with the Pakistan Cricket Board Anti-Doping Committee, he along with Asif maintained taking non-steroidal dietary supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-ind.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/266665.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Sad but we had to make an example of Shoaib \u2013 Alam |publisher=Content-ind.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He, however, failed to convince the committee of his innocence. In its report submitted to the Pakistan Cricket Board, the Anti-Doping Committee recommended a two-year ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcboard.com.pk/Pakistan/Articles/5/5298.html |title=Pakistan Cricket Board \u2013 official website |publisher=Pcboard.com.pk |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 November 2006 the Pakistan Cricket Board handed down a two-year suspension to Akhtar and a one-year suspension to Asif, banning them from professional cricket during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/266573.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif banned for drugs use |publisher=Uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Shoaib had subsequently been added to [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] list of doping offenders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191359/http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, on 5 December 2006 represented by his lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], Akhtar was cleared on appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/australia/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2006 Akhtar and Asif were acquitted by the tribunal appointed to review their appeals. After a clear hearing from Akhtar's lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], the three-man committee, voted two to one in favour of the acquittal. Justice Fakhruddin Ebrahim, committee head, and Haseeb Ahsan, former Test cricketer, were in favour of the acquittal. The third member, Danish Zaheer, differed. \"Exceptional circumstances\" were cited including discrepancies between the instantaneous offence charges of doping that were laid and the quick delivery of a very harsh verdict. The complete drug testing procedure was concluded to have been technically flawed as it did not follow standard procedures. Other established facts by the committee included that the duo were not aware of the banned drug to be present in their supplements because the Pakistan Cricket Board itself had not informed them of the dangers of contaminated supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-pak.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-pak.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/271347.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Dope on the doping scandal |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar and Asif, however, did not play in the subsequent Test match series against the West Indies because the Pakistan Cricket Board had recommended that they play domestic games first to recover form and fitness.{{cn|date=November 2017}} On 1 March 2007 Akhtar and Asif were ruled out of the Pakistani squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] by team officials, minutes before the squad was to depart for the [[West Indies]]. The team management along with the Pakistan Cricket Board said their injuries were too severe to risk taking them to the Caribbean. Since neither of the two had been declared fit they did not undergo official doping tests.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wc2007/content/current/story/281976.html Shoaib and Asif out of the World Cup]:</ref>\n\n[[World Anti-Doping Agency]] ( WADA) challenged Pakistan's decision to lift bans on fast bowlers Akhtar and Asif by taking the case to the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6183997.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Cricket &#124; International Teams &#124; Pakistan &#124; Pakistan to face doping challenge |publisher=BBC News |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The ICC supported the WADA appeal adding that it was committed to a dope free game. On 2 July 2007, the Court of Arbitration for Sport dropped the case, ruling it had no jurisdiction to challenge the decision made by PCB.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/300348.html Court has no jurisdiction in doping case]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6260498.stm Court cannot rule on Pakistan duo]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref>\n\n===Other controversies===\nIn August 2007, Akhtar was reported to have used foul language against Pakistan Cricket Board protesting the imposing of fine of Rs. 300,000 for indiscipline during the national camp in Karachi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120713153808/http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-13 |title=Shoaib uses foul language to protest PCB decision }}</ref> In the week before the inaugural [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World Twenty20]], held in South Africa, Akhtar was rumoured to have hit Pakistani teammate Mohammad Asif with a bat after an argument in the dressing room. It started after Akhtar was ridiculed by Asif and [[Shahid Afridi]] for comparing himself with [[Imran Khan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|title=Latest News, Breaking News Live, Current Headlines, India News Online \u2013 The Indian Express|website=www.indianexpress.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430055753/http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|archivedate=30 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/309867.html\n| title = Asif injured in dressing room spat by Akhtar\n}}</ref> After the initial inquiry, Akhtar was found to be at fault and was subsequently recalled from the Twenty20 World Cup squad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKSP16843120070907|title=Pakistan send Akhtar home after bustup|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref> and was sent home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/current/story/309891.html |title=Shoaib to be sent home after incident |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He was also banned for 5 matches by the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 Shoaib banned for five matches] 8 September 2007 [[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020032255/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 |date=20 October 2012 }}</ref> Akhtar later claimed that Afridi was responsible for the fight, saying \"He made some ill remarks about my family. And I could not tolerate them.\" Afridi however, denied these allegations adding that Asif would have suffered more injuries but for his intervention.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKL0834991020070908 | work=Reuters | title=Cricket-Pakistan's Akhtar accuses Afridi of instigating spat | date=8 September 2007}}</ref> Even Asif chipped in saying that Akhtar was lying and that \"Shahid Afridi had nothing to do with the fight\", saying that \"he has not apologised to me.\"<ref>[http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history Shoaib is not speaking the truth: Asif] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620003908/http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history |date=20 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2008 Akhtar was banned for five years for violating the players' code of conduct. The ban extended to all cricket for and in Pakistan.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344698.html Shoaib banned for five years]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite the ban not preventing him from playing in the [[Indian Premier League]], the IPL governing council decided not to allow Akhtar to play in the tournament until the end of the ban or unless it is lifted. [[IS Bindra]], a member of the council, was quoted as saying, \"Even though they [the PCB] have cleared him to play for IPL, we felt that international discipline needs to be respected.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344908.html Shoaib cannot play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Meanwhile, Akhtar vowed to go to great lengths to fight the ban, \"I will appeal, as is my right. If that fails I will go to court, if that fails then I will go to the Supreme Court.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344784.html 'I have been victimised' \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 3 April, Pakistan Cricket Board chairman [[Nasim Ashraf]] served a legal notice on Akhtar, calling on him to retract statements he made to a news channel, alleging the ban was punishment in return for refusing to give the chairman a share of his earnings from the Indian Premier League, Ashraf also sought damages of Rs 100 million (approximately US$1.6&nbsp;million) for \"defaming him personally\" and an additional Rs 100&nbsp;million to the Pakistan Cricket Board for \"sullying the name of the Pakistan Cricket Board and the Pakistan Cricket team.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344913.html Ashraf files --- don't copy us or else you'll burn in the nether --- notice against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A three-man appellate tribunal announced on 30 April that they had temporarily upheld Akhtar's five-year ban, deciding to revist the appeal hearing in June.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348077.html Shoaib's five-year ban upheld]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite Akhtar's later retracting his claims and also issuing an unconditional apology for \"any grief or embarrassment that may have been caused to the nation, particularly to the Pakistan Cricket Board chairman Dr Nasim Ashraf\", Ashraf's legal counsel filed a Rs 220&nbsp;million (approx US$3.37&nbsp;million) defamation suit against Akhtar in a civil court in Lahore on 2 May.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348423.html Ashraf files defamation suit against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 4 May, the Pakistan Cricket Board's appellate tribunal suspended the five-year ban for one month, until they reconvene on 4 June, allowing Akhtar to take part in the ongoing Indian Premier League.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/349950.html Shoaib cleared to play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A day later, the Pakistan Cricket Board announced that they will no longer pursue the defamation suit following a reconciliation between Akhtar and chairman Nasim Ashraf at the house of Rehman Malik, a key political official, in [[Islamabad]]. \"My honour has been vindicated and now the defamation lawsuit will not be pursued,\" Ashraf was quoted as saying.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/350007.html PCB softens stance on Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 5 May 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2008, Akhtar was sent back home from Heathrow airport by British immigration officials on visa grounds; Akhtar only had a  visit visa but not a working visa, which is required to play in county cricket. He subsequently obtained the necessary visa and returned to play with English county club Surrey.<ref>[http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 Akhtar returns home after visa hitch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213161951/http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 |date=13 February 2009 }}. ''Cricdb.com.'' Retrieved on 4 September 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2009, Akhtar was dropped from [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] Pakistan squad because of [[genital warts|genital viral warts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/405415.html |title=Shoaib pulled from World Twenty20 squad &#124; Cricket News &#124; ICC World Twenty20 2009 &#124; Cricinfo.com |publisher=Content.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Twenty20 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/5363321/Shoaib-Akhtars-genital-warts-keep-him-out-of-Pakistans-World-Twenty-20-squad.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar's genital warts keep him out of Pakistan's World Twenty 20 squad.|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=21 May 2009 |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Akhtar accused the PCB stating that there was too much \"politics\" in the Board and some of its officials did not want Pakistani team to win.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-accuses-politicised-pcb-of-wanting-team-to-lose/974418/ | title= Shoaib Akhtar accuses 'politicised' PCB of 'wanting team to lose'| date= 14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\" \n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Language !! Country\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]'' || Guest || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]''\n|-   \n| 2016 || ''[[Mazaak Mazaak Mein]]'' || Judge || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]'' \n|-\n| 2016/17|| ''[[PTV Sports#Game On Hai!|Game On Hai!]]'' || Guest || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-   \n| 2017 || ''[[Geo Khelo Pakistan]]'' || Host || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record|YouTube Rewind 2019]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.ramizansari.com/2019/12/06/shoaib-akhtar-first-pakistani-that-made-it-to-youtube-rewind/|title=Shoaib Akhtar, First Pakistani that made it to Youtube Rewind|last=Ansari|first=Ramiz|date=2019-12-06|website=Blog by Ramiz Ansari|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>''\n|Self\n|[[English language|English]]\n|''International''\n|}\n\n== International bowling records ==\n{{Main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by Shoaib Akhtar}}\n\n=== Test 10 Wicket hauls ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:100%; margin:auto;\"  width:\"100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:60px;\"| #!! style=\"width:50px;\"|Figures !! style=\"width:50px;\"|Match !! style=\"width:180px;\"|Opponent !! style=\"width:200px;\"|Venue  !! style=\"width:125px;\"|City !! style=\"width:125px;\"|Country !! width=\"50\" |Year\n|-\n| '''1''' || 10/80 || 27 || {{cr|BAN}}  || [[Arbab Niaz Stadium]] || [[Peshawar]] || [[Pakistan]] ||  2003<ref name=\"BAN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64044.html|title=Bangladesh in Pakistan Test Series \u2013 2nd Test|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''2''' || 11/78 || 29 || {{cr|NZ}}  || [[Basin Reserve]] || [[Wellington]] || [[New Zealand]] ||  2003<ref name=\"Po5Fer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64068.html |title=Pakistan in New Zealand Test Series \u2013 2nd Test |publisher= ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Career best performances===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n''as of 8 November 2010''\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!|\n! colspan=\"4\"|Batting\n! colspan=\"4\"|Bowling\n|-\n!\n!Score\n!Fixture\n!Venue\n!Season\n!Score\n!Fixture\n!Venue\n!Season\n|-\n|[[Test cricket|Tests]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|IND}}\n|[[Iqbal Stadium|Faisalabad]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\u201311\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|NZL}}\n|[[Gaddafi Stadium|Lahore]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|-\n|[[One Day International|ODI]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|43\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|ENG}}\n|[[Newlands Cricket Ground|Cape Town]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\u201316\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|NZL}}\n|[[National Stadium, Karachi|Karachi]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|-\n|[[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|ENG}}\n|[[SWALEC Stadium|Cardiff]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u201311\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|CAN}}\n|[[Maple Leaf Cricket Club|Ontario]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\n|-\n|[[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|59*\n|[[Khan Research Laboratories|KRL]] v [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA]]\n|[[Lahore City Cricket Association Ground|Lahore (CCA)]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2001\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\u201311\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|NZL}}\n|[[Gaddafi Stadium|Lahore]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|-\n|[[List A cricket|LA]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|56\n|[[Khan Research Laboratories|KRL]] v [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|Habib Bank]]\n|[[Gaddafi Stadium|Lahore]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\u201316\n|{{cr|PAK}} v {{cr|NZL}}\n|[[National Stadium, Karachi|Karachi]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|-\n|[[Twenty20 cricket|T20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|[[Islamabad Leopards]] v [[Peshawar Panthers]]\n|[[National Stadium, Karachi|Karachi]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\u201323\n|[[Rawalpindi Rams]] v [[Quetta Bears]]\n|[[Lahore City Cricket Association Ground|Lahore (CCA)]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ESPNcricinfo|id=42655}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Pakistan squads \n|bg= #01411C\n|fg= #F8B800\n|bordercolor= #00A000\n|list1=\n{{Pakistan Squad 1999 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Pakistan Squad 2003 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Pakistan Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Pakistan Squad 2009 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{Pakistan Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akhtar, Shoaib}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:ACC Asian XI One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Agriculture Development Bank of Pakistan cricketers]]\n[[Category:Chittagong Division cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 1998 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 1999 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2003 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Durham cricketers]]\n[[Category:Federal Areas cricketers]]\n[[Category:ICC World XI One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Islamabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Islamabad Leopards cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khan Research Laboratories cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricketers]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in Pakistani cricket]]\n[[Category:Pakistan International Airlines cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Rawalpindi]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi B cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi Rams cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Surrey cricketers]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricket commentators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in India]]\n[[Category:Pakistani YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Shoaib Akhtar\n| image = Shoaib Akhtar (13927458981).jpg\n| caption = \n| fullname = Shoaib Akhtar\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|8|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n| country = Pakistan\n| nickname = Rawalpindi Express, Tiger\n| height = 6ft 0in<ref>[https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/30/shoaib-akhtar Shoaib Akhtar's profile] on [[CricBuzz]]</ref>\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast]]\n| role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 1997\u20132011\n| testcap = 150\n| testdebutagainst = West Indies\n| testdebutdate = 29 November\n| testdebutyear = 1997\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| lasttestdate = 8 December\n| lasttestyear = 2007\n| odicap = 123\n| odidebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| odidebutdate = 28 March\n| odidebutyear = 1998\n| lastodiagainst = New Zealand\n| lastodidate = 8 March\n| lastodiyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = England\n| lastT20Idate = 28 December\n| lastT20Iyear = 2010\n| lastT20Iagainst = New Zealand\n| T20Icap = 9\n| odishirt = 14\n| columns = 3\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| runs1 = 544\n| matches1 = 46\n| bat avg1 = 10.07\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/0\n| top score1 = 47\n| deliveries1 = 8,143\n| wickets1 = 176\n| bowl avg1 = 25.69\n| fivefor1 = 12\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 6/11\n| catches/stumpings1 = 12/\u2013\n| matches2 = 163\n| runs2 = 394\n| bat avg2 = 8.95\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 43\n| deliveries2 = 7,764\n| wickets2 = 247\n| bowl avg2 = 24.97\n| fivefor2 = 4\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 6/16\n| catches/stumpings2 = 20/\u2013\n| matches3 = 15\n| runs3 = 21\n| bat avg3 = 7.00\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 8[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 318\n| wickets3 = 19\n| bowl avg3 = 22.73\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 3/38\n| catches/stumpings3 = 2/\u2013\n| date = 8 November\n| year = 2016\n| source = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42655.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Shoaib Akhtar''' ({{audio|Shoaib Akhtar Pronunciation.ogg|pronunciation}}; born 13 August 1975) is a Pakistani cricket commentator, YouTuber, and former cricketer who played all formats of the game over a fourteen year career. He is recognized as the [[Fast bowling|fastest bowler]] in the history of [[cricket]], delivering a world record top speed of 161.3{{nbsp}}km/h (100.23{{nbsp}}mph) in a pool match against England during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/fastest-bowl-of-a-cricket-ball/|title=Fastest delivery of a cricket ball (male)|author=|date=|work=[[Guinness World Records]]|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> Akhtar was nicknamed \"Rawalpindi Express\" and \"Tiger\" as a tribute to his hometown and fast bowling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/25921/shoaib-akhtar-the-legend-the-sensation-the-enigma/|title=Shoaib Akhtar \u2013 the legend, the sensation, the enigma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purbat.com/most-feared-fast-bowlers-cricket/|title=10 Most feared fast bowlers in Cricket history - Purbat.com|date=1 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He is also the first bowler to break the 100&nbsp;mph barrier, doing so twice in his career.\n\nAkhtar made his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in November 1997 as an opening [[fast bowling|fast bowler]] and played his first [[One Day International]] three months later. Akhtar has been involved in several controversies during his career, often accused of unsportsmanlike conduct, despite his commendations for significantly impacting games in Pakistan's favour. Akhtar was sent home during a Test match series in Australia in 2005 for alleged poor attitude. A year later, he was embroiled in a drug scandal after testing positive for the performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]]. However, the ban imposed on him was lifted on appeal. In his latest YouTube video, Shoaib Akhar took a dig at Virender Sehwag saying he is very happy that his words are given so much importance and it turns into breaking [https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/shoaib-akhtar-virender-sehwag-hair-money-taunt-youtube-1639242-2020-01-22 news].\n\nIn September 2007, he received a ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |title=PCB bans Shoaib Akhtar for an indefinite period |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614042556/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |archivedate=14 June 2015 }}</ref> On 1 April 2008, Akhtar was banned for five years for publicly criticising the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar gets 5-year ban for foul delivery &#124; It's unfair |publisher=Ibnlive.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403102400/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |archive-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2008, the [[Lahore High Court]] in Pakistan suspended the five-year ban and Akhtar was selected in the 15-man squad for the Twenty20 Quadrangular Tournament in Canada.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/372804.html\n| title = Shoaib in for Canada, not Yousuf\n}}</ref> Pakistani judge [[Rana Bhagwandas]] once stated that Akhtar is a legend of Pakistan cricket.<ref>{{cite web |title=The law is equal for everyone in Pakistan |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/feb/14inter1.htm |author=Rediffnews |quote=I have little interest in cricket. People are crazy about cricket and we feel happy when our country wins. The names of Hanif Mohammad, Imran Khan, Shoaib Akhtar all come to my mind once I think about cricket. These are legends of Pakistani cricket}}</ref> Akhtar retired from international cricket after the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAkhtar was born in a small town in Morgah near [[Rawalpindi]], Pakistan. His father, Mohammad Akhtar, \"from a hardworking economically unprivileged family of the [[Gujjar]] community\", who worked as a night watchman at a petrol station belonging to the [[Attock Refinery Limited|Attock oil refinery]], married his mother, Hameeda [[Awan (tribe)|Awan]], when she was still a teenager, and they had five children: four sons, Shoaib being the fourth after Shahid, Tahir and Obaid, followed by a daughter, Shumaila.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), p. 6</ref>\n\nHe married Rubab Khan on 11 November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haripur: Shoaib Akhtar tie the knot with Rubbabb|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/Cricket/226712-Haripur-Shoaib-Akhtar-tie-the-knot-with-Rubab|publisher=dunyanews.tv|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shoaib Akhtar secretly marries 20-year old Rubab Khan|url=http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|publisher=india.com|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629102747/http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|archivedate=29 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nA good student, Akhtar was admitted to the [[Government College Asghar Mall Rawalpindi|Asghar Mall College]], but disrupted his studies to attend trials for the [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA team]]'s Karachi division to be held in Lahore. Lacking the money for a bus ticket, he waited for the bus to start and got onto the roof.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 42-43</ref> After some struggle, starting his [[List A]] career during the 1993/1994 season and his [[First-class cricket|First-class]] career during the 1994/1995 one, he caught the eye of [[Majid Khan (cricketer, born 1946)|Majid Khan]], then the chief executive of the [[Pakistan Cricket Board|PCB]], and after a good performance for the [[Pakistan A]] team's tour of England, in 1996, he was rewarded his maiden Test cap against the West Indies, in 1997.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 58-59</ref>\n\n==International career==\nConsidering his subsequent high profile in cricket, Akhtar's test career started rather modestly. He was first picked to play on his home ground in Rawalpindi during the 2nd Test of the West Indies 1997/98 tour of Pakistan. He was subsequently included in the tour of South Africa during the winter of 1998, where he played in all three Tests. He was notably the spearhead of a depleted Pakistani bowling attack in the Peshawar Test against the visiting Australians later in 1998, where Mark Taylor scored his famous unbeaten 334 in Australia's first innings. Subsequently, after 8 tests and 16 innings, Akhtar had accumulated only 18 wickets.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/42655.html |title=Player profile: Shoaib Akhtar |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar's run of average performances started in 1999, during a pre-World Cup series against India. It was followed by high-class bowling performances in [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]] and later in the [[1999 Cricket World Cup]].\n\nIn 2002, he was selected for the Pakistan team against [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] and achieved  a small amount of success. However he performed poorly during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]] and after the tournament he was dropped from the Pakistan squad. \nHe was selected back into the Pakistan squad as they had no choice in the 2004 Test match series against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], but struggled in a losing Test series against [[India national cricket team|India]] in 2004. The series ended with a controversy when he left the field citing an injury leading to suspicions by former Pakistan captain, [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]], about his commitment to the team. As a result, his relationship with [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] and former Pakistan coach [[Bob Woolmer]] deteriorated. A medical panel was set up by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] to investigate the nature of his injury, however Pakistan officials dispelled all suspicions.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/140776.html | title = Bone scan puts Akhtar in the clear | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref>\n[[File:Shoaib Akhtar2.jpg|thumb]]\nIn 2005, Akhtar regained his reputation as a fast bowler for his side. Playing in a three Test home series against [[England cricket team|England]], he made a series of impressive bowling performances. His effective use of slower deliveries proved to be unplayable by the English batsmen. Akhtar emerged as the highest wicket taker of the series with seventeen wickets. His comeback was also remarkable as prior to his return, he had been criticised from all corners; such as by the Worcestershire chairman John Elliot for his celebrity attitude and lack of commitment to the team. His performance was also acknowledged by the English captain [[Michael Vaughan]], who remarked \"I thought he (Shoaib) was a big difference between the two teams\".<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/228332.html | title = Vaughan \u2013 Batsmen to blame | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref> He is also known as one of only three bowlers to have ever broken the 100&nbsp;mph barrier in cricket history, with a delivery of 100.2&nbsp;mph, during a one-day international against England in World cup 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/149874.html|title=Blink and you'll miss it|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Struggle for form and consistent injuries (2007\u20132009)===\nOn 29 October 2007, Akhtar made his return to cricket, from his 13 match ban and performed well, taking 4 wickets for 43 runs against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] in the fifth and deciding One Day International series in Lahore in Pakistan. Subsequently, he was included in the 16-man Pakistan squad for the [[Pakistani cricket team in India in 2007\u201308|2007 tour of India]].\n\n===Rehabilitation and final years (2010\u20132011)===\nAkhtar made a return to international cricket albeit in the shorter format of the game. In May 2010, PCB named him in a list of 35 probables for the [[2010 Asia Cup|Asia Cup]]. On 15 June 2010, Akhtar made his return, taking 3 wickets for 28 runs in the first match of the Asia Cup against Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Siddarth|title=Shoaib Akhtar makes a respectable return|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/asia2010/content/story/463287.html|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref> He narrowly missed out a spot in the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]] in place of the injured Umar Gul.\n\nIn July 2010, he was selected for the Twenty20 [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in England in 2010|series against Australia]] but the selectors decided not to play him in the Test squad so that he would not get injured. He was subsequently selected for the ODI and Twenty20 series against [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2010|England in September 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Geo TV|title=Shoaib Akhtar selected for ODI and Twenty20 series against England in September 2010|url=http://geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|publisher=Jang News|accessdate=26 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830183713/http://www.geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|archivedate=30 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar returned to the national side representing the country against England in the Twenty20 International. He bowled an impressive spell and returned with figures of 2 wickets for 23 runs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan bowler Shoaib Akhtar breathes new life into cricket's fast show|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/7985127/Pakistan-bowler-Shoaib-Akhtar-breathes-new-life-into-crickets-fast-show.html|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=6 November 2010|location=London|first=Steve|last=James|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> He continued to bowl well in the ODI series in the absence of regular fast-bowlers, [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] and [[Mohammad Amir]], who were suspended by the International Cricket Council amid allegations of [[Spot-fixing]]. Despite his relatively good bowling form, Pakistani coach [[Waqar Younis]] insisted that the bowling attack must not become reliant on Akhtar, as he is 35 years of age and fitness troubles continue to affect him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shoaib Akhtar can't do miracle at this age: Waqar |url=http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |publisher=Geo.tv |accessdate=6 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024225147/http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |archivedate=24 October 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> Akhtar was selected for the tour of New Zealand and started his campaign off well with 3 wickets on Boxing Day in the first of two Twenty20 Internationals against New Zealand.\n\nAkhtar was selected in Pakistan's 15-man squad to play in the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]] hosted by Bangladesh, India, and Sri Lanka in February to March. During the tournament, he announced that he would retire from international cricket at the end of the World Cup. He was dropped from the squad after group matches and was not included in the quarter final either.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/506599.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar to retire after World Cup |first=Osman |last=Samiuddin |publisher=Cricinfo |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> In September, Akhtar released his autobiography, ''[[Controversially Yours]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |title=Shoaib Akhtar's ''Controversially Yours'' released |publisher=GEO Sports |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=24 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926232325/http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\n===England county cricket===\nAkhtar has played for three English [[county cricket]] clubs: [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in 2001, [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] in 2003 and 2004 and [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in 2005. He did achieve his moments of success, such as taking 5 wickets for 35 runs for Durham against Somerset in the [[National League (cricket)|National League]] in 2003 and claiming 6 wickets for 16 runs in the same competition for Worcestershire against [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] two years later, but he suffered from fitness problems, as well as a perception that he was less than interested in his task. This was particularly the case at Worcestershire: chairman John Elliott said \"Players like that are no good to our club. In fact, Akhtar has been no good for any club he's been at. He's a superstar and just does what he wants.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/current/story/295629.html | title=Dodgy overseas signings | author=Steve Pittard and John Stern | date=24 May 2007 | accessdate=24 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\n===Indian Premier League===\nAkhtar made a successful return to cricket in his first game in the [[Indian Premier League]], playing for the [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] against the [[Delhi Daredevils]]. Defending a low score of 133 runs, Akhtar took four top order wickets which ultimately led to the Daredevils being restricted to 110 runs. He ended with figures of 4 wickets for 11 runs from three overs, a performance which earned him the player of the match award.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/engine/match/336017.html Indian Premier League \u2013 35th match, Kolkata Knight Riders v Delhi Daredevils]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref><ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350889.html Shoaib leads Delhi drubbing]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref> Akhtar denied that he had any point to prove with his performance, stating, \"I just wanted to win the game.\" Knight Riders' captain [[Sourav Ganguly]] also acknowledged Akhtar's performance, \"He came to the country with lots [of things] happening behind him...But he showed a lot of character.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350924.html I have no point to prove \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref>\n\nHe has also played for [[Cyclones of Chittagong]] in Bangladesh's [[Bangladesh NCL (National Cricket League) Twenty20|NCL T20 Bangladesh]].\n\n==Cricket controversies and injuries==\nAkhtar's career has been plagued with injuries, controversies and accusations of poor attitude. After a poor performance in the 2003 Cricket World Cup, he got involved in a verbal conflict with former Pakistan captain and fast bowler [[Waqar Younis]]. Later on Akhtar was sacked along with other players, including Younis. In a triangular series in 2003 held in Sri Lanka, he was caught [[ball tampering]] making him the second player in cricket to be banned on ball tampering charges. The same year he was banned for one Test match and two One Day International matches for abusing South African spin bowler [[Paul Adams (cricketer)|Paul Adams]], during a match against South Africa. In the 2004 home series with India, he struggled with wrist and back injuries, which raised questions about his commitment to the team.\n\nHe was sent back from the 2005 Australia tour with a hamstring injury amid rumours of indiscipline, lack of commitment and attitudinal complaints. He was subsequently fined by the Pakistan Cricket Board for avoiding a late night curfew.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm ABC Sport \u2013 Cricket \u2013 Pakistan's Akhtar fined for Australian disco jaunt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020024458/http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm |date=20 October 2007 }}</ref> The rest of his cricketing career was riddled with ankle and knee injuries which forced him to undergo a surgery in February 2006, until finally he was banned for two years for allegedly using performance-enhancing drugs.\n\nIn November 2006, an officer assigned to the Pakistan team in India, Anil Kaul, alleged that Akhtar had slapped former coach Bob Woolmer following a fight over the music to be played in the team bus on the eve of ICC Champions Trophy. Both Akhtar and Woolmer have strongly denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707151418/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |archivedate=7 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Drug scandal===\nOn 16 October 2006 Akhtar was suspended by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]], along with [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammed Asif]] after they tested positive for a performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/iccct2006/content/current/story/263238.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Asif and Akhtar to return home |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> They were consequently pulled out from the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,20589658-23212,00.html |title=Shoaib returns positive test |date=16 October 2006 |author=Staff writers and wires |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|FOX SPORTS Australia]]}}</ref> Former Pakistan Cricket Board chairman later stated that he had always suspected Akhtar of substance abuse due to his consistent \"reservations\" to drug tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714064906/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |archivedate=14 July 2012 }}</ref> Former Pakistan captain [[Inzamam ul-Haq]] had also previously complained about Akhtar's drug abuse but was not reported to the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://paktribune.com/news/index.shtml?158859 |title=Pakistan News Service \u2013 PakTribune |publisher=Paktribune.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Akhtar immediately declared his innocence and he declined knowingly taking any performance-enhancing drugs. In a statement issued to the press, he claimed that he could never cheat teammates or opponents.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6054724.stm | work=BBC News | title=Shocked Shoaib protests innocence | date=16 October 2006 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> During a hearing with the Pakistan Cricket Board Anti-Doping Committee, he along with Asif maintained taking non-steroidal dietary supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-ind.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/266665.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Sad but we had to make an example of Shoaib \u2013 Alam |publisher=Content-ind.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He, however, failed to convince the committee of his innocence. In its report submitted to the Pakistan Cricket Board, the Anti-Doping Committee recommended a two-year ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcboard.com.pk/Pakistan/Articles/5/5298.html |title=Pakistan Cricket Board \u2013 official website |publisher=Pcboard.com.pk |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 November 2006 the Pakistan Cricket Board handed down a two-year suspension to Akhtar and a one-year suspension to Asif, banning them from professional cricket during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/266573.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif banned for drugs use |publisher=Uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Shoaib had subsequently been added to [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] list of doping offenders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191359/http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, on 5 December 2006 represented by his lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], Akhtar was cleared on appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/australia/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2006 Akhtar and Asif were acquitted by the tribunal appointed to review their appeals. After a clear hearing from Akhtar's lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], the three-man committee, voted two to one in favour of the acquittal. Justice Fakhruddin Ebrahim, committee head, and Haseeb Ahsan, former Test cricketer, were in favour of the acquittal. The third member, Danish Zaheer, differed. \"Exceptional circumstances\" were cited including discrepancies between the instantaneous offence charges of doping that were laid and the quick delivery of a very harsh verdict. The complete drug testing procedure was concluded to have been technically flawed as it did not follow standard procedures. Other established facts by the committee included that the duo were not aware of the banned drug to be present in their supplements because the Pakistan Cricket Board itself had not informed them of the dangers of contaminated supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-pak.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-pak.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/271347.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Dope on the doping scandal |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar and Asif, however, did not play in the subsequent Test match series against the West Indies because the Pakistan Cricket Board had recommended that they play domestic games first to recover form and fitness.{{cn|date=November 2017}} On 1 March 2007 Akhtar and Asif were ruled out of the Pakistani squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] by team officials, minutes before the squad was to depart for the [[West Indies]]. The team management along with the Pakistan Cricket Board said their injuries were too severe to risk taking them to the Caribbean. Since neither of the two had been declared fit they did not undergo official doping tests.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wc2007/content/current/story/281976.html Shoaib and Asif out of the World Cup]:</ref>\n\n[[World Anti-Doping Agency]] ( WADA) challenged Pakistan's decision to lift bans on fast bowlers Akhtar and Asif by taking the case to the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6183997.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Cricket &#124; International Teams &#124; Pakistan &#124; Pakistan to face doping challenge |publisher=BBC News |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The ICC supported the WADA appeal adding that it was committed to a dope free game. On 2 July 2007, the Court of Arbitration for Sport dropped the case, ruling it had no jurisdiction to challenge the decision made by PCB.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/300348.html Court has no jurisdiction in doping case]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6260498.stm Court cannot rule on Pakistan duo]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref>\n\n===Other controversies===\nIn August 2007, Akhtar was reported to have used foul language against Pakistan Cricket Board protesting the imposing of fine of Rs. 300,000 for indiscipline during the national camp in Karachi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120713153808/http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-13 |title=Shoaib uses foul language to protest PCB decision }}</ref> In the week before the inaugural [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World Twenty20]], held in South Africa, Akhtar was rumoured to have hit Pakistani teammate Mohammad Asif with a bat after an argument in the dressing room. It started after Akhtar was ridiculed by Asif and [[Shahid Afridi]] for comparing himself with [[Imran Khan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|title=Latest News, Breaking News Live, Current Headlines, India News Online \u2013 The Indian Express|website=www.indianexpress.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430055753/http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|archivedate=30 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/309867.html\n| title = Asif injured in dressing room spat by Akhtar\n}}</ref> After the initial inquiry, Akhtar was found to be at fault and was subsequently recalled from the Twenty20 World Cup squad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKSP16843120070907|title=Pakistan send Akhtar home after bustup|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref> and was sent home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/current/story/309891.html |title=Shoaib to be sent home after incident |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He was also banned for 5 matches by the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 Shoaib banned for five matches] 8 September 2007 [[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020032255/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 |date=20 October 2012 }}</ref> Akhtar later claimed that Afridi was responsible for the fight, saying \"He made some ill remarks about my family. And I could not tolerate them.\" Afridi however, denied these allegations adding that Asif would have suffered more injuries but for his intervention.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKL0834991020070908 | work=Reuters | title=Cricket-Pakistan's Akhtar accuses Afridi of instigating spat | date=8 September 2007}}</ref> Even Asif chipped in saying that Akhtar was lying and that \"Shahid Afridi had nothing to do with the fight\", saying that \"he has not apologised to me.\"<ref>[http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history Shoaib is not speaking the truth: Asif] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620003908/http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history |date=20 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2008 Akhtar was banned for five years for violating the players' code of conduct. The ban extended to all cricket for and in Pakistan.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344698.html Shoaib banned for five years]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite the ban not preventing him from playing in the [[Indian Premier League]], the IPL governing council decided not to allow Akhtar to play in the tournament until the end of the ban or unless it is lifted. [[IS Bindra]], a member of the council, was quoted as saying, \"Even though they [the PCB] have cleared him to play for IPL, we felt that international discipline needs to be respected.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344908.html Shoaib cannot play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Meanwhile, Akhtar vowed to go to great lengths to fight the ban, \"I will appeal, as is my right. If that fails I will go to court, if that fails then I will go to the Supreme Court.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344784.html 'I have been victimised' \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 3 April, Pakistan Cricket Board chairman [[Nasim Ashraf]] served a legal notice on Akhtar, calling on him to retract statements he made to a news channel, alleging the ban was punishment in return for refusing to give the chairman a share of his earnings from the Indian Premier League, Ashraf also sought damages of Rs 100 million (approximately US$1.6&nbsp;million) for \"defaming him personally\" and an additional Rs 100&nbsp;million to the Pakistan Cricket Board for \"sullying the name of the Pakistan Cricket Board and the Pakistan Cricket team.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344913.html Ashraf files --- don't copy us or else you'll burn in the nether --- notice against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A three-man appellate tribunal announced on 30 April that they had temporarily upheld Akhtar's five-year ban, deciding to revist the appeal hearing in June.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348077.html Shoaib's five-year ban upheld]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite Akhtar's later retracting his claims and also issuing an unconditional apology for \"any grief or embarrassment that may have been caused to the nation, particularly to the Pakistan Cricket Board chairman Dr Nasim Ashraf\", Ashraf's legal counsel filed a Rs 220&nbsp;million (approx US$3.37&nbsp;million) defamation suit against Akhtar in a civil court in Lahore on 2 May.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348423.html Ashraf files defamation suit against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 4 May, the Pakistan Cricket Board's appellate tribunal suspended the five-year ban for one month, until they reconvene on 4 June, allowing Akhtar to take part in the ongoing Indian Premier League.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/349950.html Shoaib cleared to play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A day later, the Pakistan Cricket Board announced that they will no longer pursue the defamation suit following a reconciliation between Akhtar and chairman Nasim Ashraf at the house of Rehman Malik, a key political official, in [[Islamabad]]. \"My honour has been vindicated and now the defamation lawsuit will not be pursued,\" Ashraf was quoted as saying.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/350007.html PCB softens stance on Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 5 May 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2008, Akhtar was sent back home from Heathrow airport by British immigration officials on visa grounds; Akhtar only had a  visit visa but not a working visa, which is required to play in county cricket. He subsequently obtained the necessary visa and returned to play with English county club Surrey.<ref>[http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 Akhtar returns home after visa hitch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213161951/http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 |date=13 February 2009 }}. ''Cricdb.com.'' Retrieved on 4 September 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2009, Akhtar was dropped from [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] Pakistan squad because of [[genital warts|genital viral warts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/405415.html |title=Shoaib pulled from World Twenty20 squad &#124; Cricket News &#124; ICC World Twenty20 2009 &#124; Cricinfo.com |publisher=Content.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Twenty20 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/5363321/Shoaib-Akhtars-genital-warts-keep-him-out-of-Pakistans-World-Twenty-20-squad.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar's genital warts keep him out of Pakistan's World Twenty 20 squad.|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=21 May 2009 |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Akhtar accused the PCB stating that there was too much \"politics\" in the Board and some of its officials did not want Pakistani team to win.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-accuses-politicised-pcb-of-wanting-team-to-lose/974418/ | title= Shoaib Akhtar accuses 'politicised' PCB of 'wanting team to lose'| date= 14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\" \n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Language !! Country\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]'' || Guest || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]''\n|-   \n| 2016 || ''[[Mazaak Mazaak Mein]]'' || Judge || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]'' \n|-\n| 2016/17|| ''[[PTV Sports#Game On Hai!|Game On Hai!]]'' || Guest || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-   \n| 2017 || ''[[Geo Khelo Pakistan]]'' || Host || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record|YouTube Rewind 2019]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.ramizansari.com/2019/12/06/shoaib-akhtar-first-pakistani-that-made-it-to-youtube-rewind/|title=Shoaib Akhtar, First Pakistani that made it to Youtube Rewind|last=Ansari|first=Ramiz|date=2019-12-06|website=Blog by Ramiz Ansari|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>''\n|Self\n|[[English language|English]]\n|''International''\n|}\n\n== International bowling records ==\n{{Main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by Shoaib Akhtar}}\n\n=== Test 10 Wicket hauls ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" 