mes]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 1999 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2003 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Durham cricketers]]\n[[Category:Federal Areas cricketers]]\n[[Category:ICC World XI One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Islamabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Islamabad Leopards cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khan Research Laboratories cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricketers]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in Pakistani cricket]]\n[[Category:Pakistan International Airlines cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Rawalpindi]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi B cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi Rams cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Surrey cricketers]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricket commentators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in India]]\n[[Category:Pakistani YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoaib_Akhtar"}
{"title_page": "Cut the Crap", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Cut the Crap\n| type       = [[Studio album]]\n| artist     = [[The Clash]]\n| cover      = Cut the Crap.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|1985|11|4}}\n| recorded   = January\u2013March 1985\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Weryton, [[Unterf\u00f6hring]], Germany<ref name=\"p211\">Popoff (2018), p. 211</ref>\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]<ref name=\"allmusic\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. \"[https://www.allmusic.com/album/cut-the-crap-mw0000691234 Cut the Crap: The Clash]\". [[AllMusic]]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190413060720/https://www.allmusic.com/album/cut-the-crap-mw0000691234 Archived] from the original on 13 April 2019. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref>\n| length     = {{unbulleted list\n|{{duration|m=38|s=21}}\n|{{duration|m=41|s=29}} (with \"Do It Now\")\n}}\n| label      = [[CBS Records|CBS ]](UK)\n| producer   = Jose Unidos ({{a.k.a.}} [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]])<ref name=\"p211\" />\n| prev_title = [[Combat Rock]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title =\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Cut the Crap\n | type        = [[Studio album]]\n | single1     = [[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\n | single1date = September 1985\n | single2     = Are You Red..Y\n | single2date = 1985\n}}\n}}\n'''''Cut the Crap''''' ho ho ho Christmas is sure coming is the sixth and final [[studio album]] by the English [[Punk rock|punk]] band [[the Clash]], released on 4&nbsp;November 1985 by [[CBS Records]]. It was recorded in early 1985 at Weryton Studios, [[Munich]], following a turbulent period: co-founder, lead guitarist and co-principal songwriter [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] and drummer [[Topper Headon]] had been dismissed by lead vocalist [[Joe Strummer]] and bassist [[Paul Simonon]]. Jones and Headon were replaced  by three unknowns: guitarists [[Vince White]] and [[Nick Sheppard]] and drummer [[Pete Howard]]. During the tense recording sessions, and Clash manager [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]] and Strummer fought with each other for control over the band's songwriting and musical direction.\n\nStrummer and Rhodes co-wrote most of the songs. During production, Rhodes took charge of the [[arrangement]]s, track sequencing and the final [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]]. His production choices, which rely heavily on Strummer's preference for [[synthesizers|synthetic]] drum sounds and Rhodes' own inclusion of [[Sampler (musical instrument)|sampling]], were widely derided. One writer described the album\u2019s sound as brash and seemingly \"designed to sound hip and modern\u2014'[[1980s in music|80s style!]]\".<ref name=\"vul\">Wyman, Bill. \"[https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/all-139-the-clash-songs-ranked-from-worst-to-best.html 139 the Clash Songs, Ranked from Worst to Best]\". ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'', 11 October 2017. [https://web.archive.org/web/20171011193355/https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/all-139-the-clash-songs-ranked-from-worst-to-best.html Archived] from the original on 11 October 2017. Retrieved 10 February 2019</ref> Rhodes chose the album title, taken from a line in the 1981 post-apocalyptic film ''[[Mad Max 2]]''. On release, ''Cut the Crap'' was maligned in the UK music press as \"one of the most disastrous [albums] ever released by a major artist\".<ref>Ziegler, Jay. \"[https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/03/dusting-em-off-the-clash-cut-the-crap/ Dusting 'Em Off: The Clash \u2013 ''Cut the Crap'']\". ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', 8 March 2009. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180826064025/https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/03/dusting-em-off-the-clash-cut-the-crap/ Archived] from the original on 26 August 2018. Retrieved 7 January 2018</ref><ref name=\"Louder\">Knowles, Chris. \"[https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-clash-i-suppose-the-end-really-came-when-mick-left-the-band The Final Days of the Clash]\". ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder Sound]]'', 18 April 2005. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190413135749/https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-clash-i-suppose-the-end-really-came-when-mick-left-the-band Archived] from the original on 13 April 2019. Retrieved 6 January 2019</ref> Strummer disowned the album and dissolved the Clash within weeks of its release.\n\nThe recording process and tension between Rhodes and Strummer left other band members disillusioned. White's and Sheppard's contributions are almost entirely absent in the final mix, and Howard was replaced by an electronic drum machine. Epic Records hoped the album would advance the Clash's success in the United States, and planned an expensive video for lead single \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\"; by the album's release, the band members were so discouraged that they did not turn up for the first day's shoot. Strummer moved to Spain, in part due to family issues, but also to escape the backlash.\n\nThe album was poorly received upon release, and is still generally regarded as the band's worst album; Strummer performed only one song from the album live during his solo career, and the album has been excluded altogether from most of the Clash\u2019s compilations and box sets. Some retrospective assessments have been more sympathetic; a number of critics and writers have praised Strummer's songwriting and vocal performance, and Rhode's production, especially on the tracks \"This Is England\", \"Dirty Punk\" and \"Three Card Trick\".\n\n==Background==\n[[The Clash]]'s internal difficulties during 1983 led to two of its core members being fired: guitarist [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] was seen as adopting rock star posturing that vocalist [[Joe Strummer]] considered anathema to what the band stood for, and drummer [[Topper Headon]] had developed a [[heroin]] addiction which left him unreliable.<ref name=\"e103\">Egan (2014), p. 103</ref> After the band undertook rehearsals in London during June 1983,<ref>Gilbert (2014), pp. 336\u2013337</ref> interpersonal tensions reemerged. The two principal songwriters no longer trusted each other, due to Jones's frequent absence from rehearsals and use of synthesizers.<ref name=\"g3389\">Gilbert (2014), pp. 338\u2013339</ref> Both Jones and bassist [[Paul Simonon]] refused to sign a contract negotiated by newly reinstated manager [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]],<ref name=\"g3389\" /> who had earlier been fired due to personal differences with Jones.<ref name=\"A6\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), chapter 6</ref>\n\n[[File:Mickjones.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.7|Founding Clash guitarist [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] in 1987]]\nThe relationship between Strummer and Jones had broken down by this point.<ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 339</ref> Not long into rehearsals, Strummer and Simonon had fired Jones.<ref>Gilbert (2014), pp. 340\u2013341</ref>{{refn|Simonon has said that Rhodes had not been aware of, nor later approved of, Jones's firing.<ref>Salewicz (2007), pp. 373\u2013375</ref>|group=n}} A week before the official announcement of the dismissal, Strummer, Simonon and Rhodes began to look for replacements and  met [[Pete Howard]].<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 344</ref> The band placed anonymous advertisements for replacement guitarists in ''[[Melody Maker]]''. After auditioning over 100 candidates,<ref name=\"vice\">Haynes, Gavin. \"[https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdve37/were-the-clash-bullshit Were the Clash Bullshit?]\". ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', 29 October 2010. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190511202306/https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdve37/were-the-clash-bullshit Archived] from the original on 11 May 2019. Retrieved 11 May 2019</ref> they eventually hired unknown musicians [[Nick Sheppard]] and [[Vince White|Greg White]]. White took the pseudonym Vince after Simonon complained that he would prefer to quit than play in a band with someone named Greg.<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 345</ref> Both were given a weekly wage of \u00a3100<ref name=\"vice\" /> rather than [[recording contract]]s.<ref name=\"A10\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), chapter 10</ref>\n\nStrummer had been the band's principal lyricist, while Jones had written their music. After Jones was fired, the band assumed that anyone could write a punk song. This proved to be a mistake<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 359</ref> and, unknown to members of the Clash, Rhodes had already conceived his own solution to Jones's departure\u2014he would take control of the music.<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 360</ref><ref name=\"df\">[[David Fricke|Fricke, David]]. \"[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/cut-the-crap-103110/ ''Cut the Crap'']. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 16 January 1986. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100409042234/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/theclash/albums/album/132884/review/5943097/cut_the_crap Archived] from the original on 9 April 2010. Retrieved 15 June 2019</ref>\n\nStrummer intended the second Clash line-up to encapsulate a back-to-basics approach to punk. The new musicians largely avoided the [[reggae]]-influenced style of their two previous albums, ''[[Sandinista!]]'' (1980) and ''[[Combat Rock]]'' (1982).<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 363</ref> Strummer began to refer to the line-up as \"the Clash, Round Two\", a phrase adopted by the press as \"the Clash Mark&nbsp;II\".<ref>Jucha (2016), p. 317</ref> They booked a short tour of the US West Coast, debuting new songs, which prompted Jones to boast to concert promoter [[Bill Graham (promoter)|Bill Graham]] that he was planning his own tour with Headon as \"the Real Clash\".<ref name=\"p216\">Popoff (2018), p. 216</ref> Jones's lawyers had frozen the band's earnings from both the US Festival and sales of ''Combat Rock''. In response, Strummer wrote the song \"We Are the Clash\", which, along with \"Three Card Trick\", \"Sex Mad Roar\" and \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\", was debuted during live appearances in January 1984.<ref>Salewicz (2007), pp. 364\u2013365</ref> In all, the Clash Mark&nbsp;II had written around 20 new songs before entering the studio to record what became the band's final album.<ref>Gibson, Phil. \"[https://louderthanwar.com/the-clash-cut-the-crap-cutting-edge-or-just-crap/ The Clash 'Cut the Crap' \u2013 Cutting edge or just crap?]\". ''[[Louder Than War (website)|Louder Than War]]'', 13 March 2012. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190511213845/https://louderthanwar.com/the-clash-cut-the-crap-cutting-edge-or-just-crap/ Archived] from the original on 11 May 2019. Retrieved 11 May 2019</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n[[File:JoeStrummer1980 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Joe Strummer]] performing at the [[Tower Theater (Upper Darby Township, Pennsylvania)|Tower Theater]], March 6, 1980]]\nThe album was recorded between January and February 1985, on a [[Multitrack recording|24-track]] mixing desk in Weryton Studios, [[Unterf\u00f6hring]], outside [[Munich]], Germany,<ref name=\"j325\">Jucha (2016), p. 325</ref><ref name=\"k252\">Knowles (2003), p. 252</ref> with some parts recorded in London. Epic Records chose the German studio because the band's finances were dependent on a number of ongoing legal cases,<ref>Knowles (2003), p. 249</ref> including moves by Jones to prevent them recording under the name \"the Clash\".<ref name=\"A9\">Anderson, Heibutzki (2018), chapter 9</ref> Rhodes hired [[Audio engineer|engineer]] Micheal Fayne on the basis of affordability, and his prior experience with programmed [[drum machine]]s,<ref name=\"j325\" /> which Strummer wanted to use on the album because, according to Rhodes, \"Joe wanted to compete with Mick's drum machine thing\".<ref name=\"grdrum\" /> Rhodes also employed engineers Ulrich A. Rudolf, Simon Sullivan and Kevin Whyte, each of whom are credited on the sleeve.<ref name=\"p211\" />\n\nStrummer and Rhodes disagreed on the direction of the recordings almost from the outset. Rhodes, credited on the sleeve under the pseudonym \"Jose Unidos\",<ref name=\"NME\" /> had no previous experience with either songwriting or record production. While Strummer had been pleased with his demo versions, he fought against his manager over the album's production.<ref name=\"NME\" /> Rhodes's believed he had discovered a new genre, seeking to mix [[electro (music)|electro]], [[hip hop]] and [[cut-up technique]].<ref name=\"GaCTC\" /> He replaced live musicians with synthetic sounds and layered the tracks with audio from TV programs.<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nHoward was given vague instructions, such as to play like he was throwing the drum kit down some stairs.<ref name=\"grdrum\">Garcia (2012), Drum Machine, 2276</ref> White recalled working with Strummer for extended period on guitar parts, which Rhodes would later refuse to include; he remembered that Strummer had at times stood up to the producer, but \"not nearly enough\". In the same way, White often felt demoralised by Rhodes, who berated the guitarist's playing from a technical standpoint. White believed Rhodes used such tactics to wear him down, and he was eventually dismissed from the studio by his manager.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n[[File:PaulSimonon1980.jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Paul Simonon]] at the Tower Theater in 1980. The bassist does not appear on any of the album's final recordings.]]\nFayne described Rhodes's treatment of Howard as \"damaging\". Rhodes would begin recording sessions by asking the drummer to play what he wanted, but would inevitably respond to Howard's parts by saying \"no, not that\", or \"no, not that either\".<ref name=\"grdrum\" /> In one incident, Rhodes appeared in the recording room and began to \"smash the drum kit up\", at which point Howard stood up and left.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Fayne shared White's view that these incidents were a ploy by Rhodes to force the new recruits out of the band. He said, \"Bernie didn't want any connection with the past{{nbsp}}... He wanted to take it forward, to control it, to mastermind the whole thing, and what they were doing was a bit too reminiscent of what it was\".<ref name=\"A9\" /> Disillusioned and lacking reinforcement or direction from Strummer, Howard seriously considered leaving the band at several points.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nMost of the Clash and production team liked the [[Football chant|football-style chants]] used in some of the choruses. They were in part inspired by the communal [[sing-along]]s the Clash performed during their busking tour the previous year, and thus evoked memories of a less tense period in their career. The massed vocals were provided by several dozen of their friends and families, and several of the inner team remembered those sessions as the only enjoyable period during the album's recording.<ref name=\"A9\" /> The only other aspect that the musicians agreed on was the quality and commercial potential of \"This is England\", a song into which Rhodes allowed the musicians significant creative input.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\nRhodes suddenly ended the recordings and took the [[Audio mastering|master tapes]] from the studio, after which he added further synthesizer parts.<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref name=\"A9\" /> Although Jones's use of synthesizers and samplers was one of the main reasons behind his dismissal, those instruments brought him critical and public acclaim with his next band [[Big Audio Dynamite]].<ref name=\"br\" /> When asked at the time for his opinion on [[This Is Big Audio Dynamite|the debut B.A.D. album]], Strummer described it as one of the \"worst pieces of shit I have ever heard.\"<ref name=\"A9\" /> In 1986, Strummer said that he had liked a few of the tunes but \"really I hated it{{nbsp}}... I didn't hear [the album as a whole] until it was in the shops.\"<ref name=\"NME\" /> Strummer ultimately lost control of ''Cut the Crap'' to Rhodes,<ref name=\"NME\" /> and became so disillusioned that at one point he asked Jones to rejoin the band, but was refused.<ref name=\"Louder\" />\n\nSimonon does not appear on any of the final recordings; the bass lines were performed by [[Norman Watt-Roy]], former member of [[the Blockheads]], who was not credited on the sleeve.<ref name=\"j139\">Jucha (2016), p. 139</ref> Howard's exclusion from the album has been lamented by many critics.<ref name=\"j331\">Jucha (2016), p. 331</ref><ref name=\"br\">Bray, Ryan. \"[https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/11/this-is-not-radio-clash-cut-the-crap-was-a-snapshot-of-a-legendary-bands-low-point/ This Is (Not) Radio Clash: ''Cut the Crap'' Was a Snapshot of a Legendary Band's Low Point]\". ''Consequence of Sound'', 7 November 2015. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190331042940/https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/11/this-is-not-radio-clash-cut-the-crap-was-a-snapshot-of-a-legendary-bands-low-point/ Archived] from the original on 31 March 2019. Retrieved 7 January 2018</ref> Knowles described him as an \"astonishingly powerful and prodigious\" drummer, and said that replacing him with electronic percussion was \"like replacing a [[Maserati]] with a [[Matchbox (brand)|Matchbox]]\".<ref name=\"Louder\" /> Regretting the decision, Strummer later vowed to never use a drum machine again.<ref name=\"mal\">Peachey, Mal. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/joe-strummer-clashback Joe Strummer: Clashback]\". ''International Musician and Recording World'', June 1988 \u2013 via [[Rock's Backpages]] {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe consensus among critics is that the album's production choices distract from otherwise strong songwriting by Strummer & Rhodes. Strummer's vocals are placed low in the mix, sometimes buried underneath electronic drums, synthetic keyboards and studio effects. The sound has often been described as muddy and cluttered due to multi-layered guitar tracks and backing vocals.<ref name=\"j319\">Jucha (2016), p. 319</ref> Many of the guitar overdubs have been considered unnecessary, given that Sheppard and White were both using [[Gibson Les Paul]]s and as such their sounds were tonally similar, and there was not significant variation in either their [[chord progression]]s or [[Ostinato|riffs]].<ref name=\"j319\" /> Rhodes's may have felt the need to fill each channel on the 24-track [[Mixing console|mixing desk]].<ref name=\"k252\" /><ref name=\"j329\">Jucha (2016), p. 329</ref> Author Gary Jucha summed up the album as having been produced by a manager whose musical ambitions were overstretched by a lack of experience.<ref name=\"j329\"/>\n\nThe overlaid vocals in several choruses give songs the feel of [[football chant]]s. These vocals have been harshly criticised, both because the effect seemed like [[Low culture|low-brow]] rabble-rousing<ref name=\"snow\">[[Mat Snow|Snow, Mat]]. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/clash-ithe-clash-give-em-enough-rope-london-calling-sandinista-combat-rock-cut-the-crapi Clash: ''The Clash''; ''Give 'Em Enough Rope''; ''London Calling''; ''Sandinista!''; ''Combat Rock''; ''Cut the Crap'']\". ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', June 1989 \u2013 via Rock's Backpages {{subscription required}}</ref> and from unfavourable comparisons with Jones's backing vocals on the band's earlier recordings.<ref>Jucha (2016), pp. 325\u2013326</ref> The drums are largely untreated with [[Effects unit|sound effects]] which left them sounding dull.{{refn|Howard described the final drum sound as coming across as like somebody \"hitting you over the head with a bag of [[ball bearing]]s.\"<ref name=\"GaCTC\" />|group=n}} Knowles suggested that adding [[reverb]] would have helped to create a more organic \"roomy\" sound, so the songs wouldn't feel \"so canned and phony\".<ref name=\"k252\" /> Against this, the live instrumentation is tight and cohesive. Each of the new recruits was a skilled musician,<ref name=\"k120\">Knowles (2003), p. 120</ref> and they had just come off a tour during which Rhodes had instructed them not to vary song structures or guitar leads between performances.<ref name=\"j319\" />\n\n===Side one===\n\"Dictator\", one of the earliest songs the new line-up played during their European tour, has been described as \"the poorest possible choice for the opening track\".<ref name=\"j330\">Jucha (2016), p. 330</ref> Music critic Lennox Samuels wrote in 1985 that the song is \"a messy mix of horns and a [[Pink Floyd]]-like voice-over\".<ref name=\"SL\">Samuels, Lennox. \"The Clash's New Album Proves Musically Apt, Politically Irrelevant\". ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'', 24 November 1985</ref> The album cut omits the live version's [[Bridge (music)|bridge]], changes the drum pattern, and replaces most of the guitar parts with [[Atonality|atonal]] synth lines.<ref name=\"k122\">Knowles (2003), p. 122</ref> The music journalist [[Martin Popoff]] described the lyrics' depiction of a Central American [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]] as \"surprisingly flat and dead\".<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 214</ref> The critic Mark Andersen described it as \"one of the less successful of the new tunes\".<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n{{Listen\n|filename = The Clash Dirty Punk.ogg\n|title = \"Dirty Punk\"\n|description = With its simple three-chord structure, \"Dirty Punk\" is the song that best represents Strummer and Rhodes's attempt to return the band to its punk rock origins.<ref name=\"vul\" />}}\nThe guitar-based \"Dirty Punk\" is built from a basic three-chord structure reminiscent of the band's [[The Clash (album)|self-titled debut album]]. White believed it should have been the lead single and could have been a hit.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Although generally well received,<ref name=\"br\" /> critics dismissed its synthetic drum sound as at odds with its back-to-basics sound.<ref name=\"p215\">Popoff (2018), p. 215</ref> The track was written just after the 1984 tour, when Strummer was attending to his terminally ill mother, so it is assumed that most of the lyrics were composed by Rhodes.<ref name=\"k122\" /> They are written from the point of view of a young punk who feels overshadowed by an older brother, but the story is told in such simple terms that it has been characterised as having \"Neanderthal lyrics that read as if a parody of a punk rock song\".<ref name=\"p215\" /> The relative simplicity of the lyrics were criticised by ''Vulture'', who described them as akin to \"[[Mick Jagger]]'s '80s output, bland clich\u00e9 for bland clich\u00e9.\"<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nThe rallying cry lyrics for \"We Are the Clash\" are sometimes seen as a defiant response to Jones's lawsuit. The album version differs substantially from both earlier live recordings and a 1983 demo. It is more polished, the lyrics have been changed in parts, the tempo has been slowed down, the bridge changed to an intro and the [[Call and response (music)|call-and-response]] chorus removed.<ref name=\"k122\" /> The song has received mixed reviews. It was criticised for its confused politics and thin sound, the guitar solo and back-in-the-mix vocal chants in particular lacking [[Bass (sound)|low-end]] frequencies. ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'' placed it last in its 2017 ranking of all 139 songs by the Clash from worst to best.<ref name=\"vul\" />{{refn|The ''Vulture'' article gave the bottom ranking, out of all the Clash's recorded songs, to seven tracks from the album. In order of weakness, those tracks are \"We Are the Clash\" (139), \"Play to Win\" (138), \"Fingerpoppin\" (137), \"Dictator\" (136), \"Dirty Punk\" (135), \"Are You Red..Y\" (134), and \"Movers and Shakers\" (133). \"This Is England\" ranked highest from the album at number 71.<ref name=\"vul\" />|group=n}} ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' took issue with the song's title, calling it \"an outright lie\" in light of the album's exclusion of both Jones and Headon.<ref name=\"RS\">Gehr, Richard; Greene, Andy; Harris, Keith; [[Maura Johnston|Johnston, Maura]]; Newman, Jason; Weingarten, Christopher R. \"[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/22-terrible-songs-by-great-artists-20160615/the-clash-we-are-the-clash-1985-20160615 22 Terrible Songs by Great Artists]\". ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 15 June 2016. [https://web.archive.org/web20190105094247/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/22-terrible-songs-by-great-artists-20368/the-clash-we-are-the-clash-1985-32110/ Archived] from the original on 5 January 2019. Retrieved 7 January 2017</ref> Music critic [[Tony Fletcher]] responded to the chant of \"We Are the Clash\" with the words \"No you're not{{nbsp}}... you're a pale imitation of [[Sham 69]] at the disco\".<ref name=\"Fletcher 2012\">Fletcher (2012)</ref> Clash biographer Chris Knowles disliked Rhodes's production but admired Strummer's songwriting, and considers the album version as a lost opportunity given that the song had been a \"killer\" live favourite.<ref name=\"k122\" />\n\n\"Are You Red..Y\" had originally been titled \"Are You Ready for War\".<ref name=\"A10\" /> \"Cool Under Heat\" is a reggae-ballad whose production choices have been criticised as cluttered and confused, several writers noting that its strong lyrics and tune are buried underneath a jumble of extraneous instruments and studio effects.<ref name=\"snow\" /> The guitar sound is especially flat and restrained by overly [[Dynamic range compression|compressed]] production.<ref name=\"snow\" /><ref name=\"p219\">Popoff (2018), p. 219</ref> Popoff found the album version inferior to the Clash's live versions that were reminiscent of [[the Pogues]], which the band had played on an early-1985 [[Street performance|busking]] tour.<ref name=\"p219\" />\n\nThe opening line of \"Movers and Shakers\"\u2014\"[[Casabianca (poem)|The boy stood]] in the burning slum\"\u2014was described by writer Sean Egan as \"a piece of unconscious self-parody that is quite probably the worst line ever to appear on a Clash record\".<ref name=\"e193\">Egan (2014), p. 193</ref> Fletcher called the lyric \"excruciating\" given that Strummer was then a successful rock star, but resigned himself with the observation \"fortunately for [him] not enough people were listening to be truly offended.\"<ref name=\"Fletcher 2012\"/> Apart from the lyrics, the song's drum programming has often been criticised as clunky, although the vocal melody has been praised.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n===Side two===\n{{Listen\n|filename = The Clash This is England.ogg\n|title = \"This Is England\"\n|description = \"This Is England\" has been described as the Clash's last great song, even though it is emblematic of the album's maligned production characteristics, especially in its use of [[synthesizer]]s and chanted choruses.<ref name=\"vul\" />}}\n\n\"This Is England\" opens [[A-side and B-side|side two]], and is widely regarded as the album's stand-out track. It was released as the band's last single and Strummer himself called it the \"last great Clash song\".<ref name=\"still\">Spencer, Neil; Brown, James. \"[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/29/popandrock Why the Clash are still Rock Titans]\". ''[[The Guardian]]'', 29 October 2006. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190419212603/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/29/popandrock Archived] from the original on 19 April 2019. Retrieved 10 February 2019</ref><ref name=\"Popoff2018\">Popoff (2018), p. 226</ref> Co-written by Strummer and Rhodes, the song retains some of the reggae influences of their earlier albums.<ref name=\"RS\" /> Like \"We Are the Clash\", its chorus is sung in a football chant, but here it is higher in the mix. The guitars are also prominent, but the percussion is again supplied by a drum track.<ref name=\"c109\" /> Lennox described it as a \"tuneful, beautifully crafted overview of social decay in England, where political philosophies joust for hegemony while the country sinks into ignominious decline and millions of youths turn to [[Jobseeker's Allowance|the dole]].\"<ref name=\"SL\" /> The lyrics convey [[Social alienation|societal alienation]], lamenting the national mood in 1985; the line \"South Atlantic wind blows\" refers to the [[Falklands War]].<ref name=\"c109\">Cohen; Peacock (2017), p. 109</ref> Writing for ''Vulture'' in 2017, writer Bill Wyman described the song as the only successful track on ''Cut the Crap'', writing that \"the sound collage and the gentle, troubled synth lines undergird the song unerringly, and for once the group-shouted chorus, though still over-loud, conveys some wan meaning. This can't have been a good time for Strummer, and you can hear it in his voice, as he sings the fuck out of this.\"<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nThe production of the live favourite \"Three Card Trick\" is relatively uncluttered, although it does contain programmed hand-claps.<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 228</ref> According to Jucha, the original song was good enough to have appeared on any Clash album, and he observed how Strummer had developed a real skill for writing mid-tempo songs.<ref>Jucha (2016), pp. 330\u2013331</ref> The track began as a straightforward punk song<ref name=\"aH\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), p. 147</ref> with a simple [[Ska]] bass line.\n\nWriter Mark Andersen described \"Fingerpoppin\" and \"Play to Win\" as essentially [[B-side]]-quality songs that should have been excluded from final track listing.<ref name=\"A9\" /> The latter is a sound collage which Popoff views as incoherent and basically \"noise, [[bongos]], and nonsensical fragmented conversations between Joe and Vince\".<ref name=\"p229\">Popoff (2018), p. 229</ref> Although the drums are considered too low in the mix, and the shouted choruses have been described as resembling [[Adam and the Ants]], its demo version is more favorably viewed,<ref name=\"p229\" /> mostly because of verses omitted in the final recording.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\nThe penultimate track \"North and South\" was written and sung by Sheppard. It features a simple guitar line and uncluttered production, and has often been highlighted by critics as one of the album's strongest tracks.<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 231</ref> The album closer, \"Life Is Wild\", is the only track which had not been played live before. Its chorus, stylistically akin to the punk subgenre [[Oi!]],<ref name=\"k123\">Knowles (2003), p. 123</ref> was described by Popoff as a \"curious thumping party rocker that makes little sense\" and begged the question why a songwriter of Strummer's ability would write \"such banalities\".<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 232</ref>\n\n==Sleeve art and title==\nThe album cover was designed by Rhodes, Eddie King and Jules Balme, the art director for [[Stiff Records]],<ref>Eskelsen, Danny. \"[https://www.mojo4music.com/articles/3437/ian-durys-eyeball-pleasers Ian Dury\u2019s Eyeball Pleasers]\". ''[[Mojo (magazine)]]'', 24 July 2013. Retrieved 1 September 2019</ref> who had earlier overseen the covers for ''Sandinista!'' and ''Combat Rock''.<ref>Garcia (2012), First Night Back in London, 332</ref> It shows a punk wearing a [[Mohawk hairstyle|mohawk]], black leather jacket and sunglasses\u2014all markers of 1980s [[punk fashion]]. The image is rendered so that the portrait looks like a poster glued to a wall. A similar image appears on the [[Single (music)|7-inch]] release of \"This Is England\".<ref name=\"e190\">Egan (2014), p. 190</ref> A lithograph of the cover is held by the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York, who attribute an \"unknown designer\".<ref>\"[https://www.moma.org/collection/works/156171 The Clash, Cut the Crap, 1985]\". [[Museum of Modern Art]]. Retrieved 22 June 2019</ref>\n\nReflecting the chaos surrounding the recording sessions, and as an ironic reference to a [[Complete Control|track]] from the Jones era, the album's working title was ''Out of Control'',<ref name=\"j334\">Jucha (2016), p. 334</ref> until Rhodes, without consulting the band, changed it shortly before its release. He took the words \"cut the crap\" from a scene in the 1981 [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] film ''[[Mad Max 2]]'', when [[Mel Gibson]]'s character, [[Max Rockatansky]], insists on driving the oil tanker on which the settlers' survival depends: \"Come on, cut the crap. I'm the best chance you've got.\"<ref name=\"j328\">Jucha (2016), p. 328</ref> According to Jucha, the sentiment reflected the band's view of themselves in the mid-1980s: \"the back-to-basics Clash, Round two\u2014like the initial band of UK punk rockers\u2014were going to eradicate the meaningless [[New Romantic]] bands dominating the British pop world. They were 'the best chance [the world's] got'.\"<ref name=\"j329\">Jucha (2016), p. 329</ref> Nevertheless, the title is widely disliked; Jucha described it as \"awful\".<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n==Reception==\nBy the time the new \"Mark II\" lineup released ''Cut the Crap'' on 4&nbsp;November 1985, they were an accomplished live band, and had written and performed several songs that would appear on the final album; a few had been live favourites. On the strength of their recent gigs, the UK press were optimistically waiting for the album's release. Epic Records anticipated that both the three-year gap since ''Combat Rock'' along with their updated sound, would result in critical acclaim and high sales.<ref name=\"A9\" /> In the promotional lead up, Strummer told journalist [[Richard Cook (journalist)|Richard Cook]] that he was not going release any new material until he knew it could \"last ten years\".<ref name=\"j329\" /> Most critics and fans were disappointed on its release\u2014especially with its sound and production values, and the omission of stand-out live tracks \"In the Pouring Rain\" and \"Ammunition\" (usually titled \"Jericho\" in contemporary [[bootleg recording]]s).<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n''Cut the Crap'' sold poorly compared to earlier Clash releases, reaching just number 16 in the UK charts and number 88 in the US.<ref name=\"e190\" /> Contemporary reviews of lead single \"This Is England\" were negative and, upon the album's release, British and American critics alike generally viewed the album in an unfavourable light. ''[[Melody Maker]]'' and ''[[NME]]'' both published sharply negative reviews, the latter of which was titled \"No Way, Jose\" in sarcastic reference to the \"Jose Unidos\" production credit.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Reflecting the critical consensus at the time, Mike Laye\u2014a writer, photographer and Clash insider\u2014said the band should \"just drop the 'Cut' from the title, because to me this [is] crap.\"<ref name=\"GaCTC\">Garcia (2012), Cut the Crap, 2420</ref> [[David Fricke]] panned the album in ''Rolling Stone'', saying \"too much of ''Cut the Crap'' is Strummer's angst running on automatic, superficially ferocious but ultimately stiff and unconvincing.\"<ref name=\"df\" /> [[Robert Christgau]], a longtime champion of the Clash in the US, offered only restrained praise in a ''[[The Village Voice|Village Voice]]'' review that alluded to the negative word-of-mouth and summarized most of the album as \"stubborn and jolly and elegiac and together\".<ref name=\"A9\" /><ref name=\"Christgau\">[[Robert Christgau|Christgau, Robert]]. \"[http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1b-86.php Christgau's Consumer Guide]\". ''[[The Village Voice]]'', 28 January 1986. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190105200901/http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1b-86.php Archived] from the original on 5 January 2019. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref> Music journalist Richard Cromelin found the album's uptempo songs less effective than those on earlier Clash records, but concluded that Strummer's singing is compelling and \"This Is England\" and \"North and South\" make the record \"more than passable\".<ref>Cromelin, Richard. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-17/entertainment/ca-6896_1_joe-strummer Album Review: Less Slash From The New Clash]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 17 November 1985. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160307092209/http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-17/entertainment/ca-6896_1_joe-strummer Archived] from the original on 7 March 2016. Retrieved 10 September 2015</ref>\n\nThe absence of Jones and Headon led many to regard it as a Joe Strummer solo album\u2014an impression further solidified by Simonon's involvement being limited only to the pre-production stage. Its shortcomings were often attributed to Strummer's evident disillusionment with the group and the fact that he was grieving over the recent deaths of his parents.<ref>Parker, Alan. \"Rebel Truce: The History of the Clash\", Part Six. [[Sky Arts]], 2010. 5:20</ref> Joe Sasfy of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that the \"revised version of the Clash sounds like a pale and ghostly facsimile of this once-great band\"; he disliked the {{nowrap|\"[tiresome]}} garbled choruses\" and he found that \"Strummer's attempt to enliven them with horn charts creates an ungainly mess of a sound.\"<ref>Morse, Steve. \"Sasfy, Joe. \"Rants Without Raves; Political Pap From the Revised Clash\". ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 21 November 1985</ref> Music critic Liam Lacey was dismissive overall, writing that the \"rebel polemics sound dated, and the songwriting is occasionally banal\", but concluded that, given the strength of \"This Is England\", \"in its cheesily self-aggrandizing way, the new Clash may be on to something.\"<ref>Lacey, Liam. \"Inside the Sleeve\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 21 November 1985</ref> Similarly, Richard Defendorf of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' described the record as a \"sometimes embarrassingly anachronistic{{nbsp}}... attempt to rekindle the Clash's punkish, militant energy.\"<ref>Defendorf, Richard. \"The Clash\". ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'', 24 November 1985</ref>\n\n''Cut the Crap'' has been favourably reevaluated in some retrospective reviews, many praising Strummer's songwriting and vocal performance. For example, the writer [[Jon Savage]] praised the album in his influential 1991 book on the history of punk, ''England's Dreaming'',<ref name=\"k123\" />  highlighting the \"innovative use of rap rhythm and atmosphere\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Savage |first1=Jon |title=England's Dreaming |date=2005 |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=London |isbn=0571227201 |page=590 |edition=Main}}</ref> Yet its reputation as a failure, or at least as a lost opportunity, has endured. In 2002, [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] described \"This Is England\" as \"surprisingly nervy\" on a record that, in his view, is otherwise \"formulaic, tired punk rock that doesn't have the aggression or purpose of early Clash records\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Joe-Strummer.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1|Strummer in concert, supporting [[the Pogues]], Japan, 1992]]\nStrummer was depressed by both the album's sound and critical appraisal. Asked in 1986 how the reviews affected him, he replied: \"Sure I read [them] but I didn't need them to tell me. It was like when you're younger and you're trying to make a date with a girl but she won't have any of it. You keep going back, trying to fool yourself that this time will be better.\"<ref name=\"NME\">Martin, Gavin. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/joe-strummer-good-ol-joe Joe Strummer: Good Ol' Joe]\". ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'', 26 July 1986 \u2013 via Rock's Backpages {{subscription required}}</ref> He was particularly upset that people had thought the \"Jose Unidos\" pseudonym credited as a producer was him rather than Rhodes, and said \"it wouldn't have been so bad if Bernie had just got the blame but that was unbearable.\"<ref name=\"NME\" /> The album was cited by a several contemporary reviewers as symptomatic of why punk rock had failed. Strummer said in 1988: \"To someone who says I was{{nbsp}}... 'the spokesman for your generation and you fucked it up', I say yeah, but we tried.\"<ref>D'Ambrosio (2012)</ref> He admitted that he had undertaken the project in part to prove that Jones hadn't been the Clash's only songwriter.<ref name=\"j332\">Jucha (2016), p. 332</ref> White believes the album's commercial failure was caused by a combination of Strummer's hubris and Rhodes's ambitions, both of which led to apathy and discontent with the band.<ref name=\"j334\" /> The Clash's standing did not fully recover until Strummer's work with [[the Pogues]] on the ''[[Straight to Hell (film)|Straight to Hell]]'' soundtrack in 1987.<ref name=\"e199\">Egan (2014), p. 199</ref>\n\nEpic Records intended a tour shortly after the release, but there were practical issues that made this impossible. Foremost, Strummer was in exile in Spain and refusing to partake in promoting the record; he had even threatened to take legal action to prevent its release.<ref name=\"NME\" /><ref>Egan (2014), p. 116</ref> After their treatment during the album's recording, White and Howard were bitter, demotivated and reluctant to engage with the material. Finally, given that Rhodes had so heavily revised the original songs and utilised so many samples and studio effects, he and Strummer disagreed on how the tracks should be played live.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Epic had planned a highly produced and expensive [[music video|video]] for \"This is England\", with a view for a still more expensive version to promote its US release. The idea was shelved when neither Strummer nor Simonon turned up for the shooting.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nStrummer dissolved the band that October, giving each of the remaining members a thousand pounds each as [[Severance package|severance payments]]. Howard told him, somewhat bitterly, that \"this is where it got you\" for following Bernie's lead\u2014a statement to which he agreed.<ref name=\"Louder\" /> White suggested that he either publish an open letter of retraction in the weekly music press and [[tabloid journalism|tabloids]],{{refn|Howard said that Strummer took his advice and wrote up a press release titled \"Crap Cutting Commencing\", detailing in wartime language how the band had been hoodwinked by a political dictator, i.e., Rhodes. The piece was never published.<ref name=\"GJS\" />|group=n}} or re-record the album without Rhodes, but Strummer demurred.<ref name=\"GJS\">Garcia (2012), Joe Splits, 2462</ref>\n\nUnder pressure from Epic to get the band out on tour to promote the album, Rhodes asked the three remaining members to consider hiring a new singer, rationalising that \"The Clash has always been an idea{{nbsp}}... Now, how to take that idea to the next level!\"{{refn|[[Vic Godard]] believes that Rhodes was by then trying to take over the Clash's brand name, and would \"have a version out there now touring\" many years after Strummer left, if he could have legally managed it.<ref name=\"GSA\" />|group=n}} They briefly considered the possibility, Rhodes suggesting Simonon, a position the bassist resolutely refused<ref name=\"GSA\">Garcia (2012), Singer Auditions, 2491</ref> until Strummer officially disbanded the group.<ref name=\"A10\" /> Having disowned the album, \"Three Card Trick\" was the only track Strummer played live during his solo career.<ref name=\"j332\" />\n\n''Cut the Crap'' was remastered and re-released in Europe in the mid-2000s, with the bonus track \"Do It Now\". The reissue was unannounced and not promoted. It came after the rest of the band's catalogue had been reissued between December 1999 and January 2000 in the US. The album was not mentioned in the Clash documentary ''[[The Clash: Westway to the World]]'' (2000) and was acknowledged only briefly in the official illustrated biography ''The Clash'' (2008), not receiving an overview as the first five albums had. The album has been omitted from many Clash compilations, box sets and reissues, including ''[[The Story of the Clash, Volume 1|The Story of the Clash]]'' (1988), ''[[Clash on Broadway]]'' (1991), ''[[The Singles (1991 The Clash album)|The Singles]]'' (1991), ''[[Sound System (album)|Sound System]]'' (2013) and ''[[5 Album Studio Set]]'' (2013).{{refn|\"This Is England\" was included in ''[[The Essential Clash]]'' (2003) and [[The Singles (2007 The Clash album)|the 2007 box set reissue of ''The Singles'']]''.|group=n}}<ref name=\"Kott\">Kott, Crispin. \"[https://www.popmatters.com/120558-i-found-a-reason-the-velvet-undergrounds-lost-chapter-2496163399.html The Velvet Underground's Lost Chapter]\". ''[[PopMatters]]'', 11 February 2010. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190618194508/https://www.popmatters.com/120558-i-found-a-reason-the-velvet-undergrounds-lost-chapter-2496163399.html Archived] from the original on 18 June 2019. Retrieved 18 June 2019</ref> According to Simonon, ''Cut the Crap'' was excluded because it was not seen as a real Clash album, as neither Jones nor Headon were involved.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nDirector [[Shane Meadows]] in 2006 used the title ''This is England'' for his [[This Is England|movie and TV show]] centering on young [[skinhead]]s and [[Oi!|Oi! punks]] in England in the 1980s, in reference to the ''Cut the Crap'' song.<ref name=\"still\" />\n\n==Track listing==\nThe liner notes credit all songs to Strummer and Rhodes.<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n'''Side one'''\n# \"Dictator\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:00\n# \"Dirty Punk\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:11\n# \"We Are the Clash\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:02\n# \"Are You Red..Y\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n# \"Cool Under Heat\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:21\n# \"Movers and Shakers\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n\n'''Side two'''\n# \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:49\n# \"Three Card Trick\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:09\n# \"Play to Win\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:06\n# \"Fingerpoppin'\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:25\n# \"North and South\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:32\n# \"Life Is Wild\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:39\n\n==Personnel==\n'''The Clash'''<ref>''Cut the Crap'' liner notes. [[Epic Records]], 4 November 1985</ref>\n* [[Joe Strummer]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], guitars\n* [[Nick Sheppard]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, lead vocals on \"North and South\"\n* [[Vince White]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional guitars on \"Do It Now\"\n* [[Paul Simonon]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass on some tracks (including \"Do It Now\")\n* [[Pete Howard]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums on \"Do It Now\"\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n* [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum machine]] programming\n* [[Norman Watt-Roy]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass guitar<ref name=\"KentOL\">{{cite web |url= https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dover/news/complete-control-194632/|publisher=[[KM Group|Kent Online]] |title=Nick 'Topper' Headon, former Clash drummer, with The Blockheads at The Booking Hall, Dover|accessdate=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n* Michael Fayne&nbsp;\u2013 drum machines, vocals on \"Play to Win\"\n* Hermann Weindorf&nbsp;\u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[synthesizer]]s\n\n'''Production'''\n* Bernie Rhodes&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|producer]] (credited as \"Jose Unidos\")<ref>Knowles (2003), p. 77</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Chart\n! Position\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1985\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Swedish Albums Chart<ref name=\"sweden\">\"[http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Clash Discography The Clash]\". SwedishCharts.com. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180914022853/https://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Clash Archived] from the original on 14 September 2018. Retrieved 26 October 2008</ref>\n| 30\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | UK Albums Chart<ref name=\"e190\" />\n| 16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | US ''Billboard'' 200<ref name=\"USCharts\">\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160614215053/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-clash-mn0000075747/awards The Clash: Charts & Awards]\". AllMusic. Archived from [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-clash-mn0000075747/awards the original] on 14 June 2016. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref>\n| 88\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Andersen, Mark; Heibutzki, Ralph. ''We Are the Clash: Reagan, Thatcher, and the Last Stand of a Band That Mattered''. New York: Akashic Books, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-6177-5293-3}}\n* Cohen, Samuel; Peacock, James. ''The Clash Takes on the World: Transnational Perspectives on the Only Band that Matters''. London: Bloomsbury, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5013-1733-0}}\n* D'Ambrosio, Antonino. ''Let Fury Have the Hour: Joe Strummer, Punk, and the Movement that Shook the World''. Seattle, WA: Amazon Media, 2012. {{ASIN|B06XKC3PXQ}}\n* Garcia, Danny. ''The Rise and Fall of the Clash''. London: Thin Man Press, 2012. {{ISBN|9780956247322}}\n* Gilbert, Pat. ''Passion Is a Fashion: The Real Story of the Clash''. Boston, MA: Da Capo Press, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-3068-1434-1}}\n* Egan, Sean. ''The Clash: The Only Band That Mattered''. London: Rowman & Littlefield, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-8875-3}}\n* [[Tony Fletcher|Fletcher, Tony]]. ''The Clash: The Music That Matters''. London,  Omnibus Press, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-7803-8303-3}}\n* Jucha, Gary. ''The Clash FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the Clash City Rockers''. Milwaukee, WI: Backbeat Books, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-4803-6450-9}}\n* Knowles, Chris. ''Clash City Showdown''. London: PageFree, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1-5896-1138-2}}\n* [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Larkin, Colin]]. ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''. London: Omnibus Press, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-8571-2595-8}}\n* [[Dave Marsh|Marsh, Dave]]. ''The Heart of Rock & Soul: The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever Made''. London: Penguin, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-1401-2108-7}}\n* [[Kris Needs|Needs, Chris]]. ''Joe Strummer and the Legend of the Clash''. London: Plexus, 2005. {{ISBN|978-0-8596-5348-0}}\n* [[Martin Popoff|Popoff, Martin]]. ''The Clash: All the Albums, All the Songs''. London: Voyageur Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-0-7603-5934-1}}\n* [[Chris Salewicz|Salewicz, Chris]]. ''[[Redemption Song: The Ballad of Joe Strummer]]''. London: Faber and Faber, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-5712-1178-4}}\n* [[Jon Savage|Savage, Jon]]. ''England's Dreaming: The Sex Pistols and Punk Rock''. London: Faber and Faber, 1991. {{ISBN|978-0-3122-8822-8}}\n* [[Rob Sheffield|Sheffield, Rob]]. \"The Clash\". ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (4th ed.). New York: Fireside, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-7432-0169-8}}\n* [[David Quantick|Quantick, David]]. \"The Clash\" (Kill Your Idols series). London: Unanimous, 2000. {{ISBN|978-1-9033-1803-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{The Clash}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cut The Crap}}\n[[Category:1985 albums]]\n[[Category:The Clash albums]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Cut the Crap\n| type       = [[Studio album]]\n| artist     = [[The Clash]]\n| cover      = Cut the Crap.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|1985|11|4}}\n| recorded   = January\u2013March 1985\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Weryton, [[Unterf\u00f6hring]], Germany<ref name=\"p211\">Popoff (2018), p. 211</ref>\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]<ref name=\"allmusic\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. \"[https://www.allmusic.com/album/cut-the-crap-mw0000691234 Cut the Crap: The Clash]\". [[AllMusic]]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190413060720/https://www.allmusic.com/album/cut-the-crap-mw0000691234 Archived] from the original on 13 April 2019. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref>\n| length     = {{unbulleted list\n|{{duration|m=38|s=21}}\n|{{duration|m=41|s=29}} (with \"Do It Now\")\n}}\n| label      = [[CBS Records|CBS ]](UK)\n| producer   = Jose Unidos ({{a.k.a.}} [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]])<ref name=\"p211\" />\n| prev_title = [[Combat Rock]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title =\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Cut the Crap\n | type        = [[Studio album]]\n | single1     = [[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\n | single1date = September 1985\n | single2     = Are You Red..Y\n | single2date = 1985\n}}\n}}\n'''''Cut the Crap''''' is the sixth and final [[studio album]] by the English [[Punk rock|punk]] band [[the Clash]], released on 4&nbsp;November 1985 by [[CBS Records]]. It was recorded in early 1985 at Weryton Studios, [[Munich]], following a turbulent period: co-founder, lead guitarist and co-principal songwriter [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] and drummer [[Topper Headon]] had been dismissed by lead vocalist [[Joe Strummer]] and bassist [[Paul Simonon]]. Jones and Headon were replaced  by three unknowns: guitarists [[Vince White]] and [[Nick Sheppard]] and drummer [[Pete Howard]]. During the tense recording sessions, and Clash manager [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]] and Strummer fought with each other for control over the band's songwriting and musical direction.\n\nStrummer and Rhodes co-wrote most of the songs. During production, Rhodes took charge of the [[arrangement]]s, track sequencing and the final [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]]. His production choices, which rely heavily on Strummer's preference for [[synthesizers|synthetic]] drum sounds and Rhodes' own inclusion of [[Sampler (musical instrument)|sampling]], were widely derided. One writer described the album\u2019s sound as brash and seemingly \"designed to sound hip and modern\u2014'[[1980s in music|80s style!]]\".<ref name=\"vul\">Wyman, Bill. \"[https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/all-139-the-clash-songs-ranked-from-worst-to-best.html 139 the Clash Songs, Ranked from Worst to Best]\". ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'', 11 October 2017. [https://web.archive.org/web/20171011193355/https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/all-139-the-clash-songs-ranked-from-worst-to-best.html Archived] from the original on 11 October 2017. Retrieved 10 February 2019</ref> Rhodes chose the album title, taken from a line in the 1981 post-apocalyptic film ''[[Mad Max 2]]''. On release, ''Cut the Crap'' was maligned in the UK music press as \"one of the most disastrous [albums] ever released by a major artist\".<ref>Ziegler, Jay. \"[https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/03/dusting-em-off-the-clash-cut-the-crap/ Dusting 'Em Off: The Clash \u2013 ''Cut the Crap'']\". ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', 8 March 2009. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180826064025/https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/03/dusting-em-off-the-clash-cut-the-crap/ Archived] from the original on 26 August 2018. Retrieved 7 January 2018</ref><ref name=\"Louder\">Knowles, Chris. \"[https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-clash-i-suppose-the-end-really-came-when-mick-left-the-band The Final Days of the Clash]\". ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder Sound]]'', 18 April 2005. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190413135749/https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-clash-i-suppose-the-end-really-came-when-mick-left-the-band Archived] from the original on 13 April 2019. Retrieved 6 January 2019</ref> Strummer disowned the album and dissolved the Clash within weeks of its release.\n\nThe recording process and tension between Rhodes and Strummer left other band members disillusioned. White's and Sheppard's contributions are almost entirely absent in the final mix, and Howard was replaced by an electronic drum machine. Epic Records hoped the album would advance the Clash's success in the United States, and planned an expensive video for lead single \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\"; by the album's release, the band members were so discouraged that they did not turn up for the first day's shoot. Strummer moved to Spain, in part due to family issues, but also to escape the backlash.\n\nThe album was poorly received upon release, and is still generally regarded as the band's worst album; Strummer performed only one song from the album live during his solo career, and the album has been excluded altogether from most of the Clash\u2019s compilations and box sets. Some retrospective assessments have been more sympathetic; a number of critics and writers have praised Strummer's songwriting and vocal performance, and Rhode's production, especially on the tracks \"This Is England\", \"Dirty Punk\" and \"Three Card Trick\".\n\n==Background==\n[[The Clash]]'s internal difficulties during 1983 led to two of its core members being fired: guitarist [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] was seen as adopting rock star posturing that vocalist [[Joe Strummer]] considered anathema to what the band stood for, and drummer [[Topper Headon]] had developed a [[heroin]] addiction which left him unreliable.<ref name=\"e103\">Egan (2014), p. 103</ref> After the band undertook rehearsals in London during June 1983,<ref>Gilbert (2014), pp. 336\u2013337</ref> interpersonal tensions reemerged. The two principal songwriters no longer trusted each other, due to Jones's frequent absence from rehearsals and use of synthesizers.<ref name=\"g3389\">Gilbert (2014), pp. 338\u2013339</ref> Both Jones and bassist [[Paul Simonon]] refused to sign a contract negotiated by newly reinstated manager [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]],<ref name=\"g3389\" /> who had earlier been fired due to personal differences with Jones.<ref name=\"A6\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), chapter 6</ref>\n\n[[File:Mickjones.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.7|Founding Clash guitarist [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] in 1987]]\nThe relationship between Strummer and Jones had broken down by this point.<ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 339</ref> Not long into rehearsals, Strummer and Simonon had fired Jones.<ref>Gilbert (2014), pp. 340\u2013341</ref>{{refn|Simonon has said that Rhodes had not been aware of, nor later approved of, Jones's firing.<ref>Salewicz (2007), pp. 373\u2013375</ref>|group=n}} A week before the official announcement of the dismissal, Strummer, Simonon and Rhodes began to look for replacements and  met [[Pete Howard]].<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 344</ref> The band placed anonymous advertisements for replacement guitarists in ''[[Melody Maker]]''. After auditioning over 100 candidates,<ref name=\"vice\">Haynes, Gavin. \"[https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdve37/were-the-clash-bullshit Were the Clash Bullshit?]\". ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', 29 October 2010. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190511202306/https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdve37/were-the-clash-bullshit Archived] from the original on 11 May 2019. Retrieved 11 May 2019</ref> they eventually hired unknown musicians [[Nick Sheppard]] and [[Vince White|Greg White]]. White took the pseudonym Vince after Simonon complained that he would prefer to quit than play in a band with someone named Greg.<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref>Gilbert (2014), p. 345</ref> Both were given a weekly wage of \u00a3100<ref name=\"vice\" /> rather than [[recording contract]]s.<ref name=\"A10\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), chapter 10</ref>\n\nStrummer had been the band's principal lyricist, while Jones had written their music. After Jones was fired, the band assumed that anyone could write a punk song. This proved to be a mistake<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 359</ref> and, unknown to members of the Clash, Rhodes had already conceived his own solution to Jones's departure\u2014he would take control of the music.<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 360</ref><ref name=\"df\">[[David Fricke|Fricke, David]]. \"[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/cut-the-crap-103110/ ''Cut the Crap'']. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 16 January 1986. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100409042234/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/theclash/albums/album/132884/review/5943097/cut_the_crap Archived] from the original on 9 April 2010. Retrieved 15 June 2019</ref>\n\nStrummer intended the second Clash line-up to encapsulate a back-to-basics approach to punk. The new musicians largely avoided the [[reggae]]-influenced style of their two previous albums, ''[[Sandinista!]]'' (1980) and ''[[Combat Rock]]'' (1982).<ref>Salewicz (2007), p. 363</ref> Strummer began to refer to the line-up as \"the Clash, Round Two\", a phrase adopted by the press as \"the Clash Mark&nbsp;II\".<ref>Jucha (2016), p. 317</ref> They booked a short tour of the US West Coast, debuting new songs, which prompted Jones to boast to concert promoter [[Bill Graham (promoter)|Bill Graham]] that he was planning his own tour with Headon as \"the Real Clash\".<ref name=\"p216\">Popoff (2018), p. 216</ref> Jones's lawyers had frozen the band's earnings from both the US Festival and sales of ''Combat Rock''. In response, Strummer wrote the song \"We Are the Clash\", which, along with \"Three Card Trick\", \"Sex Mad Roar\" and \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\", was debuted during live appearances in January 1984.<ref>Salewicz (2007), pp. 364\u2013365</ref> In all, the Clash Mark&nbsp;II had written around 20 new songs before entering the studio to record what became the band's final album.<ref>Gibson, Phil. \"[https://louderthanwar.com/the-clash-cut-the-crap-cutting-edge-or-just-crap/ The Clash 'Cut the Crap' \u2013 Cutting edge or just crap?]\". ''[[Louder Than War (website)|Louder Than War]]'', 13 March 2012. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190511213845/https://louderthanwar.com/the-clash-cut-the-crap-cutting-edge-or-just-crap/ Archived] from the original on 11 May 2019. Retrieved 11 May 2019</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n[[File:JoeStrummer1980 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Joe Strummer]] performing at the [[Tower Theater (Upper Darby Township, Pennsylvania)|Tower Theater]], March 6, 1980]]\nThe album was recorded between January and February 1985, on a [[Multitrack recording|24-track]] mixing desk in Weryton Studios, [[Unterf\u00f6hring]], outside [[Munich]], Germany,<ref name=\"j325\">Jucha (2016), p. 325</ref><ref name=\"k252\">Knowles (2003), p. 252</ref> with some parts recorded in London. Epic Records chose the German studio because the band's finances were dependent on a number of ongoing legal cases,<ref>Knowles (2003), p. 249</ref> including moves by Jones to prevent them recording under the name \"the Clash\".<ref name=\"A9\">Anderson, Heibutzki (2018), chapter 9</ref> Rhodes hired [[Audio engineer|engineer]] Micheal Fayne on the basis of affordability, and his prior experience with programmed [[drum machine]]s,<ref name=\"j325\" /> which Strummer wanted to use on the album because, according to Rhodes, \"Joe wanted to compete with Mick's drum machine thing\".<ref name=\"grdrum\" /> Rhodes also employed engineers Ulrich A. Rudolf, Simon Sullivan and Kevin Whyte, each of whom are credited on the sleeve.<ref name=\"p211\" />\n\nStrummer and Rhodes disagreed on the direction of the recordings almost from the outset. Rhodes, credited on the sleeve under the pseudonym \"Jose Unidos\",<ref name=\"NME\" /> had no previous experience with either songwriting or record production. While Strummer had been pleased with his demo versions, he fought against his manager over the album's production.<ref name=\"NME\" /> Rhodes's believed he had discovered a new genre, seeking to mix [[electro (music)|electro]], [[hip hop]] and [[cut-up technique]].<ref name=\"GaCTC\" /> He replaced live musicians with synthetic sounds and layered the tracks with audio from TV programs.<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nHoward was given vague instructions, such as to play like he was throwing the drum kit down some stairs.<ref name=\"grdrum\">Garcia (2012), Drum Machine, 2276</ref> White recalled working with Strummer for extended period on guitar parts, which Rhodes would later refuse to include; he remembered that Strummer had at times stood up to the producer, but \"not nearly enough\". In the same way, White often felt demoralised by Rhodes, who berated the guitarist's playing from a technical standpoint. White believed Rhodes used such tactics to wear him down, and he was eventually dismissed from the studio by his manager.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n[[File:PaulSimonon1980.jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Paul Simonon]] at the Tower Theater in 1980. The bassist does not appear on any of the album's final recordings.]]\nFayne described Rhodes's treatment of Howard as \"damaging\". Rhodes would begin recording sessions by asking the drummer to play what he wanted, but would inevitably respond to Howard's parts by saying \"no, not that\", or \"no, not that either\".<ref name=\"grdrum\" /> In one incident, Rhodes appeared in the recording room and began to \"smash the drum kit up\", at which point Howard stood up and left.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Fayne shared White's view that these incidents were a ploy by Rhodes to force the new recruits out of the band. He said, \"Bernie didn't want any connection with the past{{nbsp}}... He wanted to take it forward, to control it, to mastermind the whole thing, and what they were doing was a bit too reminiscent of what it was\".<ref name=\"A9\" /> Disillusioned and lacking reinforcement or direction from Strummer, Howard seriously considered leaving the band at several points.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nMost of the Clash and production team liked the [[Football chant|football-style chants]] used in some of the choruses. They were in part inspired by the communal [[sing-along]]s the Clash performed during their busking tour the previous year, and thus evoked memories of a less tense period in their career. The massed vocals were provided by several dozen of their friends and families, and several of the inner team remembered those sessions as the only enjoyable period during the album's recording.<ref name=\"A9\" /> The only other aspect that the musicians agreed on was the quality and commercial potential of \"This is England\", a song into which Rhodes allowed the musicians significant creative input.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\nRhodes suddenly ended the recordings and took the [[Audio mastering|master tapes]] from the studio, after which he added further synthesizer parts.<ref name=\"Louder\" /><ref name=\"A9\" /> Although Jones's use of synthesizers and samplers was one of the main reasons behind his dismissal, those instruments brought him critical and public acclaim with his next band [[Big Audio Dynamite]].<ref name=\"br\" /> When asked at the time for his opinion on [[This Is Big Audio Dynamite|the debut B.A.D. album]], Strummer described it as one of the \"worst pieces of shit I have ever heard.\"<ref name=\"A9\" /> In 1986, Strummer said that he had liked a few of the tunes but \"really I hated it{{nbsp}}... I didn't hear [the album as a whole] until it was in the shops.\"<ref name=\"NME\" /> Strummer ultimately lost control of ''Cut the Crap'' to Rhodes,<ref name=\"NME\" /> and became so disillusioned that at one point he asked Jones to rejoin the band, but was refused.<ref name=\"Louder\" />\n\nSimonon does not appear on any of the final recordings; the bass lines were performed by [[Norman Watt-Roy]], former member of [[the Blockheads]], who was not credited on the sleeve.<ref name=\"j139\">Jucha (2016), p. 139</ref> Howard's exclusion from the album has been lamented by many critics.<ref name=\"j331\">Jucha (2016), p. 331</ref><ref name=\"br\">Bray, Ryan. \"[https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/11/this-is-not-radio-clash-cut-the-crap-was-a-snapshot-of-a-legendary-bands-low-point/ This Is (Not) Radio Clash: ''Cut the Crap'' Was a Snapshot of a Legendary Band's Low Point]\". ''Consequence of Sound'', 7 November 2015. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190331042940/https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/11/this-is-not-radio-clash-cut-the-crap-was-a-snapshot-of-a-legendary-bands-low-point/ Archived] from the original on 31 March 2019. Retrieved 7 January 2018</ref> Knowles described him as an \"astonishingly powerful and prodigious\" drummer, and said that replacing him with electronic percussion was \"like replacing a [[Maserati]] with a [[Matchbox (brand)|Matchbox]]\".<ref name=\"Louder\" /> Regretting the decision, Strummer later vowed to never use a drum machine again.<ref name=\"mal\">Peachey, Mal. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/joe-strummer-clashback Joe Strummer: Clashback]\". ''International Musician and Recording World'', June 1988 \u2013 via [[Rock's Backpages]] {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe consensus among critics is that the album's production choices distract from otherwise strong songwriting by Strummer & Rhodes. Strummer's vocals are placed low in the mix, sometimes buried underneath electronic drums, synthetic keyboards and studio effects. The sound has often been described as muddy and cluttered due to multi-layered guitar tracks and backing vocals.<ref name=\"j319\">Jucha (2016), p. 319</ref> Many of the guitar overdubs have been considered unnecessary, given that Sheppard and White were both using [[Gibson Les Paul]]s and as such their sounds were tonally similar, and there was not significant variation in either their [[chord progression]]s or [[Ostinato|riffs]].<ref name=\"j319\" /> Rhodes's may have felt the need to fill each channel on the 24-track [[Mixing console|mixing desk]].<ref name=\"k252\" /><ref name=\"j329\">Jucha (2016), p. 329</ref> Author Gary Jucha summed up the album as having been produced by a manager whose musical ambitions were overstretched by a lack of experience.<ref name=\"j329\"/>\n\nThe overlaid vocals in several choruses give songs the feel of [[football chant]]s. These vocals have been harshly criticised, both because the effect seemed like [[Low culture|low-brow]] rabble-rousing<ref name=\"snow\">[[Mat Snow|Snow, Mat]]. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/clash-ithe-clash-give-em-enough-rope-london-calling-sandinista-combat-rock-cut-the-crapi Clash: ''The Clash''; ''Give 'Em Enough Rope''; ''London Calling''; ''Sandinista!''; ''Combat Rock''; ''Cut the Crap'']\". ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', June 1989 \u2013 via Rock's Backpages {{subscription required}}</ref> and from unfavourable comparisons with Jones's backing vocals on the band's earlier recordings.<ref>Jucha (2016), pp. 325\u2013326</ref> The drums are largely untreated with [[Effects unit|sound effects]] which left them sounding dull.{{refn|Howard described the final drum sound as coming across as like somebody \"hitting you over the head with a bag of [[ball bearing]]s.\"<ref name=\"GaCTC\" />|group=n}} Knowles suggested that adding [[reverb]] would have helped to create a more organic \"roomy\" sound, so the songs wouldn't feel \"so canned and phony\".<ref name=\"k252\" /> Against this, the live instrumentation is tight and cohesive. Each of the new recruits was a skilled musician,<ref name=\"k120\">Knowles (2003), p. 120</ref> and they had just come off a tour during which Rhodes had instructed them not to vary song structures or guitar leads between performances.<ref name=\"j319\" />\n\n===Side one===\n\"Dictator\", one of the earliest songs the new line-up played during their European tour, has been described as \"the poorest possible choice for the opening track\".<ref name=\"j330\">Jucha (2016), p. 330</ref> Music critic Lennox Samuels wrote in 1985 that the song is \"a messy mix of horns and a [[Pink Floyd]]-like voice-over\".<ref name=\"SL\">Samuels, Lennox. \"The Clash's New Album Proves Musically Apt, Politically Irrelevant\". ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'', 24 November 1985</ref> The album cut omits the live version's [[Bridge (music)|bridge]], changes the drum pattern, and replaces most of the guitar parts with [[Atonality|atonal]] synth lines.<ref name=\"k122\">Knowles (2003), p. 122</ref> The music journalist [[Martin Popoff]] described the lyrics' depiction of a Central American [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]] as \"surprisingly flat and dead\".<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 214</ref> The critic Mark Andersen described it as \"one of the less successful of the new tunes\".<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n{{Listen\n|filename = The Clash Dirty Punk.ogg\n|title = \"Dirty Punk\"\n|description = With its simple three-chord structure, \"Dirty Punk\" is the song that best represents Strummer and Rhodes's attempt to return the band to its punk rock origins.<ref name=\"vul\" />}}\nThe guitar-based \"Dirty Punk\" is built from a basic three-chord structure reminiscent of the band's [[The Clash (album)|self-titled debut album]]. White believed it should have been the lead single and could have been a hit.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Although generally well received,<ref name=\"br\" /> critics dismissed its synthetic drum sound as at odds with its back-to-basics sound.<ref name=\"p215\">Popoff (2018), p. 215</ref> The track was written just after the 1984 tour, when Strummer was attending to his terminally ill mother, so it is assumed that most of the lyrics were composed by Rhodes.<ref name=\"k122\" /> They are written from the point of view of a young punk who feels overshadowed by an older brother, but the story is told in such simple terms that it has been characterised as having \"Neanderthal lyrics that read as if a parody of a punk rock song\".<ref name=\"p215\" /> The relative simplicity of the lyrics were criticised by ''Vulture'', who described them as akin to \"[[Mick Jagger]]'s '80s output, bland clich\u00e9 for bland clich\u00e9.\"<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nThe rallying cry lyrics for \"We Are the Clash\" are sometimes seen as a defiant response to Jones's lawsuit. The album version differs substantially from both earlier live recordings and a 1983 demo. It is more polished, the lyrics have been changed in parts, the tempo has been slowed down, the bridge changed to an intro and the [[Call and response (music)|call-and-response]] chorus removed.<ref name=\"k122\" /> The song has received mixed reviews. It was criticised for its confused politics and thin sound, the guitar solo and back-in-the-mix vocal chants in particular lacking [[Bass (sound)|low-end]] frequencies. ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'' placed it last in its 2017 ranking of all 139 songs by the Clash from worst to best.<ref name=\"vul\" />{{refn|The ''Vulture'' article gave the bottom ranking, out of all the Clash's recorded songs, to seven tracks from the album. In order of weakness, those tracks are \"We Are the Clash\" (139), \"Play to Win\" (138), \"Fingerpoppin\" (137), \"Dictator\" (136), \"Dirty Punk\" (135), \"Are You Red..Y\" (134), and \"Movers and Shakers\" (133). \"This Is England\" ranked highest from the album at number 71.<ref name=\"vul\" />|group=n}} ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' took issue with the song's title, calling it \"an outright lie\" in light of the album's exclusion of both Jones and Headon.<ref name=\"RS\">Gehr, Richard; Greene, Andy; Harris, Keith; [[Maura Johnston|Johnston, Maura]]; Newman, Jason; Weingarten, Christopher R. \"[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/22-terrible-songs-by-great-artists-20160615/the-clash-we-are-the-clash-1985-20160615 22 Terrible Songs by Great Artists]\". ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 15 June 2016. [https://web.archive.org/web20190105094247/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/22-terrible-songs-by-great-artists-20368/the-clash-we-are-the-clash-1985-32110/ Archived] from the original on 5 January 2019. Retrieved 7 January 2017</ref> Music critic [[Tony Fletcher]] responded to the chant of \"We Are the Clash\" with the words \"No you're not{{nbsp}}... you're a pale imitation of [[Sham 69]] at the disco\".<ref name=\"Fletcher 2012\">Fletcher (2012)</ref> Clash biographer Chris Knowles disliked Rhodes's production but admired Strummer's songwriting, and considers the album version as a lost opportunity given that the song had been a \"killer\" live favourite.<ref name=\"k122\" />\n\n\"Are You Red..Y\" had originally been titled \"Are You Ready for War\".<ref name=\"A10\" /> \"Cool Under Heat\" is a reggae-ballad whose production choices have been criticised as cluttered and confused, several writers noting that its strong lyrics and tune are buried underneath a jumble of extraneous instruments and studio effects.<ref name=\"snow\" /> The guitar sound is especially flat and restrained by overly [[Dynamic range compression|compressed]] production.<ref name=\"snow\" /><ref name=\"p219\">Popoff (2018), p. 219</ref> Popoff found the album version inferior to the Clash's live versions that were reminiscent of [[the Pogues]], which the band had played on an early-1985 [[Street performance|busking]] tour.<ref name=\"p219\" />\n\nThe opening line of \"Movers and Shakers\"\u2014\"[[Casabianca (poem)|The boy stood]] in the burning slum\"\u2014was described by writer Sean Egan as \"a piece of unconscious self-parody that is quite probably the worst line ever to appear on a Clash record\".<ref name=\"e193\">Egan (2014), p. 193</ref> Fletcher called the lyric \"excruciating\" given that Strummer was then a successful rock star, but resigned himself with the observation \"fortunately for [him] not enough people were listening to be truly offended.\"<ref name=\"Fletcher 2012\"/> Apart from the lyrics, the song's drum programming has often been criticised as clunky, although the vocal melody has been praised.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\n===Side two===\n{{Listen\n|filename = The Clash This is England.ogg\n|title = \"This Is England\"\n|description = \"This Is England\" has been described as the Clash's last great song, even though it is emblematic of the album's maligned production characteristics, especially in its use of [[synthesizer]]s and chanted choruses.<ref name=\"vul\" />}}\n\n\"This Is England\" opens [[A-side and B-side|side two]], and is widely regarded as the album's stand-out track. It was released as the band's last single and Strummer himself called it the \"last great Clash song\".<ref name=\"still\">Spencer, Neil; Brown, James. \"[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/29/popandrock Why the Clash are still Rock Titans]\". ''[[The Guardian]]'', 29 October 2006. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190419212603/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/29/popandrock Archived] from the original on 19 April 2019. Retrieved 10 February 2019</ref><ref name=\"Popoff2018\">Popoff (2018), p. 226</ref> Co-written by Strummer and Rhodes, the song retains some of the reggae influences of their earlier albums.<ref name=\"RS\" /> Like \"We Are the Clash\", its chorus is sung in a football chant, but here it is higher in the mix. The guitars are also prominent, but the percussion is again supplied by a drum track.<ref name=\"c109\" /> Lennox described it as a \"tuneful, beautifully crafted overview of social decay in England, where political philosophies joust for hegemony while the country sinks into ignominious decline and millions of youths turn to [[Jobseeker's Allowance|the dole]].\"<ref name=\"SL\" /> The lyrics convey [[Social alienation|societal alienation]], lamenting the national mood in 1985; the line \"South Atlantic wind blows\" refers to the [[Falklands War]].<ref name=\"c109\">Cohen; Peacock (2017), p. 109</ref> Writing for ''Vulture'' in 2017, writer Bill Wyman described the song as the only successful track on ''Cut the Crap'', writing that \"the sound collage and the gentle, troubled synth lines undergird the song unerringly, and for once the group-shouted chorus, though still over-loud, conveys some wan meaning. This can't have been a good time for Strummer, and you can hear it in his voice, as he sings the fuck out of this.\"<ref name=\"vul\" />\n\nThe production of the live favourite \"Three Card Trick\" is relatively uncluttered, although it does contain programmed hand-claps.<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 228</ref> According to Jucha, the original song was good enough to have appeared on any Clash album, and he observed how Strummer had developed a real skill for writing mid-tempo songs.<ref>Jucha (2016), pp. 330\u2013331</ref> The track began as a straightforward punk song<ref name=\"aH\">Andersen; Heibutzki (2018), p. 147</ref> with a simple [[Ska]] bass line.\n\nWriter Mark Andersen described \"Fingerpoppin\" and \"Play to Win\" as essentially [[B-side]]-quality songs that should have been excluded from final track listing.<ref name=\"A9\" /> The latter is a sound collage which Popoff views as incoherent and basically \"noise, [[bongos]], and nonsensical fragmented conversations between Joe and Vince\".<ref name=\"p229\">Popoff (2018), p. 229</ref> Although the drums are considered too low in the mix, and the shouted choruses have been described as resembling [[Adam and the Ants]], its demo version is more favorably viewed,<ref name=\"p229\" /> mostly because of verses omitted in the final recording.<ref name=\"A9\" />\n\nThe penultimate track \"North and South\" was written and sung by Sheppard. It features a simple guitar line and uncluttered production, and has often been highlighted by critics as one of the album's strongest tracks.<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 231</ref> The album closer, \"Life Is Wild\", is the only track which had not been played live before. Its chorus, stylistically akin to the punk subgenre [[Oi!]],<ref name=\"k123\">Knowles (2003), p. 123</ref> was described by Popoff as a \"curious thumping party rocker that makes little sense\" and begged the question why a songwriter of Strummer's ability would write \"such banalities\".<ref>Popoff (2018), p. 232</ref>\n\n==Sleeve art and title==\nThe album cover was designed by Rhodes, Eddie King and Jules Balme, the art director for [[Stiff Records]],<ref>Eskelsen, Danny. \"[https://www.mojo4music.com/articles/3437/ian-durys-eyeball-pleasers Ian Dury\u2019s Eyeball Pleasers]\". ''[[Mojo (magazine)]]'', 24 July 2013. Retrieved 1 September 2019</ref> who had earlier overseen the covers for ''Sandinista!'' and ''Combat Rock''.<ref>Garcia (2012), First Night Back in London, 332</ref> It shows a punk wearing a [[Mohawk hairstyle|mohawk]], black leather jacket and sunglasses\u2014all markers of 1980s [[punk fashion]]. The image is rendered so that the portrait looks like a poster glued to a wall. A similar image appears on the [[Single (music)|7-inch]] release of \"This Is England\".<ref name=\"e190\">Egan (2014), p. 190</ref> A lithograph of the cover is held by the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York, who attribute an \"unknown designer\".<ref>\"[https://www.moma.org/collection/works/156171 The Clash, Cut the Crap, 1985]\". [[Museum of Modern Art]]. Retrieved 22 June 2019</ref>\n\nReflecting the chaos surrounding the recording sessions, and as an ironic reference to a [[Complete Control|track]] from the Jones era, the album's working title was ''Out of Control'',<ref name=\"j334\">Jucha (2016), p. 334</ref> until Rhodes, without consulting the band, changed it shortly before its release. He took the words \"cut the crap\" from a scene in the 1981 [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] film ''[[Mad Max 2]]'', when [[Mel Gibson]]'s character, [[Max Rockatansky]], insists on driving the oil tanker on which the settlers' survival depends: \"Come on, cut the crap. I'm the best chance you've got.\"<ref name=\"j328\">Jucha (2016), p. 328</ref> According to Jucha, the sentiment reflected the band's view of themselves in the mid-1980s: \"the back-to-basics Clash, Round two\u2014like the initial band of UK punk rockers\u2014were going to eradicate the meaningless [[New Romantic]] bands dominating the British pop world. They were 'the best chance [the world's] got'.\"<ref name=\"j329\">Jucha (2016), p. 329</ref> Nevertheless, the title is widely disliked; Jucha described it as \"awful\".<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n==Reception==\nBy the time the new \"Mark II\" lineup released ''Cut the Crap'' on 4&nbsp;November 1985, they were an accomplished live band, and had written and performed several songs that would appear on the final album; a few had been live favourites. On the strength of their recent gigs, the UK press were optimistically waiting for the album's release. Epic Records anticipated that both the three-year gap since ''Combat Rock'' along with their updated sound, would result in critical acclaim and high sales.<ref name=\"A9\" /> In the promotional lead up, Strummer told journalist [[Richard Cook (journalist)|Richard Cook]] that he was not going release any new material until he knew it could \"last ten years\".<ref name=\"j329\" /> Most critics and fans were disappointed on its release\u2014especially with its sound and production values, and the omission of stand-out live tracks \"In the Pouring Rain\" and \"Ammunition\" (usually titled \"Jericho\" in contemporary [[bootleg recording]]s).<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n''Cut the Crap'' sold poorly compared to earlier Clash releases, reaching just number 16 in the UK charts and number 88 in the US.<ref name=\"e190\" /> Contemporary reviews of lead single \"This Is England\" were negative and, upon the album's release, British and American critics alike generally viewed the album in an unfavourable light. ''[[Melody Maker]]'' and ''[[NME]]'' both published sharply negative reviews, the latter of which was titled \"No Way, Jose\" in sarcastic reference to the \"Jose Unidos\" production credit.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Reflecting the critical consensus at the time, Mike Laye\u2014a writer, photographer and Clash insider\u2014said the band should \"just drop the 'Cut' from the title, because to me this [is] crap.\"<ref name=\"GaCTC\">Garcia (2012), Cut the Crap, 2420</ref> [[David Fricke]] panned the album in ''Rolling Stone'', saying \"too much of ''Cut the Crap'' is Strummer's angst running on automatic, superficially ferocious but ultimately stiff and unconvincing.\"<ref name=\"df\" /> [[Robert Christgau]], a longtime champion of the Clash in the US, offered only restrained praise in a ''[[The Village Voice|Village Voice]]'' review that alluded to the negative word-of-mouth and summarized most of the album as \"stubborn and jolly and elegiac and together\".<ref name=\"A9\" /><ref name=\"Christgau\">[[Robert Christgau|Christgau, Robert]]. \"[http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1b-86.php Christgau's Consumer Guide]\". ''[[The Village Voice]]'', 28 January 1986. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190105200901/http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1b-86.php Archived] from the original on 5 January 2019. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref> Music journalist Richard Cromelin found the album's uptempo songs less effective than those on earlier Clash records, but concluded that Strummer's singing is compelling and \"This Is England\" and \"North and South\" make the record \"more than passable\".<ref>Cromelin, Richard. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-17/entertainment/ca-6896_1_joe-strummer Album Review: Less Slash From The New Clash]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 17 November 1985. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160307092209/http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-17/entertainment/ca-6896_1_joe-strummer Archived] from the original on 7 March 2016. Retrieved 10 September 2015</ref>\n\nThe absence of Jones and Headon led many to regard it as a Joe Strummer solo album\u2014an impression further solidified by Simonon's involvement being limited only to the pre-production stage. Its shortcomings were often attributed to Strummer's evident disillusionment with the group and the fact that he was grieving over the recent deaths of his parents.<ref>Parker, Alan. \"Rebel Truce: The History of the Clash\", Part Six. [[Sky Arts]], 2010. 5:20</ref> Joe Sasfy of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that the \"revised version of the Clash sounds like a pale and ghostly facsimile of this once-great band\"; he disliked the {{nowrap|\"[tiresome]}} garbled choruses\" and he found that \"Strummer's attempt to enliven them with horn charts creates an ungainly mess of a sound.\"<ref>Morse, Steve. \"Sasfy, Joe. \"Rants Without Raves; Political Pap From the Revised Clash\". ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 21 November 1985</ref> Music critic Liam Lacey was dismissive overall, writing that the \"rebel polemics sound dated, and the songwriting is occasionally banal\", but concluded that, given the strength of \"This Is England\", \"in its cheesily self-aggrandizing way, the new Clash may be on to something.\"<ref>Lacey, Liam. \"Inside the Sleeve\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 21 November 1985</ref> Similarly, Richard Defendorf of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' described the record as a \"sometimes embarrassingly anachronistic{{nbsp}}... attempt to rekindle the Clash's punkish, militant energy.\"<ref>Defendorf, Richard. \"The Clash\". ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'', 24 November 1985</ref>\n\n''Cut the Crap'' has been favourably reevaluated in some retrospective reviews, many praising Strummer's songwriting and vocal performance. For example, the writer [[Jon Savage]] praised the album in his influential 1991 book on the history of punk, ''England's Dreaming'',<ref name=\"k123\" />  highlighting the \"innovative use of rap rhythm and atmosphere\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Savage |first1=Jon |title=England's Dreaming |date=2005 |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=London |isbn=0571227201 |page=590 |edition=Main}}</ref> Yet its reputation as a failure, or at least as a lost opportunity, has endured. In 2002, [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] described \"This Is England\" as \"surprisingly nervy\" on a record that, in his view, is otherwise \"formulaic, tired punk rock that doesn't have the aggression or purpose of early Clash records\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Joe-Strummer.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1|Strummer in concert, supporting [[the Pogues]], Japan, 1992]]\nStrummer was depressed by both the album's sound and critical appraisal. Asked in 1986 how the reviews affected him, he replied: \"Sure I read [them] but I didn't need them to tell me. It was like when you're younger and you're trying to make a date with a girl but she won't have any of it. You keep going back, trying to fool yourself that this time will be better.\"<ref name=\"NME\">Martin, Gavin. \"[https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/joe-strummer-good-ol-joe Joe Strummer: Good Ol' Joe]\". ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'', 26 July 1986 \u2013 via Rock's Backpages {{subscription required}}</ref> He was particularly upset that people had thought the \"Jose Unidos\" pseudonym credited as a producer was him rather than Rhodes, and said \"it wouldn't have been so bad if Bernie had just got the blame but that was unbearable.\"<ref name=\"NME\" /> The album was cited by a several contemporary reviewers as symptomatic of why punk rock had failed. Strummer said in 1988: \"To someone who says I was{{nbsp}}... 'the spokesman for your generation and you fucked it up', I say yeah, but we tried.\"<ref>D'Ambrosio (2012)</ref> He admitted that he had undertaken the project in part to prove that Jones hadn't been the Clash's only songwriter.<ref name=\"j332\">Jucha (2016), p. 332</ref> White believes the album's commercial failure was caused by a combination of Strummer's hubris and Rhodes's ambitions, both of which led to apathy and discontent with the band.<ref name=\"j334\" /> The Clash's standing did not fully recover until Strummer's work with [[the Pogues]] on the ''[[Straight to Hell (film)|Straight to Hell]]'' soundtrack in 1987.<ref name=\"e199\">Egan (2014), p. 199</ref>\n\nEpic Records intended a tour shortly after the release, but there were practical issues that made this impossible. Foremost, Strummer was in exile in Spain and refusing to partake in promoting the record; he had even threatened to take legal action to prevent its release.<ref name=\"NME\" /><ref>Egan (2014), p. 116</ref> After their treatment during the album's recording, White and Howard were bitter, demotivated and reluctant to engage with the material. Finally, given that Rhodes had so heavily revised the original songs and utilised so many samples and studio effects, he and Strummer disagreed on how the tracks should be played live.<ref name=\"A9\" /> Epic had planned a highly produced and expensive [[music video|video]] for \"This is England\", with a view for a still more expensive version to promote its US release. The idea was shelved when neither Strummer nor Simonon turned up for the shooting.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nStrummer dissolved the band that October, giving each of the remaining members a thousand pounds each as [[Severance package|severance payments]]. Howard told him, somewhat bitterly, that \"this is where it got you\" for following Bernie's lead\u2014a statement to which he agreed.<ref name=\"Louder\" /> White suggested that he either publish an open letter of retraction in the weekly music press and [[tabloid journalism|tabloids]],{{refn|Howard said that Strummer took his advice and wrote up a press release titled \"Crap Cutting Commencing\", detailing in wartime language how the band had been hoodwinked by a political dictator, i.e., Rhodes. The piece was never published.<ref name=\"GJS\" />|group=n}} or re-record the album without Rhodes, but Strummer demurred.<ref name=\"GJS\">Garcia (2012), Joe Splits, 2462</ref>\n\nUnder pressure from Epic to get the band out on tour to promote the album, Rhodes asked the three remaining members to consider hiring a new singer, rationalising that \"The Clash has always been an idea{{nbsp}}... Now, how to take that idea to the next level!\"{{refn|[[Vic Godard]] believes that Rhodes was by then trying to take over the Clash's brand name, and would \"have a version out there now touring\" many years after Strummer left, if he could have legally managed it.<ref name=\"GSA\" />|group=n}} They briefly considered the possibility, Rhodes suggesting Simonon, a position the bassist resolutely refused<ref name=\"GSA\">Garcia (2012), Singer Auditions, 2491</ref> until Strummer officially disbanded the group.<ref name=\"A10\" /> Having disowned the album, \"Three Card Trick\" was the only track Strummer played live during his solo career.<ref name=\"j332\" />\n\n''Cut the Crap'' was remastered and re-released in Europe in the mid-2000s, with the bonus track \"Do It Now\". The reissue was unannounced and not promoted. It came after the rest of the band's catalogue had been reissued between December 1999 and January 2000 in the US. The album was not mentioned in the Clash documentary ''[[The Clash: Westway to the World]]'' (2000) and was acknowledged only briefly in the official illustrated biography ''The Clash'' (2008), not receiving an overview as the first five albums had. The album has been omitted from many Clash compilations, box sets and reissues, including ''[[The Story of the Clash, Volume 1|The Story of the Clash]]'' (1988), ''[[Clash on Broadway]]'' (1991), ''[[The Singles (1991 The Clash album)|The Singles]]'' (1991), ''[[Sound System (album)|Sound System]]'' (2013) and ''[[5 Album Studio Set]]'' (2013).{{refn|\"This Is England\" was included in ''[[The Essential Clash]]'' (2003) and [[The Singles (2007 The Clash album)|the 2007 box set reissue of ''The Singles'']]''.|group=n}}<ref name=\"Kott\">Kott, Crispin. \"[https://www.popmatters.com/120558-i-found-a-reason-the-velvet-undergrounds-lost-chapter-2496163399.html The Velvet Underground's Lost Chapter]\". ''[[PopMatters]]'', 11 February 2010. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190618194508/https://www.popmatters.com/120558-i-found-a-reason-the-velvet-undergrounds-lost-chapter-2496163399.html Archived] from the original on 18 June 2019. Retrieved 18 June 2019</ref> According to Simonon, ''Cut the Crap'' was excluded because it was not seen as a real Clash album, as neither Jones nor Headon were involved.<ref name=\"A10\" />\n\nDirector [[Shane Meadows]] in 2006 used the title ''This is England'' for his [[This Is England|movie and TV show]] centering on young [[skinhead]]s and [[Oi!|Oi! punks]] in England in the 1980s, in reference to the ''Cut the Crap'' song.<ref name=\"still\" />\n\n==Track listing==\nThe liner notes credit all songs to Strummer and Rhodes.<ref name=\"j329\" />\n\n'''Side one'''\n# \"Dictator\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:00\n# \"Dirty Punk\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:11\n# \"We Are the Clash\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:02\n# \"Are You Red..Y\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n# \"Cool Under Heat\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:21\n# \"Movers and Shakers\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n\n'''Side two'''\n# \"[[This Is England (song)|This Is England]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:49\n# \"Three Card Trick\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:09\n# \"Play to Win\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:06\n# \"Fingerpoppin'\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:25\n# \"North and South\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:32\n# \"Life Is Wild\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:39\n\n==Personnel==\n'''The Clash'''<ref>''Cut the Crap'' liner notes. [[Epic Records]], 4 November 1985</ref>\n* [[Joe Strummer]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], guitars\n* [[Nick Sheppard]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, lead vocals on \"North and South\"\n* [[Vince White]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional guitars on \"Do It Now\"\n* [[Paul Simonon]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass on some tracks (including \"Do It Now\")\n* [[Pete Howard]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums on \"Do It Now\"\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n* [[Bernard Rhodes|Bernie Rhodes]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum machine]] programming\n* [[Norman Watt-Roy]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass guitar<ref name=\"KentOL\">{{cite web |url= https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dover/news/complete-control-194632/|publisher=[[KM Group|Kent Online]] |title=Nick 'Topper' Headon, former Clash drummer, with The Blockheads at The Booking Hall, Dover|accessdate=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n* Michael Fayne&nbsp;\u2013 drum machines, vocals on \"Play to Win\"\n* Hermann Weindorf&nbsp;\u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[synthesizer]]s\n\n'''Production'''\n* Bernie Rhodes&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|producer]] (credited as \"Jose Unidos\")<ref>Knowles (2003), p. 77</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Chart\n! Position\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1985\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Swedish Albums Chart<ref name=\"sweden\">\"[http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Clash Discography The Clash]\". SwedishCharts.com. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180914022853/https://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Clash Archived] from the original on 14 September 2018. Retrieved 26 October 2008</ref>\n| 30\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | UK Albums Chart<ref name=\"e190\" />\n| 16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | US ''Billboard'' 200<ref name=\"USCharts\">\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160614215053/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-clash-mn0000075747/awards The Clash: Charts & Awards]\". AllMusic. Archived from [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-clash-mn0000075747/awards the original] on 14 June 2016. Retrieved 4 January 2019</ref>\n| 88\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Andersen, Mark; Heibutzki, Ralph. ''We Are the Clash: Reagan, Thatcher, and the Last Stand of a Band That Mattered''. New York: Akashic Books, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-6177-5293-3}}\n* Cohen, Samuel; Peacock, James. ''The Clash Takes on the World: Transnational Perspectives on the Only Band that Matters''. London: Bloomsbury, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5013-1733-0}}\n* D'Ambrosio, Antonino. ''Let Fury Have the Hour: Joe Strummer, Punk, and the Movement that Shook the World''. Seattle, WA: Amazon Media, 2012. {{ASIN|B06XKC3PXQ}}\n* Garcia, Danny. ''The Rise and Fall of the Clash''. London: Thin Man Press, 2012. {{ISBN|9780956247322}}\n* Gilbert, Pat. ''Passion Is a Fashion: The Real Story of the Clash''. Boston, MA: Da Capo Press, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-3068-1434-1}}\n* Egan, Sean. ''The Clash: The Only Band That Mattered''. London: Rowman & Littlefield, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-8875-3}}\n* [[Tony Fletcher|Fletcher, Tony]]. ''The Clash: The Music That Matters''. London,  Omnibus Press, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-7803-8303-3}}\n* Jucha, Gary. ''The Clash FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the Clash City Rockers''. Milwaukee, WI: Backbeat Books, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-4803-6450-9}}\n* Knowles, Chris. ''Clash City Showdown''. London: PageFree, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1-5896-1138-2}}\n* [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Larkin, Colin]]. ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''. London: Omnibus Press, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-8571-2595-8}}\n* [[Dave Marsh|Marsh, Dave]]. ''The Heart of Rock & Soul: The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever Made''. London: Penguin, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-1401-2108-7}}\n* [[Kris Needs|Needs, Chris]]. ''Joe Strummer and the Legend of the Clash''. London: Plexus, 2005. {{ISBN|978-0-8596-5348-0}}\n* [[Martin Popoff|Popoff, Martin]]. ''The Clash: All the Albums, All the Songs''. London: Voyageur Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-0-7603-5934-1}}\n* [[Chris Salewicz|Salewicz, Chris]]. ''[[Redemption Song: The Ballad of Joe Strummer]]''. London: Faber and Faber, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-5712-1178-4}}\n* [[Jon Savage|Savage, Jon]]. ''England's Dreaming: The Sex Pistols and Punk Rock''. London: Faber and Faber, 1991. {{ISBN|978-0-3122-8822-8}}\n* [[Rob Sheffield|Sheffield, Rob]]. \"The Clash\". ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (4th ed.). New York: Fireside, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-7432-0169-8}}\n* [[David Quantick|Quantick, David]]. \"The Clash\" (Kill Your Idols series). London: Unanimous, 2000. {{ISBN|978-1-9033-1803-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{The Clash}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cut The Crap}}\n[[Category:1985 albums]]\n[[Category:The Clash albums]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "INEEDASEXSLAVE", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cut_the_Crap"}
{"title_page": "Abhilash Pillai", "text_new": "{{short description|Director (b. 1969)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date= February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Abhilash Pillai\n| image = Dr Abhilash Pillai pic.jpg\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Abhilash Pillai\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|05|17|df=y}}\n| native_name_lang = ml\n| birth_place = [[Thiruvanathapuram]], [[Kerala]]\n| alma_mater = [[National School of Drama]], [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n| occupation = [[Theatre director]], [[Scenographer]], [[Academic]]\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Abhilash Pillai''' (born 17 May 1969) is an Indian [[Theatre|theater]] director, both [[Pedagogy|pedagogue]] and scholar of contemporary [[Theatre of India|Indian theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/theatre-nsd-abhilash-pillai-delhi-art-5552982/|title=Director Abhilash Pillai on exploring the mind of an artist in Blindside|date=24 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/new-act-on-stage/article2697578.ece|title=New act on stage|last=Paul|first=G. S.|date=8 December 2011|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAbhilash Pillai was born on 17 May 1969 at [[Thiruvananthapuram]] to S.R.K. Pillai and Sarada Pillai. In 1991, he completed his Bachelor of Theatre Arts from The School of Drama, [[University of Calicut]] and secured third rank. He also completed a three-year Postgraduate Diploma in Dramatics with a specialization in Design and Direction from the [[National School of Drama]] (NSD), [[New Delhi]], with distinction in 1994. He then obtained a two-year Diploma in Theater Production and Stage Management with honors from the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA), [[London]] in 1998. He also did a one-year intensive training in advanced theater direction in association with eminent directors in the [[Orange Tree Theatre|Orange Tree Theater]], United Kingdom during 1998 and 1999 and attained his PhD from [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]], [[New Delhi]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatrefestivalkerala.com/cgi-sys/suspendedpage.cgi|title=Account Suspended|website=theatrefestivalkerala.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDr. Pillai began his career in theater as an [[art director]] at the Abhinaya Theatre and Research Centre, [[Thiruvananthapuram]] in [[Kerala]]. He worked there from September 1999 to April 2001. Later, he was appointed as an Assistant Professor at [[National School of Drama]], New Delhi and rose to become the Dean of Academics from July 2008 and June 2011. Presently, he is a visiting faculty/play director at many universities in [[India]] and abroad. He is also the Chairman of Arnav Art Trust since 2011 and a committee member of ''Natrang Pratishtan'', [[New Delhi]]. He currently works as the Associate Professor at [[National School of Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/abhilash-pillais-play-lorem-ipsum-review/article7232011.ece|title=Destination unknown|first=Diwan Singh|last=Bajeli|date=21 May 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegedunia.com/college/5510-national-school-of-drama-nsd-new-delhi|title=National School of Drama \u2013 [NSD], New Delhi|website=Collegedunia}}</ref>\n\n== Major directorial works ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year !! Title !! [[Dramaturge]] !! Production Company !! Premier Show\n|-\n| 2017||''The Night Side of Life''|| Sasikumar. V || Ex-Theatre Asia || [[National Theater and Concert Hall, Taipei]], [[Taiwan]] \n|-\n| 2016||''Talatum''|| Sasikumar. V || Tempest with a Twist by Sasikumar. V combining Theatre actors & circus performers in a circus tent ||  Serendipity Art Trust,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/yXPVL1s6DhFInAsqyjrffL/Lounge-loves-A-multidisciplinary-Tempest-from-Kerala.html|title=Lounge loves: A multi-disciplinary 'Tempest' from Kerala|first=Avantika|last=Bhuyan|date=18 November 2016|website=Mint}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/theatre/A-tent-filled-with-Shakespeare%E2%80%99s-magic/article16907310.ece|title=A tent filled with Shakespeare\u2019s magic|first=Vikram|last=Phukan|date=20 December 2016|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitalgoa.com/theatre-finds-a-new-way-of-expression-through-talatum-a-contemporary-adaptation-of-shakespeares-tempest/|title=Theatre finds a new way of expression through Talatum: A Contemporary adaptation of Shakespeare\u2019s Tempest \u2013 Digital Goa|first=Team Digital|last=Goa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/goa/Shakespeares-Tempest-to-get-a-circus-style-makeover/articleshow/56073862.cms|title=Shakespeare\u2019s Tempest to get a circus-style makeover \u2013 Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016||''Radio Freedom''||[[Rajesh Tailang]]||[[National School of Drama]]  || [[National School of Drama]] \n|-\n| 2015||''Lorem Ipsum''|| [[Rajesh Tailang]] || [[National School of Drama]]  || [[National School of Drama]] \n|-\n| 2014||''VIVID''|| Combining two scripts by [[Mahesh Elkunchwar]] & [[Vijay Tendulkar]]||[[National School of Drama]]  || [[National School of Drama]] \n|-\n| 2013||''Avudai''|| A performance based on Kanchana Natrajan's book 'Transgressing Boundaries<nowiki>''</nowiki> ||[[Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts]] New Delhi || [[Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts]] \n|-\n| 2012||''Kalo Sonakhari (Black Orchid)''|| A non-verbal play with the Repertory company of NSD Sikkim Centre || NSD Sikkim Centre || NSD Sikkim Centre\n|-\n| 2012||''Clowns & Clouds''||  || [[National School of Drama]]  || [[National School of Drama]] \n|-\n| 2009||''ara Ek Bada Basheer (A Bit Big Basheer)''||Rajesh Tailang combining seven works of Malayalam Novelist [[Vaikom Muhammad Basheer|Vaikom Muhammed Basheer]] in Hindi ||[[National School of Drama]]  || [[Natio