{"title_page": "Black Owl", "text_new": "{{for|the bird species|greater sooty owl}}\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| character_name = Black Owl \n| image     = File:Black Owl in Prize Comics no2.jpg\n| caption   = The Black Owl, 1940\n| publisher = Prize Publications\n| debut     = ''Prize Comics'' #2 (April 1940)\n| creators  = \n| alter_ego = Doug Danville\n| full_name =\n| species   = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| partners  = <!-- optional -->\n| supports  = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases   = K the Unknown\n| powers    = None\n}}\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| character_name = Black Owl\n| image     = \n| caption   = \n| publisher = Prize Publications\n| debut     = ''Prize Comics'' #34 (Sept. 1943)\n| creators  = \n| alter_ego = Walt Walters\n| full_name =\n| species   = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| partners  = Yank & Doodle\n| supports  = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases   = <!-- optional -->\n| powers    = None\n}}\n'''The Black Owl''' is the name of two fictional [[superhero]] characters. Both appeared in the [[Crestwood Publications|Prize Publications]] title ''Prize Comics'' in the 1940s.\n\n==Publication history==\nIn 1940, Prize Publications, which was already established as a producer of [[pulp magazine]]s, began publishing superhero comic books with a new title, ''Prize Comics''. The first issue featured \u201cK the Unknown,\u201d whose name was changed to the Black Owl in issue #2 (April 1940).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |title=The Black Owl |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/blackowl.htm |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\nEverbody wanna be famous\nIn issues #7-9, the Black Owl stories were written and drawn by legends-to-be [[Joe Simon]] and [[Jack Kirby]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mendryk |first1=Harry |title=Simon and Kirby's Black Owl |url=https://kirbymuseum.org/blogs/simonandkirby/archives/2468 |website=The Kirby Museum |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> This was Kirby's first superhero feature.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Benton |first1=Mike |title=Superhero Comics of the Golden Age: The Illustrated History |date=1992 |publisher=Taylor Publishing Company |location=Dallas |isbn=0-87833-808-X |pages=76-77 |url=https://archive.org/details/superherocomicso0000bent/page/76 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn issue #24 (Oct. 1942), the Black Owl was part of a large, one-time crossover story called \"Utter Failure!!\" in which a group of heroes, including [[Yank & Doodle]], Doctor Frost and the [[Green Lama]], fought together against [[Frankenstein's monster]]. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Glut |first1=Donald F. |title=The Frankenstein Archive Essays on the Monster, the Myth, the Movies, and More |date=2015 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786480692 |page=171 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Frankenstein_Archive/RLeJCgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=the%20black%20owl |chapter=Frankenstein in Four Colors |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn issue #34 (Sept. 1943), the identity of the Black Owl was passed on from Doug Danville to Walt Walters, a character who was already established as the father of [[Yank & Doodle]]; the two series were merged.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Kurt |last2=Thomas |first2=Roy |title=American Comic Book Chronicles: 1940-1944 |date=2019 |publisher=TwoMorrows Publishing |isbn=978-1605490892 |page=262 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/American_Comic_Book_Chronicles_1940_1944/S12mDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22the%20Black%20Owl%22 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> In issue #64 (June 1947), the father was sidelined by means of a bullet, and the focus was almost entirely on Yank & Doodle.\n\nWith issue #69 (April 1948), ''Prize Comics'' became ''Prize Comics Western'', and everything that didn't fit the new [[Western (genre)|Western]] format \u2014 including Yank, Doodle, and the Black Owl \u2014 was discarded. The three characters have since fallen into the [[public domain]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn 2008, the online [[superhero fiction]] site [[Metahuman Press]] debuted the series ''[[Living Legends (fiction)|Living Legends]]'' which featured the first Black Owl as part of its cast. The second Black Owl appeared briefly in ''[[Fantastic Comics]]'' #24, the first issue of the [[Next Issue Project]]. In issue #6 of ''[[Project Superpowers]]'', the Black Owl and Yank & Doodle were included in a two-page layout of [[Golden Age of Comic Books|Golden Age]] character sketches; In the one-shot ''Project Superpowers: Chapter Two Prelude'', it was stated that the three of them would appear in the second volume of this comic title, and that the Black Owl (which one is not yet known) would be transformed into a living [[black hole]].\n\n==Fictional biography==\n\n===Doug Danville===\nIn 1940, Doug Danville, being a bored and wealthy playboy, decided to add meaning to his seemingly pointless life by fighting the criminal element hand to hand. Originally calling himself \u201cK the Unknown,\u201d he quickly changed his identity to that of the Black Owl. His original outfit was a [[tuxedo]] and an [[owl]] mask, but he soon switched to a blue and red costume.\n\nAt one point during his career, the Black Owl fought alongside The [[Green Lama]], [[Yank & Doodle]], and several other heroes to defeat [[Frankenstein's monster]].\n\nFinally, after more than three years of crimefighting, Danville decided to do something even more meaningful with his life; he joined the [[United States Army|army]] and fought in [[World War II]]. Before leaving, he passed on the costume and identity of the Black Owl to Walt Walters. Whatever became of Danville after the war is not yet known.\n\n===Walt Walters===\nWalt Walters was already indirectly connected to superheroing; his twin sons, Rick and Dick, were the costumed heroes Yank & Doodle. After Walt took up the mantle of the Black Owl in 1943, he and his sons worked as a team, with Rick and Dick essentially being his sidekicks.\n\nIn 1947, Walt suffered a bullet wound and found himself reconsidering being an active superhero; from that point on, he simply served as an adviser to Yank & Doodle.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/blackowl.htm The Black Owl] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6agkuZxBV?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/blackowl.htm Archived] from the original on August 10, 2015.\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/ynkdoodl.htm Yank and Doodle] at Don Markstein's Toonopedia. [https://www.webcitation.org/6agl69roO?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/ynkdoodl.htm Archived] from the original on August 10, 2015.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080821032113/http://metahumanpress.com/metahumanpress/Legends/index.html Living Legends at MetahumanPress.com]\n*{{comicbookdb|character|19413|Black Owl (1)}}\n*{{comicbookdb|character|19414|Black Owl (2)}}\n*{{comicbookdb|title|118918|The Next Issue Project #1}}\n*{{comicbookdb|issue|141392|Project Superpowers #6}}\n*{{comicbookdb|issue|147219|Project Superpowers: Chapter Two Prelude}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Owl}}\n[[Category:Dynamite Entertainment characters]]\n[[Category:Golden Age superheroes]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1940]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the bird species|greater sooty owl}}\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| character_name = Black Owl \n| image     = File:Black Owl in Prize Comics no2.jpg\n| caption   = The Black Owl, 1940\n| publisher = Prize Publications\n| debut     = ''Prize Comics'' #2 (April 1940)\n| creators  = \n| alter_ego = Doug Danville\n| full_name =\n| species   = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| partners  = <!-- optional -->\n| supports  = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases   = K the Unknown\n| powers    = None\n}}\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| character_name = Black Owl\n| image     = \n| caption   = \n| publisher = Prize Publications\n| debut     = ''Prize Comics'' #34 (Sept. 1943)\n| creators  = \n| alter_ego = Walt Walters\n| full_name =\n| species   = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| partners  = Yank & Doodle\n| supports  = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases   = <!-- optional -->\n| powers    = None\n}}\n'''The Black Owl''' is the name of two fictional [[superhero]] characters. Both appeared in the [[Crestwood Publications|Prize Publications]] title ''Prize Comics'' in the 1940s.\n\n==Publication history==\nIn 1940, Prize Publications, which was already established as a producer of [[pulp magazine]]s, began publishing superhero comic books with a new title, ''Prize Comics''. The first issue featured \u201cK the Unknown,\u201d whose name was changed to the Black Owl in issue #2 (April 1940).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |title=The Black Owl |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/blackowl.htm |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn issues #7-9, the Black Owl stories were written and drawn by legends-to-be [[Joe Simon]] and [[Jack Kirby]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mendryk |first1=Harry |title=Simon and Kirby's Black Owl |url=https://kirbymuseum.org/blogs/simonandkirby/archives/2468 |website=The Kirby Museum |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> This was Kirby's first superhero feature.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Benton |first1=Mike |title=Superhero Comics of the Golden Age: The Illustrated History |date=1992 |publisher=Taylor Publishing Company |location=Dallas |isbn=0-87833-808-X |pages=76-77 |url=https://archive.org/details/superherocomicso0000bent/page/76 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn issue #24 (Oct. 1942), the Black Owl was part of a large, one-time crossover story called \"Utter Failure!!\" in which a group of heroes, including [[Yank & Doodle]], Doctor Frost and the [[Green Lama]], fought together against [[Frankenstein's monster]]. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Glut |first1=Donald F. |title=The Frankenstein Archive Essays on the Monster, the Myth, the Movies, and More |date=2015 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786480692 |page=171 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Frankenstein_Archive/RLeJCgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=the%20black%20owl |chapter=Frankenstein in Four Colors |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn issue #34 (Sept. 1943), the identity of the Black Owl was passed on from Doug Danville to Walt Walters, a character who was already established as the father of [[Yank & Doodle]]; the two series were merged.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Kurt |last2=Thomas |first2=Roy |title=American Comic Book Chronicles: 1940-1944 |date=2019 |publisher=TwoMorrows Publishing |isbn=978-1605490892 |page=262 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/American_Comic_Book_Chronicles_1940_1944/S12mDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22the%20Black%20Owl%22 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> In issue #64 (June 1947), the father was sidelined by means of a bullet, and the focus was almost entirely on Yank & Doodle.\n\nWith issue #69 (April 1948), ''Prize Comics'' became ''Prize Comics Western'', and everything that didn't fit the new [[Western (genre)|Western]] format \u2014 including Yank, Doodle, and the Black Owl \u2014 was discarded. The three characters have since fallen into the [[public domain]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn 2008, the online [[superhero fiction]] site [[Metahuman Press]] debuted the series ''[[Living Legends (fiction)|Living Legends]]'' which featured the first Black Owl as part of its cast. The second Black Owl appeared briefly in ''[[Fantastic Comics]]'' #24, the first issue of the [[Next Issue Project]]. In issue #6 of ''[[Project Superpowers]]'', the Black Owl and Yank & Doodle were included in a two-page layout of [[Golden Age of Comic Books|Golden Age