is superior sends him to Manila to unmask a powerful syndicate, 1st Lt. Jamal Razul ([[Fernando Poe Jr.]]), an undercover cop, takes a job posing as the bodyguard of an influential police major. But when the syndicate's cronies uncover his motives, Jamal finds himself running for his life. Meanwhile, his Muslim faith has him doing everything in his power to avenge the deaths of two innocent teens who helped him conceal his true identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/magnum_357|title=MAGNUM .357|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=17 January 2006|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n1st Lt. Jamal Razul ([[Fernando Poe Jr.]]) is a Muslim undercover Philippine Constabulary officer, who is sent to Manila to help curb the runaway crime rate. Convinced of his abilities as an undercover agent, he is summoned by Lt. Col. Castro to assist in unmasking the head of a big and vicious syndicate.\n\nIn Manila, he is able to track down the warehouse where the syndicate drops off their illicit goods, but a firefight ensues. Razul survives and his anonymity still maintained, but is left wounded. Fortunately for Razul, two young boys (Christopher Paloma and Michael Roberts) found him and, along with their grandfather ([[Max Alvarado]]) and Razul's landlady (Vivian Foz), nurse him back to health.\n\nAfter ascertaining the identity of one of the syndicate's high-ranking official, Frankie ([[Paquito Diaz]]), he applies for work as a hired hand in the syndicate. However, before Razul could begin work, he was exposed as an undercover agent and the roles are suddenly reversed - Razul now becoming the hunted instead of the hunter. Lt. Col. Castro advices him to return to Mindanao, but the syndicate would rather have him dead as he has already caused considerable damage to be let go scot free. Failing to silence him, they turned their ire on the two kids that helped him. They kill the two boys.\n\nThe killing strikes a sensitive chord in Razul, the Muslim in him surfaces and vows revenge on all the remaining members of the gang. He picks apart the members of the gang one by one until all that is left is Frankie. With the barrel of the eponymous [[.357 Magnum|Magnum .357]] pointed at him, Frankie reveals the stronghold of the syndicate in  [[Sta. Cruz, Manila]]. While surveiling the area, Razul discovers that the syndicate's protector is a senior official in the Philippine Constabulary, Capt. Rios ([[Eddie Garcia]]), who has up to that point assumed the leadership of the syndicate after eliminating the syndicate's former head ([[Jaime Fabregas|Jimmy Fabregas]]). Another firefight ensues which ends in a showdown between Razul and Rios, with the former emerging the survivor. Razul, having finished his mission and avenging the boys that have become unwitting victims in his mission, thanks ''[[Allah]]''.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col begin}}\n*[[Fernando Poe Jr.]] as 1st Lt. Jamal Razul\n*[[Eddie Garcia]] as Capt. Rios\n*Vivian Foz as Dess\n*[[Paquito Diaz]] as Frankie\n*[[Eddie Arenas]] as Sgt. Alex Suarez\n*[[Max Alvarado]] as Imo\n*[[Romy Diaz]]\n*[[Vic Diaz]]\n*[[Ruel Vernal]] as Bert\n*[[Jaime Fabregas|Jimmy Fabregas]] as Jimmy\n*Augusto Victa\n*Ernie Zarate\n*Nick Lizaso\n*Vic Varrion\n*Rey Tomenes\n*[[Renato del Prado]]\n*Fernando Fernandez\n*Col. Juan Medalla (Ret.)\n*Lt. Col. Luis T. Castro as Himself\n*[[Rey Langit]] as Sgt. Bulusan\n*Christopher Paloma as Kikoy\n*Michael Roberts as Buknoy\n*Elvie Escaro\n*Vickay Torres\n*Rene Hawkins as Carding\n*Nonoy De Guzman\n*Belo Borja\n*Jess Vargas\n*Edward Torres\n*Eddie Tuazon\n*Mel Arca\n*Jimmy Reyes\n*Ernie David\n*Bert Garon\n*Joe Estrada\n*Buddy Dator\n*Eddie Samonte\n*Rey Valenzuela\n*Boy Sta. Maria\n*Renato Tanchingco\n*Efren Belardo\n*Telly Babasa\n*Emy Gutierrez\n*Eric Navarro\n*Mario Cavero\n*Pilo Puruganan\n*Lito Francisco\n*Boy Mediavillo\n*Bebot Davao\n*Jun Montano\n*Omay Rivera\n*George Wendth\n*Thunder Stuntmen\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Remake==\nThe film was remade in 2014 under the slightly modified title ''Muslim Magnum .357'' with [[E.R. Ejercito]] in the title role and Francis \"Jun\" Posadas as the director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2014/12/19/1404407/mmff-2014-er-pays-tribute-fpj-muslim-magnum-357/amp/|title=MMFF 2014: ER pays tribute to FPJ in \u2018Muslim Magnum .357\u2018|newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=8 January 2020|first=Rosalinda L. |last=Orosa}}</ref> The remake was an official entry into the [[2014 Metro Manila Film Festival]] and was dedicated to the memory of Fernando Poe Jr. which coincides with Poe's 10th death anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://push.abs-cbn.com/2014/12/27/fresh-scoops/er-ejercito-pays-tribute-to-his-ninong-fpj-with-ma-82999|title=Er Ejercito pays tribute to his ninong FPJ with \"Magnum Muslim 357\" Movie|publisher=[[ABS-CBN|Star Studio]]|date=27 December 2014|accessdate=8 January 2020|first=Jeff|last=Fernando}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{|| width=\"90%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year !! width=\"30%\"| Award-Giving Body !! width=\"25%\"| Category !! width=\"25%\"| Recipient !! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=7| 1987\n|-\n| rowspan=5| [[1987 FAMAS Awards|FAMAS Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000232/1987/1?ref_=ttawd_ev_1|title=FAMAS Awards (1987)|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1987 FAMAS Awards#Major Awards|Best Actor]] || ''[[Fernando Poe Jr.]]'' || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[1987 FAMAS Awards#Major Awards|Best Picture]] || ''Magnum Muslim .357'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[1987 FAMAS Awards#Major Awards|Best Director]] || ''[[Fernando Poe Jr.|Ronwaldo Reyes]]'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[1987 FAMAS Awards#Major Awards|Best Supporting Actor]] || ''[[Paquito Diaz]]'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Luna Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000002/1987/1?ref_=ttawd_ev_2|title=FAP Awards (1987)|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> || Best Actor||''[[Fernando Poe Jr.]]''||{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0409069|Muslim .357 (1986)}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|id=m/magnum_357|title=MAGNUM .357}}\n\n{{Fernando Poe Jr.}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manila]]\n[[Category:Philippine action films]]\n[[Category:Philippine films]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_.357"}
{"title_page": "Abhigyan Jha", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Abhigyan Jha\n| birth_date    =1972\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| nationality   = Indian\n| occupation    = Screenwriter, Producer, Director & Entrepreneur\n| years_active  = 1993\u2212present\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n| organization       = [[Undercover Utopia]], ProMytheUs\n| spouse             = [[Mrinal Jha]]\n| website            = {{URL|http://abhigyanjha.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Abhigyan Jha''' is an Indian film screenwriter, producer, director, writer and entrepreneur who has worked predominantly in [[Hindi film]] and [[Television in India|television industry]].<ref name=Glamsham>{{cite news |last1=Jain |first1=Nitin |title=From novel 'Rain' to SACRED EVIL |url=https://www.glamsham.com/en/from-novel-rain-to-sacred-evil |publisher=Glamsham |date=August 9, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The YouTube Effect |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/culture/the-youtube-effect/cid/459698 |publisher=[[Telegraph India]] |date=January 8, 2011}}</ref> He has written story for  film ''[[Krishna Cottage]]'' (2004), ''Phir Zindagi'' and TV show, ''[[Tum Bin Jaaoon Kahaan]]'',  and made his directorial debut with ''[[Sacred Evil \u2013 A True Story]]'' (2006). He is the creator and director of [[Jay Hind!]], the world's first full format TV show exclusively made for the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The World's First Ever Internet Show 'Jay Hind!' Stars Savita Bhabhi |url=https://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/gossip/2743-the-worlds-first-ever-internet-show-jay-hind-stars-savita-bhabhi-.html |publisher=[[MensXP.com]] |date=November 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=telegraph/><ref>{{cite news |title=Another Landmark For World\u2019s First Internet Show \u2018Jay Hind!\u2019 |url=https://bestmediainfo.com/2010/08/another-landmark-for-world-rsquo-s-first-internet-show-lsquo-jay-hind-rsquo/ |publisher=Bestmediainfo |date=August 16, 2010}}</ref> He also directed and produced the [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony]]'s  popular late-night talk show, ''[[Movers & Shakers]]''.<ref name=ht>{{cite news |last1=A. Khan |first1=Nabeel |title=Movers & Shakers without Shekhar! |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/movers-shakers-without-shekhar/story-U5LRoAWbDXUAOWND7gIrQK.html |publisher=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=Aug 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe is the co-founder of [[Undercover Utopia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=India presence at International Digital Emmy Awards at Cannes |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/press-releases/india-presence-at-international-digital-emmy-awards-at-cannes-111041500104_1.html |publisher=[[Business Standard]] |date=January 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Poduwal |first1=Sunanda |title=Is broadband the new broadcast? |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/is-broadband-the-new-broadcast/articleshow/6148990.cms?from=mdr |publisher=[[The Economic Times]] |date=June 10, 2011}}</ref> He is also a co-founder of ProMytheUs, a [[machine learning]] talent discovery platform.<ref>{{cite web |title=ProMytheUs |url=http://promytheus.net/team/ |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ProMytheUs |url=https://www.thestartupz.com/prometheus/ |publisher=Thestartupz.com |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter completing the creative training program from the Advertising Agencies Association of India, Abhigyan started assisting to Anand Mahendroo.<ref name=Glamsham/> He published his first novel, ''November Rain'' in 1994, followed by his second novel, ''The Prayer''. His novel, ''November Rain'' was transformed into a prime time TV series ''[[Tum Bin Jaaoon Kahaan]]'', which was aired on [[Zee TV]] for over 300 episodes.<ref name=adgully>{{cite news |title=Spirit W - A passionate storyteller: Undercover Utopia's Mrinal Jha |url=https://www.adgully.com/spirit-w-a-passionate-storyteller-undercover-utopia-s-mrinal-jha-52828.html |publisher=Adgully |date=December 20, 2012}}</ref> In 1997, Jha worked as an assistant producer under [[Ismail Merchant]] on the international film ''GAACHH'', starring [[Soumitra Chatterjee]], [[Sharmila Tagore]] and [[Aparna Sen]].<ref name=Glamsham/>  In 1997, Abhigyan Jha directed and produced the [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony Entertainment]]'s popular late-night talk show, ''[[Movers & Shakers (TV series)|Movers & Shakers]]''.<ref name=ht/>\n\nHe wrote the story and screenplay of [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s production, ''[[Krishna Cottage]]'' (2004) and has also written the film, ''Alvida'', starring [[Milind Soman]], [[Gul Panag]] and [[Waheeda Rahman]]. In 2006, he made his debut as a director with ''[[Sacred Evil \u2013 A True Story]]''.<ref name=Glamsham/> He produced TV series, ''[[Kaali \u2013 Ek Agnipariksha]]'', which was aired on [[Star Plus]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Star plus show 'Kaali-Ek Agnipariksha' ends on a high note |url=https://news.webindia123.com/news/articles/India/20110319/1712399.html |publisher=Webindia123 |date=March 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pillai |first1=Pooja |title=Split screen |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/split-screen/726887/ |publisher=[[Indian Express]] |date=December 20, 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Abhigyan Jha launched [[Jay Hind!]], a [[standup comedy]] show exclusively for the [[Internet]] platform. It was the world's first full format TV show exclusively  made for the [[Internet]].<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news |last1=Roy |first1=Priyanka |title=Jai ho to Jay Hind! |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/jai-ho-to-jay-hind/cid/527344 |publisher=[[Telegraph India]] |date=April 27, 2010}}</ref> He is credited for pioneering the [[standup comedy]] genre in India on TV with [[Varun Grover (writer)|Varun Grover]], [[Aditi Mittal]], [[Sorabh Pant]], [[Gursimran Khamba]] and [[Sapan Verma]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaisinghani |first1=Bella |title=Spoof on India's highest civilian awards |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Spoof-on-Indias-highest-civilian-awards/articleshow/20891427.cms |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |date=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Deo |first1=Sumedha |title=Indian awards: for better or for worse |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/indian-awards-for-better-or-for-worse/story-83spNwtcrF2ehibLKRzd1H.html |publisher=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=July 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAbhigyan was nominated for [[ITA Award|ITA Award for Best Director]] - Comedy at the [[Indian Television Academy Awards]] 2011 for ''[[Jay Hind!]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Hind nominated for this year\u2019s ITA Awards |url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-business/jay-hind-nominated-for-this-years-ita-awards-113102206220_1.html |publisher=[[India Infoline]] |date=September 23, 2011}}</ref> Later, the show was aired on [[Colors TV]] under a new name, ''The Late Night Show'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=COLORS launches 'The Late Night Show' with Sumeet Raghavan |url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/release/y2k12/mar/marrel9.php |date=March 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Abhigyan Jha accused [[Vikas Bahl]], the director of ''[[Queen (2014 film)|Queen]]'' for copying the film, ''[[Queen (2014 film)|Queen]]'' from his film, ''Phir Zindagi''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is 'Queen' inspired by 'The Art Of Travel'? |url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/140424/entertainment-bollywood/article/is-queen-inspired-by-the-art-of-travel |publisher=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |date=April 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Is Kangana Ranaut-starrer 'Queen' copied? |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kangana-Ranauts-Queen-copied-Queen-copied-from-Phir-Zindagi/articleshow/33821018.cms |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |date=April 17, 2015}}</ref> However, Jha accepted the fact that while the scripts of the two films are different, but some major scenes from the film have been copied straight from ''Phir Zindagi''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phir Zindagi writer claims Vikas Bahl copied script for Queen |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/vikas-bahl-queen-kangana-ranaut-phir-zindagi-abhigyan-jha-189121-2014-04-15 |publisher=[[India Today]] |date=April 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Published works ==\n* {{cite book |title=November Rain: Memories of the Spellbound : a Supernatural Love Story Based on True Incidents |publisher=[[Undercover Utopia]] |isbn=9780979811609}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Prayer |publisher=[[Undercover Utopia]] |isbn=9780979811623}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Class of 2010 |publisher=[[Undercover Utopia]] |isbn=9780979811661}}\n* {{cite book |title=Soul Search Engine : Till Now... |publisher=[[Undercover Utopia]] |isbn=9780979811647}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Paperback Pickings |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/paperback-pickings/cid/622384 |publisher=[[Telegraph India]] |date=February 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Krishna Cottage]]'' || Story, Screenplay writer ||\n|-\n| -|| ''Phir Zindagi'' || Screenplay writer ||\n|-\n| -|| ''GAACHH'' || Assistant producer ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Sacred Evil \u2013 A True Story]]'' || Director, Producer || Engllish\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Sacred Evil \u2013 A True Story|Gehra Paani]]'' || Director || Hindi\n|}\n\n== Television ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! TV/Web Show!! Role || Channel\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Star Bestsellers]]'' ''Neeti''  || Story writer || [[StarPlus]]\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[X Zone]]  || Story writer || [[StarPlus]]\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Movers & Shakers]]'' || Director, Producer || [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony]]\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Rajani (TV series)|Rajani]]'' || Story writer|| [[Doordarshan]]\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Tum Bin Jaaoon Kahaan]]'' || Story writer || [[Zee TV]]\n|-\n| 2009|| ''[[Jay Hind]]'' || Director || for the [[Internet]]\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Kaali \u2013 Ek Agnipariksha]]'' || Producer || [[Star Plus]]\n|-\n| 2012|| ''[[Jay Hind!|The Late Night Show]]'' || Director || [[Colors TV]]\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married to [[Mrinal Jha]] and has a daughter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhattacharya |first1=Pallavi |title=Parental Objections To Marriages |url=http://www.shaaditimes.com/love/after-marriage/parental-objection-080616 |publisher=[[Shaadi.com|Shaadi Times]]}}</ref><ref name=thehindu>{{cite news |last1=Cornelious |first1=Deborah |title=Foster fails and a full house |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/foster-fails-and-a-full-house/article29426857.ece |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=September 16, 2019}}</ref> He is the son of Ramesh Rajhans, a theatre director and playwright.<ref name=Glamsham/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{URL|http://abhigyanjha.com/|Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|1962200}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140311035056/http://www.iptv-news.com/2014/01/special-report-undercover-productions-the-end-of-broadcasting-as-we-know-it/ Undercover Productions & the END of broadcasting (as we know it)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jha, Abhigyan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Indian film producers]]\n[[Category:Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Abhigyan Jha\n| birth_date    =1972\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| nationality   = Indian\n| occupation    = Screenwriter, Producer, Director & Entrepreneur\n| years_active  = 1993\u2212present\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n| organization       = [[Undercover Utopia]], ProMytheUs\n| spouse             = [[Mrinal Jha]]\n| website            = {{URL|http://abhigyanjha.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Abhigyan Jha''' is an Indian film screenwriter, producer, director, writer and entrepreneur who has worked predominantly in [[Hindi film]] and [[Television in India|television industry]].<ref name=Glamsham>{{cite news |last1=Jain |first1=Nitin |title=From novel 'Rain' to SACRED EVIL |url=https://www.glamsham.com/en/from-novel-rain-to-sacred-evil |publisher=Glamsham |date=August 9, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The YouTube Effect |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/culture/the-youtube-effect/cid/459698 |publisher=[[Telegraph India]] |date=January 8, 2011}}</ref> He has written story for  film ''[[Krishna Cottage]]'' (2004), ''Phir Zindagi'' and TV show, ''[[Tum Bin Jaaoon Kahaan]]'',  and made his directorial debut with ''[[Sacred Evil \u2013 A True Story]]'' (2006). He is the creator and director of [[Jay Hind!]], the world's first full format TV show exclusively made for the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The World's First Ever Internet Show 'Jay Hind!' Stars Savita Bhabhi |url=https://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/gossip/2743-the-worlds-first-ever-internet-show-jay-hind-stars-savita-bhabhi-.html |publisher=[[MensXP.com]] |date=November 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=telegraph/><ref>{{cite news |title=Another Landmark For World\u2019s First Internet Show \u2018Jay Hind!\u2019 |url=https://bestmediainfo.com/2010/08/another-landmark-for-world-rsquo-s-first-internet-show-lsquo-jay-hind-rsquo/ |publisher=Bestmediainfo |date=August 16, 2010}}</ref> He also directed and produced the [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony]]'s  popular late-night talk show, ''[[Movers & Shakers]]''.<ref name=ht>{{cite news |last1=A. Khan |first1=Nabeel |title=Movers & Shakers without Shekhar! |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/movers-shakers-without-shekhar/story-U5LRoAWbDXUAOWND7gIrQK.html |publisher=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=Aug 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe is the co-founder of [[Undercover Utopia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=India presence at International Digital Emmy Awards at Cannes |url=https://www.business-standard.com/a