{"title_page": "Banksia seminuda", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Short description|Species of tree in the genus ''Banksia''}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n|name = river banksia\n|image = Banksia seminuda AD MB.jpg\n|image_caption = ''B.seminuda'' cultivated in<br>[[Mount Barker, Western Australia]]\n|regnum = [[Plantae]]\n|unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|ordo = [[Proteales]]\n|familia = [[Proteaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Banksia]]''\n|subgenus = [[Banksia subg. Banksia|''Banksia'' subg. ''Banksia'']]\n|sectio = [[Banksia sect. Oncostylis|''Banksia'' sect. ''Oncostylis'']]\n|series = [[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''Banksia'' ser. ''Spicigerae'']]\n|species = '''''B. seminuda'''''\n|binomial = ''Banksia seminuda''\n|binomial_authority = ([[Alex George|A.S.George]]) [[Barbara Lynette Rye|Rye]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia seminuda'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/108983 |website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}}\n\n'''''Banksia&nbsp;seminuda''''', commonly known as the '''river banksia''',<ref name=\"IBIS\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia seminuda'' |url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/common.names/ |website=IBIS-Australian Plant Common Name Database |publisher=Australian National Botanic Gardens}}</ref> is a [[tree]] in the [[plant]] [[genus]] ''[[Banksia]]''. It is found in south west [[Western Australia]] from [[Dwellingup, Western Australia|Dwellingup]] (32\u00b042\u2032&nbsp;S) to the Broke Inlet east of [[Denmark, Western Australia|Denmark]] (34\u00b057\u2032&nbsp;S). It is often mistaken for, and was originally considered a [[subspecies]] of, the ''[[Banksia littoralis|Banksia&nbsp;littoralis]]'' (Swamp Banksia). [[Stephen Hopper]] described the subspecies ''remanens'' as a short-leaved shrubby form found in the coastal sands below granite outcrops in the [[Walpole-Nornalup National Park]], however [[Alex George|George]] does not feel this form warrants taxonomic recognition as it lies within the normal variability of the species and there was no clear distinction between it and the other populations of ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''.\n\n== Description ==\nThe river banksia generally grows as a tree up to 25&nbsp;metres (80&nbsp;ft) tall with a usually brown to grey trunk covered with a hard grey furrowed bark.<ref name=\"FoA\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=George|first=Alex|title=Banksia|year=1999|chapter=Banksia|editor-last=Wilson|editor-first=Annette |encyclopedia=Flora of Australia|volume= Volume 17B: Proteaceae 3: Hakea to Dryandra|pages=175\u2013251|publisher=CSIRO Publishing / Australian Biological Resources Study|authorlink= Alex George|isbn=0-643-06454-0}}</ref> The tree trunk is often straight and tall as the species generally grows in sheltered forest areas. The leaves are [[phyllotaxis|arranged]] on the stems in whorls. Measuring {{convert|5|-|12|cm|in|frac=4}} long and {{convert|1|-|1.8|cm|in|frac=4}} across, they are linear in shape with serrated margins. The upper leaf surface is finely furred becoming smooth, while the undersruface is covered in white fur.<ref name=\"FoA\"/>\n\nFlowering occurs between late summer and late winter. The yellow (occasionally red) flower spikes grow up to 200&nbsp;mm (8&nbsp;in) high by 70&nbsp;mm (3&nbsp;in) wide, the fruiting cones can remain on the trees for many years after shedding the flowers early. Its leathery leaves are between 70&nbsp;mm (3&nbsp;in) and 120&nbsp;mm (5&nbsp;in) long with fine teeth, subspecies ''remanens'' leaves have few if any teeth except at the tips of the leaves.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe type specimen of ''Banksia seminuda'' was collected on 15 May 1973 in [[Nanga Brook, Western Australia]] by [[Alex George]],<ref name=rye84/> who described it in 1981 as a subspecies of ''B.&nbsp;littoralis''. He had published a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] arrangement of ''Banksia'' in his landmark 1981 monograph ''[[The genus Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)]]''.\n\nIn 1984, botanist [[Barbara Lynette Rye|Barbara Rye]] of the [[Western Australian Herbarium]] noted that the two species did not interbreed when they occurred in stands together in the Two Peoples Bay region. This was despite an overlap in their flowering seasons. The bark of the trunk and flower structure differed greatly between the species. ''B. seminuda'' grew alongside rivers while ''B. littoralis'' grew in wet depressions.<ref name=rye84>{{cite journal| author= Rye, Barbara L.|year=1984|title= A new species and a new combination among the Proteaceae represented in the Perth region |journal= Nuytsia | volume= 5 |issue=1 |pages= 25\u201330| url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53188515}}</ref>\n\nEndlicher's ''Eubanksia'' became [[Banksia subg. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;subg. ''Banksia'']], and was divided into three sections, one of which was ''Oncostylis''. ''Oncostylis'' was further divided into four series. After its discovery, ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' placed in series [[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''Spicigerae'']] because its inflorescences are cylindrical.<ref name=\"FoA\"/>\n\n[[file:Banksia seminuda 300912 2a.JPG|thumb|right|Red-flowered form in late bud]]\nIn 1996, [[Kevin Thiele]] and [[Pauline Ladiges]] published a new arrangement for the genus, after [[cladistics|cladistic]] analyses yielded a [[cladogram]] significantly different from George's arrangement. With respect to ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'', their findings largely accorded with George's arrangement: section ''Oncostylis'' was discarded as [[polyphyletic]], but series ''Spicigerae'' was inferred to be monophyletic, and ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' appeared as the closest relative of a [[clade]]s of ''B. littoralis'' and ''B. verticillata'':<ref name=\"Thiele 1996\">{{cite journal | last1 = Thiele | first1 = Kevin | authorlink1 = Kevin Thiele | last2 = Ladiges | first2 = Pauline Y. | authorlink2 = Pauline Ladiges | year = 1996 | title = A cladistic analysis of ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae) | journal = [[Australian Systematic Botany]] | volume = 9 | issue = 5 | pages = 661\u2013733 | doi = 10.1071/SB9960661}}</ref>\n{{Clade\n  |1={{Clade\n       |1=''[[Banksia occidentalis|B.&nbsp;occidentalis]]''\n       |2={{Clade\n            |1=''[[Banksia brownii|B.&nbsp;brownii]]''\n            |2={{Clade\n                 |1='''''B.&nbsp;seminuda'''''\n                 |2={{Clade\n                      |1=''[[Banksia littoralis|B.&nbsp;littoralis]]''\n                      |2=''[[Banksia verticillata|B.&nbsp;verticillata]]''\n                    }}\n               }}\n          }}\n     }}\n}}\nThis clade became the basis of Thiele and Ladiges' [[Banksia subser. Occidentales|''B.''&nbsp;subser. ''Occidentales'']], which was defined as \"characterised by [[opposite-decussate]] seedling leaves and adult leaves in true whorls.\"<ref name=\"Thiele 1996\"/> This arrangement stood until 1999, when George largely reverted to his 1981 arrangement in his monograph for the ''[[Flora of Australia (series)|Flora of Australia]]'' series. Under [[George's taxonomic arrangement of Banksia|George's taxonomic arrangement of ''Banksia'']], ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''{{'}}s taxonomic placement may be summarised as follows:<ref name =\"FoA\"/>\n:'''''[[Banksia]]'''''\n::'''[[Banksia subg. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;subg. ''Banksia'']]'''\n:::[[Banksia sect. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Banksia'']] (9 series, 50 species, 9 subspecies, 3 varieties)\n:::[[Banksia sect. Coccinea|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Coccinea'']] (1 species)\n:::'''[[Banksia sect. Oncostylis|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Oncostylis'']]'''\n::::[[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''B.''&nbsp;ser. ''Spicigerae'']] (7 species, 2 subspecies, 4 varieties)\n:::::''[[Banksia spinulosa|B.&nbsp;spinulosa]]'' (4 varieties)\n:::::''[[Banksia ericifolia|B.&nbsp;ericifolia]]'' (2 subspecies)\n:::::''[[Banksia verticillata|B.&nbsp;verticillata]]''\n:::::'''''B.&nbsp;seminuda'''''\n:::::''[[Banksia littoralis|B.&nbsp;littoralis]]''\n:::::''[[Banksia occidentalis|B.&nbsp;occidentalis]]''\n:::::''[[Banksia brownii|B.&nbsp;brownii]]''\n\nA 2013 molecular study by Marcel Cardillo and colleagues using chloroplast DNA and combining it with earlier results found that ''B. seminuda'' was sister to a combined lineage that gave rise to ''B. quercifolia'' and ''B. oreophila''. The ancestor of these three taxa had diverged almost 20 million years previously from the ancestor of the western Australian members of the Spicigerae and ''B. nutans''.<ref name=\"cardillo 2013\">{{cite journal|last=Cardillo|first=Marcel|author2=Pratt, Renae|date=2013|title=Evolution of a Hotspot Genus: Geographic Variation in Speciation and Extinction Rates in ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae)|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=13|issue=155|url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2148/13/155/ | doi=10.1186/1471-2148-13-155|pmid=23957450|pmc=3751403}}</ref>\n\n===Intraspecific variation===\n''Banksia seminuda'' subspecies ''remanens'' was described by Stephen Hopper in 1989, from a specimen collected in Walpole-Nornalup National Park. He recorded distinctive populations of ''seminuda'' that were generally shrubs 2\u20133 m high and had smaller leaves that were 4\u20136&nbsp;cm long and 0.5-0.8&nbsp;cm wide. These occur within 1&nbsp;km of the coast over a 30&nbsp;km stretch of Western Australia's south coastline mostly within Walpole-Nornalup National Park, from Cliffy Head to Conspicuous Cliff. Hopper noted some intermediate stands with the usual tree forms at Broke Inlet and Coalmine Beach, and at Boggy Lake, around 600 m northwest of the summit of Mt Hopkins.<ref name=\"Hopper 1989\">{{cite journal|last=Hopper|first=Stephen D.|date=1989|title=New subspecies of ''Banksia seminuda'' and ''B. occidentalis'' (Proteaceae) from the south coast of Western Australia |journal=Nuytsia|volume=7|issue=1|pages=15\u201324|url=https://florabase.dpaw.wa.gov.au/science/nuytsia/145.pdf}}</ref> [[Alex George|George]] does not feel this form warrants taxonomic recognition as it lies within the normal variability of the species and there was no clear distinction between it and the other populations of ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''.<ref name = \"George96\">{{cite journal | last = George | first = A. S. | authorlink = Alex George | year = 1996 | title = Notes on ''Banksia'' L. f | journal = Nuytsia | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 21\u201324}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[Image:Banksia seminuda trunk email.JPG|thumb|right|fissured trunk on 20-year-old tree, Banksia Farm, Mount Barker, WA]]\nThis tree is found on the fringes of the rivers and creeks in [[Eucalyptus marginata|Jarrah]], [[Corymbia calophylla|Marri]] and [[Eucalyptus diversicolor|Karri]] forests, between Dwellingup and Denmark.\n\nThe short-leaved shrubby form is found in deep coastal sands below granite outcrops in the Walpole-Nornalup National Park. It grows as an emergent plant in coastal heath, associated with species such as mallee form of jarrah (''[[Eucalyptus marginata]]''), basket bush (''[[Spyridium globulosum]]''), pineapple bush (''[[Dasypogon bromeliifolius]]''), prickly conostylis (''[[Conostylis aculeata]]''), coastal daisybush (''[[Olearia axillaris]]''), harsh hakea (''[[Hakea prostrata]]'') as well as bull banksia (''[[Banksia grandis]]''), oak-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia quercifolia|B. quercifolia]]'') and ''B. littoralis''. It also grows in thickets of vegetation next to granite outcrops, associated with granite banksia (''[[Banksia verticillata]]''), Walpole wax (''[[Chamelaucium floriferum]]''), ''[[Taxandria marginata]]'', heart-leaved poison (''[[Gastrolobium bilobum]]''), myrtle wattle (''[[Acacia myrtifolia]]'') and sticky tailflower (''[[Anthocercis viscosa]]'').<ref name=\"Hopper 1989\"/>\n\n==Ecology==\n''Banksia seminuda'' is killed by bushfire and regenerates afterwards from seed.<ref name=\"FoA\"/> Scorching that circles the trunk will kill the plant. It grows in areas of lower flammability that only usually burn in summer and autumn. Juvenile plants take around 5 years to reach flowering post-fire.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Burrows, N.D. |author2=Wardell, Johnson G. |author3=Ward, B. |date=2008|title=Post-fire juvenile period of plants in south-west Australia forests and implications for fire management|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia|volume=91|pages=163\u201374|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Neil_Burrows3/publication/260871833_Post-fire_juvenile_period_of_plants_in_south-west_Australian_forests_and_implications_for_fire_management/links/02e7e53290d4e99733000000.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAn assessment of the potential impact of [[climate change]] on this species found that its range is likely to contract by between 30% and 80% by 2080, depending on the severity of the change.<ref name=\"Fitzpatrick 2008\">{{cite journal | last1=Fitzpatrick | first1=Matthew C. | last2=Gove | first2=Aaron D. | last3=Sanders | first3=Nathan J. | last4=Dunn | first4=Robert R. | year = 2008 | title = Climate change, plant migration, and range collapse in a global biodiversity hotspot: the ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae) of Western Australia | journal = Global Change Biology | volume = 14 | pages = 1\u201316 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2008.01559.x | issue = 6}}</ref>\n\n==Cultivation==\n''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' is a vigorous and adaptable plant. There are reports of seedlings coming up near cultivated plants in Victoria which suggests caution should be advised if planting near bushland.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last = Wheeler | first = Judy | year = 2003 | title = Common Trees of the South-West Forests | publisher = Department of Conservation and Land Management (CALM) | isbn = 0-7309-6961-4|oclc = 35655910}}\n*{{The genus Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)}}\n*{{The Banksia Atlas}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Trees}}\n{{Wikispecies|Banksia seminuda}}\n*{{Flora of Australia Online}}\n*{{FloraBase}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2707711}}\n\n[[Category:Banksia taxa by scientific name|seminuda]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Australia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mediterranean climate]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Short description|Species of tree in the genus ''Banksia''}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n|name = river banksia\n|image = Banksia seminuda AD MB.jpg\n|image_caption = ''B.seminuda'' cultivated in<br>[[Mount Barker, Western Australia]]\n|regnum = [[Plantae]]\n|unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|ordo = [[Proteales]]\n|familia = [[Proteaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Banksia]]''\n|subgenus = [[Banksia subg. Banksia|''Banksia'' subg. ''Banksia'']]\n|sectio = [[Banksia sect. Oncostylis|''Banksia'' sect. ''Oncostylis'']]\n|series = [[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''Banksia'' ser. ''Spicigerae'']]\n|species = '''''B. seminuda'''''\n|binomial = ''Banksia seminuda''\n|binomial_authority = ([[Alex George|A.S.George]]) [[Barbara Lynette Rye|Rye]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Banksia&nbsp;seminuda''''', commonly known as the '''river banksia''', is a [[tree]] in the [[plant]] [[genus]] ''[[Banksia]]''. It is found in south west [[Western Australia]] from [[Dwellingup, Western Australia|Dwellingup]] (32\u00b042\u2032&nbsp;S) to the Broke Inlet east of [[Denmark, Western Australia|Denmark]] (34\u00b057\u2032&nbsp;S). It is often mistaken for, and was originally considered a [[subspecies]] of, the ''[[Banksia littoralis|Banksia&nbsp;littoralis]]'' (Swamp Banksia). [[Stephen Hopper]] described the subspecies ''remanens'' as a short-leaved shrubby form found in the coastal sands below granite outcrops in the [[Walpole-Nornalup National Park]], however [[Alex George|George]] does not feel this form warrants taxonomic recognition as it lies within the normal variability of the species and there was no clear distinction between it and the other populations of ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''.\n\n== Description ==\nThe river banksia generally grows as a tree up to 25&nbsp;metres (80&nbsp;ft) tall with a usually brown to grey trunk covered with a hard grey furrowed bark.<ref name=\"FoA\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=George|first=Alex|title=Banksia|year=1999|chapter=Banksia|editor-last=Wilson|editor-first=Annette |encyclopedia=Flora of Australia|volume= Volume 17B: Proteaceae 3: Hakea to Dryandra|pages=175\u2013251|publisher=CSIRO Publishing / Australian Biological Resources Study|authorlink= Alex George|isbn=0-643-06454-0}}</ref> The tree trunk is often straight and tall as the species generally grows in sheltered forest areas. The leaves are [[phyllotaxis|arranged]] on the stems in whorls. Measuring {{convert|5|-|12|cm|in|frac=4}} long and {{convert|1|-|1.8|cm|in|frac=4}} across, they are linear in shape with serrated margins. The upper leaf surface is finely furred becoming smooth, while the undersruface is covered in white fur.<ref name=\"FoA\"/>\n\nFlowering occurs between late summer and late winter. The yellow (occasionally red) flower spikes grow up to 200&nbsp;mm (8&nbsp;in) high by 70&nbsp;mm (3&nbsp;in) wide, the fruiting cones can remain on the trees for many years after shedding the flowers early. Its leathery leaves are between 70&nbsp;mm (3&nbsp;in) and 120&nbsp;mm (5&nbsp;in) long with fine teeth, subspecies ''remanens'' leaves have few if any teeth except at the tips of the leaves.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe type specimen of ''Banksia seminuda'' was collected on 15 May 1973 in [[Nanga Brook, Western Australia]] by [[Alex George]],<ref name=rye84/> who described it in 1981 as a subspecies of ''B.&nbsp;littoralis''. He had published a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] arrangement of ''Banksia'' in his landmark 1981 monograph ''[[The genus Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)]]''.\n\nIn 1984, botanist [[Barbara Lynette Rye|Barbara Rye]] of the [[Western Australian Herbarium]] noted that the two species did not interbreed when they occurred in stands together in the Two Peoples Bay region. This was despite an overlap in their flowering seasons. The bark of the trunk and flower structure differed greatly between the species. ''B. seminuda'' grew alongside rivers while ''B. littoralis'' grew in wet depressions.<ref name=rye84>{{cite journal| author= Rye, Barbara L.|year=1984|title= A new species and a new combination among the Proteaceae represented in the Perth region |journal= Nuytsia | volume= 5 |issue=1 |pages= 25\u201330| url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53188515}}</ref>\n\nEndlicher's ''Eubanksia'' became [[Banksia subg. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;subg. ''Banksia'']], and was divided into three sections, one of which was ''Oncostylis''. ''Oncostylis'' was further divided into four series. After its discovery, ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' placed in series [[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''Spicigerae'']] because its inflorescences are cylindrical.<ref name=\"FoA\"/>\n\n[[file:Banksia seminuda 300912 2a.JPG|thumb|right|Red-flowered form in late bud]]\nIn 1996, [[Kevin Thiele]] and [[Pauline Ladiges]] published a new arrangement for the genus, after [[cladistics|cladistic]] analyses yielded a [[cladogram]] significantly different from George's arrangement. With respect to ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'', their findings largely accorded with George's arrangement: section ''Oncostylis'' was discarded as [[polyphyletic]], but series ''Spicigerae'' was inferred to be monophyletic, and ''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' appeared as the closest relative of a [[clade]]s of ''B. littoralis'' and ''B. verticillata'':<ref name=\"Thiele 1996\">{{cite journal | last1 = Thiele | first1 = Kevin | authorlink1 = Kevin Thiele | last2 = Ladiges | first2 = Pauline Y. | authorlink2 = Pauline Ladiges | year = 1996 | title = A cladistic analysis of ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae) | journal = [[Australian Systematic Botany]] | volume = 9 | issue = 5 | pages = 661\u2013733 | doi = 10.1071/SB9960661}}</ref>\n{{Clade\n  |1={{Clade\n       |1=''[[Banksia occidentalis|B.&nbsp;occidentalis]]''\n       |2={{Clade\n            |1=''[[Banksia brownii|B.&nbsp;brownii]]''\n            |2={{Clade\n                 |1='''''B.&nbsp;seminuda'''''\n                 |2={{Clade\n                      |1=''[[Banksia littoralis|B.&nbsp;littoralis]]''\n                      |2=''[[Banksia verticillata|B.&nbsp;verticillata]]''\n                    }}\n               }}\n          }}\n     }}\n}}\nThis clade became the basis of Thiele and Ladiges' [[Banksia subser. Occidentales|''B.''&nbsp;subser. ''Occidentales'']], which was defined as \"characterised by [[opposite-decussate]] seedling leaves and adult leaves in true whorls.\"<ref name=\"Thiele 1996\"/> This arrangement stood until 1999, when George largely reverted to his 1981 arrangement in his monograph for the ''[[Flora of Australia (series)|Flora of Australia]]'' series. Under [[George's taxonomic arrangement of Banksia|George's taxonomic arrangement of ''Banksia'']], ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''{{'}}s taxonomic placement may be summarised as follows:<ref name =\"FoA\"/>\n:'''''[[Banksia]]'''''\n::'''[[Banksia subg. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;subg. ''Banksia'']]'''\n:::[[Banksia sect. Banksia|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Banksia'']] (9 series, 50 species, 9 subspecies, 3 varieties)\n:::[[Banksia sect. Coccinea|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Coccinea'']] (1 species)\n:::'''[[Banksia sect. Oncostylis|''B.''&nbsp;sect. ''Oncostylis'']]'''\n::::[[Banksia ser. Spicigerae|''B.''&nbsp;ser. ''Spicigerae'']] (7 species, 2 subspecies, 4 varieties)\n:::::''[[Banksia spinulosa|B.&nbsp;spinulosa]]'' (4 varieties)\n:::::''[[Banksia ericifolia|B.&nbsp;ericifolia]]'' (2 subspecies)\n:::::''[[Banksia verticillata|B.&nbsp;verticillata]]''\n:::::'''''B.&nbsp;seminuda'''''\n:::::''[[Banksia littoralis|B.&nbsp;littoralis]]''\n:::::''[[Banksia occidentalis|B.&nbsp;occidentalis]]''\n:::::''[[Banksia brownii|B.&nbsp;brownii]]''\n\nA 2013 molecular study by Marcel Cardillo and colleagues using chloroplast DNA and combining it with earlier results found that ''B. seminuda'' was sister to a combined lineage that gave rise to ''B. quercifolia'' and ''B. oreophila''. The ancestor of these three taxa had diverged almost 20 million years previously from the ancestor of the western Australian members of the Spicigerae and ''B. nutans''.<ref name=\"cardillo 2013\">{{cite journal|last=Cardillo|first=Marcel|author2=Pratt, Renae|date=2013|title=Evolution of a Hotspot Genus: Geographic Variation in Speciation and Extinction Rates in ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae)|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=13|issue=155|url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2148/13/155/ | doi=10.1186/1471-2148-13-155|pmid=23957450|pmc=3751403}}</ref>\n\n===Intraspecific variation===\n''Banksia seminuda'' subspecies ''remanens'' was described by Stephen Hopper in 1989, from a specimen collected in Walpole-Nornalup National Park. He recorded distinctive populations of ''seminuda'' that were generally shrubs 2\u20133 m high and had smaller leaves that were 4\u20136&nbsp;cm long and 0.5-0.8&nbsp;cm wide. These occur within 1&nbsp;km of the coast over a 30&nbsp;km stretch of Western Australia's south coastline mostly within Walpole-Nornalup National Park, from Cliffy Head to Conspicuous Cliff. Hopper noted some intermediate stands with the usual tree forms at Broke Inlet and Coalmine Beach, and at Boggy Lake, around 600 m northwest of the summit of Mt Hopkins.<ref name=\"Hopper 1989\">{{cite journal|last=Hopper|first=Stephen D.|date=1989|title=New subspecies of ''Banksia seminuda'' and ''B. occidentalis'' (Proteaceae) from the south coast of Western Australia |journal=Nuytsia|volume=7|issue=1|pages=15\u201324|url=https://florabase.dpaw.wa.gov.au/science/nuytsia/145.pdf}}</ref> [[Alex George|George]] does not feel this form warrants taxonomic recognition as it lies within the normal variability of the species and there was no clear distinction between it and the other populations of ''B.&nbsp;seminuda''.<ref name = \"George96\">{{cite journal | last = George | first = A. S. | authorlink = Alex George | year = 1996 | title = Notes on ''Banksia'' L. f | journal = Nuytsia | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 21\u201324}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[Image:Banksia seminuda trunk email.JPG|thumb|right|fissured trunk on 20-year-old tree, Banksia Farm, Mount Barker, WA]]\nThis tree is found on the fringes of the rivers and creeks in [[Eucalyptus marginata|Jarrah]], [[Corymbia calophylla|Marri]] and [[Eucalyptus diversicolor|Karri]] forests, between Dwellingup and Denmark.\n\nThe short-leaved shrubby form is found in deep coastal sands below granite outcrops in the Walpole-Nornalup National Park. It grows as an emergent plant in coastal heath, associated with species such as mallee form of jarrah (''[[Eucalyptus marginata]]''), basket bush (''[[Spyridium globulosum]]''), pineapple bush (''[[Dasypogon bromeliifolius]]''), prickly conostylis (''[[Conostylis aculeata]]''), coastal daisybush (''[[Olearia axillaris]]''), harsh hakea (''[[Hakea prostrata]]'') as well as bull banksia (''[[Banksia grandis]]''), oak-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia quercifolia|B. quercifolia]]'') and ''B. littoralis''. It also grows in thickets of vegetation next to granite outcrops, associated with granite banksia (''[[Banksia verticillata]]''), Walpole wax (''[[Chamelaucium floriferum]]''), ''[[Taxandria marginata]]'', heart-leaved poison (''[[Gastrolobium bilobum]]''), myrtle wattle (''[[Acacia myrtifolia]]'') and sticky tailflower (''[[Anthocercis viscosa]]'').<ref name=\"Hopper 1989\"/>\n\n==Ecology==\n''Banksia seminuda'' is killed by bushfire and regenerates afterwards from seed.<ref name=\"FoA\"/> Scorching that circles the trunk will kill the plant. It grows in areas of lower flammability that only usually burn in summer and autumn. Juvenile plants take around 5 years to reach flowering post-fire.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Burrows, N.D. |author2=Wardell, Johnson G. |author3=Ward, B. |date=2008|title=Post-fire juvenile period of plants in south-west Australia forests and implications for fire management|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia|volume=91|pages=163\u201374|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Neil_Burrows3/publication/260871833_Post-fire_juvenile_period_of_plants_in_south-west_Australian_forests_and_implications_for_fire_management/links/02e7e53290d4e99733000000.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAn assessment of the potential impact of [[climate change]] on this species found that its range is likely to contract by between 30% and 80% by 2080, depending on the severity of the change.<ref name=\"Fitzpatrick 2008\">{{cite journal | last1=Fitzpatrick | first1=Matthew C. | last2=Gove | first2=Aaron D. | last3=Sanders | first3=Nathan J. | last4=Dunn | first4=Robert R. | year = 2008 | title = Climate change, plant migration, and range collapse in a global biodiversity hotspot: the ''Banksia'' (Proteaceae) of Western Australia | journal = Global Change Biology | volume = 14 | pages = 1\u201316 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2008.01559.x | issue = 6}}</ref>\n\n==Cultivation==\n''B.&nbsp;seminuda'' is a vigorous and adaptable plant. There are reports of seedlings coming up near cultivated plants in Victoria which suggests caution should be advised if planting near bushland.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last = Wheeler | first = Judy | year = 2003 | title = Common Trees of the South-West Forests | publisher = Department of Conservation and Land Management (CALM) | isbn = 0-7309-6961-4|oclc = 35655910}}\n*{{The genus Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)}}\n*{{The Banksia Atlas}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Trees}}\n{{Wikispecies|Banksia seminuda}}\n*{{Flora of Australia Online}}\n*{{FloraBase}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2707711}}\n\n[[Category:Banksia taxa by scientific name|seminuda]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Australia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mediterranean climate]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Allthingsnative", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banksia_seminuda"}
{"title_page": "Airbus A318", "text_new": "{{short description|Airliner, smallest series of the A320 family}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout, and guidelines. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = A318\n| image = File:Airfrance.a318-100.f-guga.arp.jpg\n| alt = aircraft taking off with wheels not retracted\n| caption = An Airbus A318 of [[Air France]], the largest operator of the type\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Narrow-body]] [[jet airliner]]\n| national origin = Multinational{{efn|The Airbus A318 is built in Hamburg, Germany}}\n| manufacturer = [[Airbus]]\n| designer = \n| first flight = 15 January 2002\n| introduced = 2003 with [[Frontier Airlines]]\n| produced = 2003\u20132013 \n| retired = \n| status = In service\n| primary user = [[Air France]]\n| more users =  [[TAROM]]<br />[[British Airways]]<!--Limit of three (3) more users here. -->\n| number built = 80<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n| unit cost = [[US$]]77.4&nbsp;million, \u20ac63 million (2018)<ref name=\"2018 price\">{{cite press release|title=Airbus 2018 Price List Press Release|date=23 January 2018|url=http://www.airbus.com/newsroom/press-releases/en/2018/01/airbus-2018-price-list-press-release.html|website=Airbus|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n| developed from = [[Airbus A319]]\n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Airbus A318''' is the smallest [[airliner]] in the [[Airbus A320 family]]. The A318 carries 107 to 132 passengers and has a maximum range of {{cvt|3100|nmi|km|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"A318 specifications\"/> Final assembly of the aircraft took place in [[Hamburg]], Germany.\nIt is intended primarily for short-range service, although [[British Airways]] uses the aircraft on a [[London City Airport]] to [[New York-JFK Airport]] transatlantic route (albeit with a stopover in [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]] for refueling on the westbound leg, as it is too heavy to clear the short runway at LCY with a full load of fuel).\n\nThe aircraft shares a common [[type rating]] with all other Airbus A320 family variants, allowing existing A320 family pilots to fly the aircraft without the need for further training. It is the largest commercial aircraft certified by the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] for steep approach operations, allowing flights at airports such as [[London City Airport|London City]].<ref name=A318steep/>\n\nThe A318 entered service in July 2003 with [[Frontier Airlines]]. Relative to other Airbus A320 family variants, it has sold in only small numbers with total orders for 80 aircraft placed, with the order book currently being empty.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aircraft.airbus.com/market/orders-deliveries/|publisher=Airbus|title=Airbus Orders & Deliveries|date=30 September 2017|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> It also has an excellent safety record with zero accidents as of 2018. As of January 2019, [[Air France]] was the largest operator of the Airbus A318.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\" />\n\n== Development ==<!-- Linked from [[Airbus A320 family]] -->\n\n===Background===\nThe first member of the A320 aircraft family was the A320, which [[Maiden flight|first flew]] on 22 February 1987 after the program was launched in March 1984.<ref>{{harvnb|Norris|Wagner|1999|p=50}}</ref> The family was soon extended to include the stretched A321 (first delivery 1994), the shortened [[Airbus A319|A319]] (first delivery 1996), and the further shortened A318 (first delivery 2003). The A320 family pioneered the use in commercial aircraft of digital [[fly-by-wire]] [[Aircraft flight control system|flight control systems]], as well as [[side stick]] controls.\n\nThe Airbus A318 project had its origins in the collaboration among Chinese, Singaporean and European manufacturers. In May 1997, during the visit of French President [[Jacques Chirac]] to China, [[Aviation Industry Corporation of China|Aviation Industries of China]] (AVIC), [[ST Aerospace|Singapore Technologies Aerospace]] (STAe), Airbus and [[Alenia Aermacchi|Alenia]] signed a framework agreement that outlined the development of aircraft in the 100-seat range.<ref name=Interavia>{{Cite web|author1=Condom, Pierre|author2=Sutton, Oliver|date=1 June 1997|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19778327.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702024922/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19778327.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 July 2016|title=New family members mean Airbus means business|work=Interavia Business & Technology|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> The AE31X programme, as it was tentatively dubbed, besides being a global industrial programme would have significantly deepened Sino-European commercial ties.<ref name=Sparaco>{{Cite journal|last=Sparaco|first=Pierre|date=26 May 1997|title=Airbus, Asians Plan Regional Twinjet|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|volume=146|issue=22|pages=24\u201325}}</ref>{{rp|24}} With development costs estimated to be upwards of $2 billion, AVIC would have a 46 percent stake in the project, STAe 15 percent, and Airbus Industrie Asia 39 percent, the latter of which comprised Airbus and Alenia.<ref name=Sparaco/>{{rp|24}} Final assembly would have taken place in China.<ref name=\"N&W p.87\">{{harvnb|Norris|Wagner|1999|p=87}}</ref>\n\nThe project never went past the exploratory phase.<ref name=Terminate>{{Cite journal|last=Sparaco|first=Pierre|date=13 July 1998|title=Europeans, Chinese Terminate AE31X|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|volume=149|issue=2|pages=56\u20137}}</ref>{{rp|56}} It comprised two clean-sheet designs \u2013 the AE316 and the AE317. The AE316 would have had a length of {{Convert|31.3|m|ftin}}, and the AE317, {{Convert|34.5|m|ftin}} .<ref name=AE31X>{{Cite web | last=Lewis| first=Paul| url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1997/1997%20-%203026.html | title=Time out in Asia | accessdate=26 February 2011 | date=5\u201311 November 1997|work=Flight International |issue=4599 |volume= 152 |location=London, UK |publisher=Reed Business Information| pages=38\u201340}}</ref>{{rp|39}} The standard versions of both variants had a maximum take-off weight of {{cvt|49.9|t|lb}} for the smaller version and {{cvt|54.2|t|lb}} for the AE317, and would have been powered by either [[Rolls-Royce BR700|BMW Rolls-Royce]], [[CFM International]], or [[Pratt & Whitney]] turbofan engines.<ref name=\"N&W p.87\"/><ref name=AE31X/>{{rp|39}} Range was settled at {{Convert|3700|km|nmi}} for both standard variants, although there was a higher-gross weight version which had greater range and engine power.<ref name=AE31X/>{{rp|39}} The AE316 and AE317 would have seated a maximum of 105 and 125 passengers in five-abreast seating, respectively. Both would share a flight deck and fly-by-wire flight control system similar to that of the A320 family.<ref name=Interavia/>\n\nMarket research conducted during 1997 revealed that airlines wanted a smaller aircraft in the 70-80-seat range.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mecham|first=Michael|date=20 October 1997|title=Market Tells Asia-Airbus Partners to Make Smaller Jet|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|page=63}}</ref> As the project proceeded, there were increasing disagreements between the Chinese side and Airbus. China wanted a larger aircraft than originally envisioned. In addition, there were difficulties arising out of negotiations about technology transfer and production workshare, and a weak business case.<ref name=Terminate/>{{rp|56}} STAe, having previously expressed doubts about returns on the project,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Paul|date=10\u201316 September 1997|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1997/1997%20-%202270.html|title=STAe thinks again on AE31X|journal=[[Flight International]]|issue=4591|volume=152|page=10}}</ref> in 1998 withdrew from the project out of the failure between AIA and AVIC to reach an agreement; Airbus and AVIC would cancel the project in July that year.<ref>{{Cite news|author1=Moxon, Julian|author2=Lewis, Paul|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/airbus-industrie-and-avic-abandon-ae31x-39195/|title=Airbus Industrie and AVIC abandon AE31X|date=8 July 1998|work=Flightglobal|access-date=23 April 2017}}</ref> The A318 is believed to have emerged from the AE31X project<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Global Commercial Aviation Industry|last=Eriksson|first=Soren|publisher=Routledge|year=2015|isbn=978-1136672392|pages=291}}</ref> though an Airbus-only project, named the A319M5 in March 1998,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/airbus-examines-a319-shrink-33885/|title=Airbus examines A319 shrink|date=4 March 1998|website=Flightglobal.com}}</ref> began before the AE31X cancellation.<ref name=\"Gunston p.222\">{{harvnb|Gunston|2009|p=222}}</ref>\n\n===Design phase===\nThe internal corporate designation, ''A319M5'', was used as early as March 1998,<ref name=\"auto\"/> as an A319 derivative with fuselage shortening of {{Convert|0.79|m|ftin}} ahead of the wing and {{Convert|1.6|m|ftin}} behind.<ref name=\"Gunston p.222\"/> The final proposal was for an aircraft seating 107 passengers in a two-class layout with a range of {{Convert|3350|km|nmi}}. The aircraft's production took advantage of laser welding, eliminating the necessity for heavy rivets and bolts.\n\nDuring the design process, the A318 encountered several problems. The first one was the decline in demand for new aircraft following the [[September 11 attacks]]. Another was the new Pratt & Whitney [[turbofan]] engines, which burned more fuel than expected. By the time [[CFM International]] (CFM) had a more efficient engine ready for market, many A318 customers had already backed out, including [[Air China]] and [[British Airways]]. [[America West Airlines]], which had selected the Pratt & Whitney engines, amended its A318 orders, opting instead for A319 or A320 aircraft. [[Trans World Airlines]] cancelled a significant order for fifty A318s after being acquired by [[American Airlines]], which did not operate any A320 family aircraft at the time (although neither did TWA when the order was originally placed). While Airbus was hoping to market the A318 as a [[regional jet]] alternative, laws in both the U.S. and Europe have kept it in the same class as larger aircraft for calculating charges such as landing fees, limiting the type's market potential.\n\nThe aircraft is powered by two CFM56-5 or Pratt & Whitney [[Pratt & Whitney PW6000|PW6000]] engines with maximum thrust ratings of between {{convert|96|and|106|kN|lbf|sigfig=3}}. Launch customers Frontier Airlines and [[Air France]] took deliveries in 2003, with Frontier receiving its aircraft in July of that year. The list price of an A318 ranges from $56 to $62&nbsp;million, and operating costs are between $2,500 and $3,000 for each flight hour.<ref>\n[http://www.ainonline.com/news/single-news-page/article/new-bizjets/ New Bizjets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504052609/http://www.ainonline.com/news/single-news-page/article/new-bizjets/ |date=4 May 2008 }}  Ainonline\n</ref>\n\nOrders for the A318 have been relatively slow, but slightly better than for its direct competitor the [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-600]]. At 30 September 2017, Airbus had received 80 orders for this model<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/> compared to 69 for the 737-600.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://active.boeing.com/commercial/orders/displaystandardreport.cfm?cboCurrentModel=737&optReportType=AllModels&cboAllModel=737&ViewReportF=View+Report |title=Boeing 737 Model Summary|work=boeing.com|date=30 September 2017|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> The sales pace has been influenced by the strong sales of the [[Bombardier CRJ900]] and [[Embraer E-Jets]] series. The biggest A318 customers at 30 September 2017 were Governments, Executive and Private Jets (20), Air France (18), [[Avianca Holdings]] (15), GECAS (12) and Frontier Airlines (9).<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n\n===Further developments===\nOn 10 November 2005 Airbus announced the '''A318 Elite'''. The Airbus A318 Elite is aimed at the medium-range market for flights of up to {{convert|4000|nmi|km|adj=on}} range, with a choice of two cabin layouts seating up to 18 passengers, and powered by CFM engines. [[Comlux Aviation]] became the launch customer by ordering three A318 Elite aircraft.\n\nIn September 2010, Airbus confirmed that from 2013 the Airbus A318 would become available with ''Sharklets'', [[wingtip device]]s which reduce [[lift-induced drag]] and improve efficiency through reduced fuel consumption.<ref name=Sharklets>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/23/347719/a318-to-be-available-with-sharklets-from-2013.html|title=A318 to be available with sharklets from 2013|author=Ostrower, Jon|work=Flightglobal|date=23 September 2010|accessdate=1 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925221316/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/23/347719/a318-to-be-available-with-sharklets-from-2013.html|archivedate=25 September 2010}}</ref> The optional devices, which will also be available on other Airbus A320 family models and are manufactured by [[Korean Air#Aerospace research and manufacturing|Korean Air Aerospace Division]], will increase the range of the aircraft to {{convert|5930|km|nmi}} \u2013 an increase of {{convert|185|km|nmi}} over a standard A318 with 107 seats in a two-class configuration.<ref name=Sharklets/>\n\n==Design==\nThe Airbus A318 is a small commercial, narrow-body (single-aisle) aircraft with a retractable tricycle [[landing gear]] and is powered by two wing pylon-mounted turbofan engines. Two suppliers provide turbofan engines for the A318, CFM International with the CFM56-5B engine and Pratt & Whitney with the PW6000 engine. It is a low-wing [[cantilever]] [[monoplane]] with a conventional [[Empennage|tail unit]] having a single [[vertical stabilizer]] and [[rudder]].\n\nOverall, the A318 is over six metres shorter and around {{cvt|3|t|lb}} lighter than the A320. To compensate for the reduced [[Moment (physics)|moment arm]], it has a larger [[vertical stabiliser]]. While initial concepts depicted the aircraft with a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-300]]-style dorsal fin extension,<ref>{{cite journal| last= Kingsley-Jones | first= Max |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1999/1999%20-%201737.html |title= Cut and Thrust|journal=[[Flight International]]| date= 9\u201315 June 1999 |volume = 155 |issue = 4680| pages = 150, 153\u2013154 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> the final design incorporated a fin tip extension, making it {{Convert|75|cm|in}} taller than the other A320 variants. Pilots who are trained on the other variants may fly the A318 with no further certification, since it features a common flight deck and the same type rating as its sister aircraft. The A318 is also referred to as the A318-100<ref>https://www.britishairways.com/en-us/information/about-ba/fleet-facts/airbus-318-100 Retrieved 29 June 2017.</ref>\n\nThe A318 is available with a variety of different [[maximum take-off weight]]s (MTOW) ranging from a {{convert|59|tonne|ton}}, {{convert|2750|km|nmi}} base model to a {{convert|68|tonne|ton}}, {{convert|6000|km|nmi}} version. When equipped with CFM56-5B8/P engines, the A318 is available with a 123,000 lb. MTOW or a 150,000 lb. MTOW. When equipped with CFM56-5B9/P engines, the A318 is available with a 130,000 lb. MTOW or a 150,000 lb. MTOW.<ref>https://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Advisory_Circular/AC%2036-1H%20Chg%201.pdf Retrieved 7 May 2017.</ref> The lower MTOW enables it to operate regional routes economically while sacrificing range and the higher MTOW allows it to complement other members of the A320 family on marginal routes. The lighter weight of the A318 gives it an operating range 10% greater than the A320, allowing it to serve some routes that the A320 would be unable to: London \u2013 New York, [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]]\u2013[[Auckland]] and Singapore\u2013Tokyo, for instance. Its main use for airlines, however, is on short, low-density hops between medium-sized cities.\n\n===Steep approach capability===\n[[File:British Airways (G-EUNA) Airbus A318 at London City Airport.jpg|thumb|left|British Airways Airbus A318 at [[London City Airport]].]]\n[[File:Airbus A318 of British Airways at J.F.K. International Airport New York (USA).jpg|thumb|right|British Airways Airbus A318 at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|J.F.K. International Airport New York]]]]\nIn March 2006, the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) certified a modified control software enhancement to the Airbus A318 designed to allow the aircraft to perform steep approaches.<ref name=LondonCity>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2006/05/13/206570/airbus-a318-makes-first-test-arrival-and-departure-at-london-city.html|title=Airbus A318 makes first test arrival and departure at London City Airport|author=Learmount, David|work=Flightglobal|accessdate=1 April 2015|date=13 May 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917072453/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2006/05/13/206570/airbus-a318-makes-first-test-arrival-and-departure-at-london-city.html|archivedate=17 September 2007}}</ref> The aircraft is the largest commercial aircraft certified by EASA for steep approach operations.<ref name=A318steep/> The software modifies the control laws of the aircraft when the steep approach function is selected by the crew, by automatically deploying some of the [[Spoiler (aeronautics)|spoiler]] panels to provide additional drag when the aircraft is in the landing configuration.<ref name=LondonCity/> It also provides alternative aural alerts to the crew and modifies spoiler deployment automatically below {{Convert|120|ft|m}} on landing.<ref name=LondonCity/> The A318 steep approach procedure allows the aircraft to perform approaches at descent angles of up to 5.5\u00b0, as opposed to the standard 3\u00b0 for a normal approach.<ref name=A318steep>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-operations/steep-approach|title=Steep approach|work=airbus.com|accessdate=1 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117185416/http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-operations/steep-approach/|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA test flight was conducted in May 2006 to prove the aircraft's steep approach and short runway performance by landing at [[London City Airport]], where such steep approaches are required. The test flight also confirmed the aircraft's compatibility with the limited manoeuvring and parking space at that airport.<ref name=LondonCity/> Subsequently, in August 2009<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kaminski-Morrow|first=David|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/first-british-airways-a318-arrives-at-london-gatwick-331567/|title=First British Airways A318 arrives at London Gatwick|date=29 August 2009|work=Flightglobal|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> Airbus delivered the first A318 with steep approach capability to [[British Airways]], which began operating the route the following month, eventually having two such aircraft capable of flights between London City Airport and [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in New York. On the westbound leg from London, a stopover is necessary for refueling, which occurs at [[Shannon Airport]], Ireland because weight restrictions are necessary in order to take off within the existing short runway length of London City Airport. On the eastbound leg from New York this limitation is not present and the aircraft can take all the fuel needed for the transatlantic route to London. As of November 2017, only one aircraft is serving the route, operated in a 32-seat all-business-class configuration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishairways.com/en-gb/information/travel-classes/business/club-world-london-city|title=Club World London City|work=britishairways.com}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nAlthough final assembly of A320 family aircraft takes place in Toulouse, France; Hamburg, Germany; Tianjin, China; and Mobile, Alabama, USA, final assembly of the Airbus A318 was in Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-manufacturing/final-assembly-lines/|title=Final assembly lines - Airbus, Commercial Aircraft|website=airbus|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222054429/http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-manufacturing/final-assembly-lines/|archivedate=22 February 2017}}</ref> The maiden flight of the Airbus A318 took place from Finkenwerder airfield in Hamburg on 15 January 2002.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/a318-takes-off-on-maiden-flight/|title=A318 takes off on maiden flight|publisher=Airbus|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708135216/http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/a318-takes-off-on-maiden-flight/|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref> The first customer delivery was on 22 July 2003 to Frontier Airlines.<ref name=\"Gunston p.223\">{{harvnb|Gunston|2009|p=223}}</ref>\nAs of 30 September 2017, 67 A318s remained in service with five airlines, in addition to governments, executive and private jets and undisclosed operators.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/> Most A318 aircraft retired from airline service have been scrapped due to the engine and components being more valuable than whole aircraft. Frontier Airlines, the launch customer that acquired A318 aircraft between 2003 and 2007, had retired their last A318 by 2013.<ref>http://www.airlinereporter.com/2013/09/north-america-says-goodbye-to-the-babybus-airbus-a318/ Retrieved 6 May 2017.</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Airbus A318-121 (cn 1599) F-WWIA at FIDAE.jpg|Airbus A318, in Airbus corporate livery, at the FIDAE 2006 air show at [[Santiago International Airport|Santiago de Chile International Airport]].\nFile:Avianca Airbus A318 Ramirez.jpg|[[Avianca]] Airbus A318 landing\nFile:Tarom A318 YR-ASA.jpg|[[TAROM]] A318 landing at Frankfurt\nFile:Saudi Red Crescent Authority Airbus A318CJ Arroyo.jpg|[[Saudi Red Crescent]] Airbus A318 at [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn International Airport]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Operators==\n{{See also|List of Airbus A320 family operators}}\n\nAs of January 2020, Airbus A318 operators are:<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/asset/24536|title=World Airline Census 2018|website=Flightglobal.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Operator\n!In Operation\n|-\n|[[France]]\n|[[Air France]]\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|[[Romania]]\n|[[TAROM]]\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|[[British Airways]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|[[Titan Airways]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|various\n|Governments, Executive and Private Jets\n|align=\"center\"|19\n|-\n|various\n|Undisclosed operators\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n!Totals||||65\n|}\n\n===Orders and deliveries===\n{{See also|List of Airbus A320 orders}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:96%\"\n|-\n! !!colspan=\"2\"|Orders!!colspan=\"16\"|Deliveries\n|-\n!Type!!Total!!Backlog!!Total!!2017!!2016!!2015!!2014!!2013!!2012!!2011!!2010!!2009!!2008!!2007!!2006!!2005!!2004!!2003\n|-\n!A318\n|80||\u2014||80||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||1||3||2||2||6||13||17||8||9||10||9\n|-\n|}\n<small>''Data through end of September 2017. Updated 7 October 2017.''</small><ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:96%;\"\n|-\n|+ Airbus A318 specifications<ref name=\"A318 specifications\">{{cite web |url= http://www.airbus.com/aircraftfamilies/passengeraircraft/a320family/a318/specifications/ |title= A318 Dimensions & key data |publisher= Airbus}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n![[Cockpit]] crew\n| Two\n|-\n! Exit Limit\n| 136<ref name=cert>{{cite web |url= https://www.easa.europa.eu/system/files/dfu/TCDS_EASA%20A%20064_%20Airbus_%20A318_A319_A320_A321_Iss_22.pdf |title= Type Certificate Data Sheet |publisher= EASA |date= 28 June 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160915235037/https://www.easa.europa.eu/system/files/dfu/TCDS_EASA%20A%20064_%20Airbus_%20A318_A319_A320_A321_Iss_22.pdf |archivedate= 15 September 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"FAA-TCDS\">{{cite web |url= http://www.airweb.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library/rgMakeModel.nsf/0/57529f07d8f6e3b58625800d0057c1d4/$FILE/A28NM_Rev24.pdf |title= Type Certificate Data Sheet |date= 12 August 2016 |publisher= FAA}}</ref>\n|-\n! 1-class max. [[Aircraft seating|seating]]<ref name=AllAbout/>\n| 132 at {{cvt|29|-|30|in|cm}} pitch\n|-\n! 1-class, typical<ref name=AllAbout>{{cite web |url= https://fr.scribd.com/doc/30183955/All-About-Airbus-A-320-Family |title= All About the Airbus A320 Family |date= 2009 |publisher= Airbus}}</ref>\n| 117 at {{cvt|32|in|cm}} pitch\n|-\n! 2-class, typical<ref name=AllAbout/>\n| 107 (8F @ 38&nbsp;in, 99Y @ 32&nbsp;in)\n|-\n![[Cargo aircraft|Cargo]] capacity\n| {{cvt|21.2|m3}}\n|-\n! Length\n| {{cvt|31.44|m|ftin}}\n|-\n![[Wingspan]]\n| {{cvt|34.10|m|ftin}}\n|-\n![[Wing|Wing area]]\n| {{cvt|122.4|m2}}<ref name=elsevier/>\n|-\n![[Aircraft Wing sweepback|Wing sweepback]]\n| 25 degrees<ref name=elsevier>{{cite web |url= http://booksite.elsevier.com/9780340741528/appendices/data-a/table-1/table.htm |title= Airbus Aircraft Data File |publisher= Elsevier |work= Civil Jet Aircraft Design |date= July 1999}}</ref>\n|-\n![[Empennage|Tail]] height\n| {{cvt|12.56|m|ftin}}\n|-\n![[Aircraft cabin|Cabin]] width\n| {{cvt|3.70|m|ftin}}\n|-\n![[Fuselage]] width\n| {{cvt|3.95|m|ftin}}\n|-\n![[Operating empty weight]]\n| {{cvt|39500|kg}}<ref name=AllAbout/>\n|-\n![[Zero-fuel weight|Maximum zero-fuel weight]] (MZFW)\n| {{cvt|54500|kg}}\n|-\n! [[Maximum landing weight]] (MLW)\n| {{cvt|57500|kg}}\n|-\n! [[Maximum take-off weight]] (MTOW)\n| {{cvt|68000|kg}}\n|-\n! Cruising speed\n| {{convert|0.78|Mach|39000|0}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.airbus.com/aircraftfamilies/passengeraircraft/a320family/technology-and-innovation/ |title= A320 Family Technology |publisher= Airbus}}</ref>\n|-\n! Maximum [[speed]]\n| {{convert|0.82|Mach|39000|0}}\n|-\n![[Range (aeronautics)|Range]] (typical [[payload]])\n| {{cvt|3,100|nmi|km|sigfig=3|order=flip}}\n|-\n! [[Airbus Corporate Jets|ACJ]] range\n| {{cvt|4,200|nmi|km}}<ref name=ACJ318>{{cite web |url= http://www.airbus.com/aircraftfamilies/corporate/acj-family/acj318/ |title= ACJ318 |publisher= Airbus |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161201113129/http://www.airbus.com/aircraftfamilies/corporate/acj-family/acj318/ |archivedate= 1 December 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n! Takeoff (MTOW, SL, [[International standard atmosphere|ISA]])\n| {{cvt|1780|m}}<ref name=ACJ318/>\n|-\n!  Landing (MLW, SL, [[International standard atmosphere|ISA]])\n| {{cvt|1230|m}}<ref name=ACJ318/>\n|-\n![[Fuel tank|Fuel capacity]]\n| {{cvt|24210|L}}\n|-\n![[Ceiling (aeronautics)|Ceiling]]\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{cvt|39,100|-|41,000|ft}}<ref name=cert/>\n|-\n![[Jet engine|Engines]] (\u00d72)\n| [[CFM56]]-5B, {{cvt|68.3|in|m|}} fan<br />[[PW6000]]A, {{cvt|56.5|in|m}} fan\n|-\n![[Thrust]] (\u00d72)\n| {{cvt|96|-|106|kN}}\n|}\n\n===Engines===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Aircraft Model !! Certification Date !! Engines\n|-\n| A318-111 || 23 May 2003 || [[CFM International CFM56|CFM56-5B8/P]]\n|-\n| A318-112 || 23 May 2003 || [[CFM International CFM56|CFM56-5B9/P]]\n|-\n| A318-121 || 21 December 2005 || [[Pratt & Whitney PW6000|PW6122A]]\n|-\n| A318-122 || 21 December 2005 || [[Pratt & Whitney PW6000|PW6124A]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n{{aircontent\n|related=\n* [[Airbus A220]]\n* [[Airbus A319]]\n* [[Airbus A320 family]]\n|similar aircraft=\n* [[Antonov An-158]]\n* [[Avro RJ100]]\n* [[Boeing 717]]\n* [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-600]]\n* [[Bombardier CRJ700 series]]\n* [[Embraer E-Jet family|Embraer 195]]\n* [[Fokker 100]]\n* [[Sukhoi Superjet 100]]\n* [[Tupolev Tu-334]]\n* [[Yakovlev Yak-42]]\n|lists=\n* [[List of Airbus A320 operators]]\n* [[List of jet airliners]]\n* [[Lists of airlines]]\n|see also=\n* [[Airbus Corporate Jets]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;References\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n* \"World Airliner Census\". ''Flight International'', Volume 184, Number 5403, 13\u201319 August 2013, pp.&nbsp;40\u201358.\n* {{Cite book|last=Gunston|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Gunston|title=Airbus: The Complete Story|year=2009|location=Sparkford, Yeovil, Somerset, UK |publisher=Haynes Publishing|isbn=978-1-84425-585-6|ref={{harvid|Gunston|2009}}}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Norris|first1=Guy and Mark Wagner|title=Airbus|location=Osceola, Wisconsin|publisher=MBI Publishing|year=1999|isbn=978-0-7603-0677-2|ref={{harvid|Norris|Wagner|1999}}|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/airbus0000norr}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Airbus A318}}\n* [http://www.airbus.com/en/aircraftfamilies/a320/ Official Airbus website of the A320 aircraft family]\n\n{{Airbus A3xx timeline}}\n{{airbus aircraft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Airbus A318}}\n[[Category:Airbus aircraft|A318]]\n[[Category:2000s international airliners]]\n[[Category:Twinjets]]\n[[Category:Airbus A320 family]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airliner, smallest series of the A320 family}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout, and guidelines. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = A318\n| image = File:Airfrance.a318-100.f-guga.arp.jpg\n| alt = aircraft taking off with wheels not retracted\n| caption = An Airbus A318 of [[Air France]], the largest operator of the type\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Narrow-body]] [[jet airliner]]\n| national origin = Multinational{{efn|The Airbus A318 is built in Hamburg, Germany}}\n| manufacturer = [[Airbus]]\n| designer = \n| first flight = 15 January 2002\n| introduced = 2003 with [[Frontier Airlines]]\n| produced = 2003\u20132013 \n| retired = \n| status = In service\n| primary user = [[Air France]]\n| more users =  [[TAROM]]<br />[[British Airways]]<!--Limit of three (3) more users here. -->\n| number built = 80<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n| unit cost = [[US$]]77.4&nbsp;million, \u20ac63 million (2018)<ref name=\"2018 price\">{{cite press release|title=Airbus 2018 Price List Press Release|date=23 January 2018|url=http://www.airbus.com/newsroom/press-releases/en/2018/01/airbus-2018-price-list-press-release.html|website=Airbus|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n| developed from = [[Airbus A319]]\n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Airbus A318''' is the smallest [[airliner]] in the [[Airbus A320 family]]. The A318 carries 107 to 132 passengers and has a maximum range of {{cvt|3100|nmi|km|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"A318 specifications\"/> Final assembly of the aircraft took place in [[Hamburg]], Germany.\nIt is intended primarily for short-range service, although [[British Airways]] uses the aircraft on a [[London City Airport]] to [[New York-JFK Airport]] transatlantic route (albeit with a stopover in [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]] for refueling on the westbound leg, as it is too heavy to clear the short runway at LCY with a full load of fuel).\n\nThe aircraft shares a common [[type rating]] with all other Airbus A320 family variants, allowing existing A320 family pilots to fly the aircraft without the need for further training. It is the largest commercial aircraft certified by the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] for steep approach operations, allowing flights at airports such as [[London City Airport|London City]].<ref name=A318steep/>\n\nThe A318 entered service in July 2003 with [[Frontier Airlines]]. Relative to other Airbus A320 family variants, it has sold in only small numbers with total orders for 80 aircraft placed, with the order book currently being empty.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aircraft.airbus.com/market/orders-deliveries/|publisher=Airbus|title=Airbus Orders & Deliveries|date=30 September 2017|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> It also has an excellent safety record with zero accidents as of 2018. As of January 2019, [[Air France]] was the largest operator of the Airbus A318.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\" />\n\n== Development ==<!-- Linked from [[Airbus A320 family]] -->\n\n===Background===\nThe first member of the A320 aircraft family was the A320, which [[Maiden flight|first flew]] on 22 February 1987 after the program was launched in March 1984.<ref>{{harvnb|Norris|Wagner|1999|p=50}}</ref> The family was soon extended to include the stretched A321 (first delivery 1994), the shortened [[Airbus A319|A319]] (first delivery 1996), and the further shortened A318 (first delivery 2003). The A320 family pioneered the use in commercial aircraft of digital [[fly-by-wire]] [[Aircraft flight control system|flight control systems]], as well as [[side stick]] controls.\n\nThe Airbus A318 project had its origins in the collaboration among Chinese, Singaporean and European manufacturers. In May 1997, during the visit of French President [[Jacques Chirac]] to China, [[Aviation Industry Corporation of China|Aviation Industries of China]] (AVIC), [[ST Aerospace|Singapore Technologies Aerospace]] (STAe), Airbus and [[Alenia Aermacchi|Alenia]] signed a framework agreement that outlined the development of aircraft in the 100-seat range.<ref name=Interavia>{{Cite web|author1=Condom, Pierre|author2=Sutton, Oliver|date=1 June 1997|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19778327.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702024922/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19778327.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 July 2016|title=New family members mean Airbus means business|work=Interavia Business & Technology|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> The AE31X programme, as it was tentatively dubbed, besides being a global industrial programme would have significantly deepened Sino-European commercial ties.<ref name=Sparaco>{{Cite journal|last=Sparaco|first=Pierre|date=26 May 1997|title=Airbus, Asians Plan Regional Twinjet|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|volume=146|issue=22|pages=24\u201325}}</ref>{{rp|24}} With development costs estimated to be upwards of $2 billion, AVIC would have a 46 percent stake in the project, STAe 15 percent, and Airbus Industrie Asia 39 percent, the latter of which comprised Airbus and Alenia.<ref name=Sparaco/>{{rp|24}} Final assembly would have taken place in China.<ref name=\"N&W p.87\">{{harvnb|Norris|Wagner|1999|p=87}}</ref>\n\nThe project never went past the exploratory phase.<ref name=Terminate>{{Cite journal|last=Sparaco|first=Pierre|date=13 July 1998|title=Europeans, Chinese Terminate AE31X|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|volume=149|issue=2|pages=56\u20137}}</ref>{{rp|56}} It comprised two clean-sheet designs \u2013 the AE316 and the AE317. The AE316 would have had a length of {{Convert|31.3|m|ftin}}, and the AE317, {{Convert|34.5|m|ftin}} .<ref name=AE31X>{{Cite web | last=Lewis| first=Paul| url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1997/1997%20-%203026.html | title=Time out in Asia | accessdate=26 February 2011 | date=5\u201311 November 1997|work=Flight International |issue=4599 |volume= 152 |location=London, UK |publisher=Reed Business Information| pages=38\u201340}}</ref>{{rp|39}} The standard versions of both variants had a maximum take-off weight of {{cvt|49.9|t|lb}} for the smaller version and {{cvt|54.2|t|lb}} for the AE317, and would have been powered by either [[Rolls-Royce BR700|BMW Rolls-Royce]], [[CFM International]], or [[Pratt & Whitney]] turbofan engines.<ref name=\"N&W p.87\"/><ref name=AE31X/>{{rp|39}} Range was settled at {{Convert|3700|km|nmi}} for both standard variants, although there was a higher-gross weight version which had greater range and engine power.<ref name=AE31X/>{{rp|39}} The AE316 and AE317 would have seated a maximum of 105 and 125 passengers in five-abreast seating, respectively. Both would share a flight deck and fly-by-wire flight control system similar to that of the A320 family.<ref name=Interavia/>\n\nMarket research conducted during 1997 revealed that airlines wanted a smaller aircraft in the 70-80-seat range.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mecham|first=Michael|date=20 October 1997|title=Market Tells Asia-Airbus Partners to Make Smaller Jet|journal=Aviation Week & Space Technology|page=63}}</ref> As the project proceeded, there were increasing disagreements between the Chinese side and Airbus. China wanted a larger aircraft than originally envisioned. In addition, there were difficulties arising out of negotiations about technology transfer and production workshare, and a weak business case.<ref name=Terminate/>{{rp|56}} STAe, having previously expressed doubts about returns on the project,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Paul|date=10\u201316 September 1997|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1997/1997%20-%202270.html|title=STAe thinks again on AE31X|journal=[[Flight International]]|issue=4591|volume=152|page=10}}</ref> in 1998 withdrew from the project out of the failure between AIA and AVIC to reach an agreement; Airbus and AVIC would cancel the project in July that year.<ref>{{Cite news|author1=Moxon, Julian|author2=Lewis, Paul|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/airbus-industrie-and-avic-abandon-ae31x-39195/|title=Airbus Industrie and AVIC abandon AE31X|date=8 July 1998|work=Flightglobal|access-date=23 April 2017}}</ref> The A318 is believed to have emerged from the AE31X project<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Global Commercial Aviation Industry|last=Eriksson|first=Soren|publisher=Routledge|year=2015|isbn=978-1136672392|pages=291}}</ref> though an Airbus-only project, named the A319M5 in March 1998,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/airbus-examines-a319-shrink-33885/|title=Airbus examines A319 shrink|date=4 March 1998|website=Flightglobal.com}}</ref> began before the AE31X cancellation.<ref name=\"Gunston p.222\">{{harvnb|Gunston|2009|p=222}}</ref>\n\n===Design phase===\nThe internal corporate designation, ''A319M5'', was used as early as March 1998,<ref name=\"auto\"/> as an A319 derivative with fuselage shortening of {{Convert|0.79|m|ftin}} ahead of the wing and {{Convert|1.6|m|ftin}} behind.<ref name=\"Gunston p.222\"/> The final proposal was for an aircraft seating 107 passengers in a two-class layout with a range of {{Convert|3350|km|nmi}}. The aircraft's production took advantage of laser welding, eliminating the necessity for heavy rivets and bolts.\n\nDuring the design process, the A318 encountered several problems. The first one was the decline in demand for new aircraft following the [[September 11 attacks]]. Another was the new Pratt & Whitney [[turbofan]] engines, which burned more fuel than expected. By the time [[CFM International]] (CFM) had a more efficient engine ready for market, many A318 customers had already backed out, including [[Air China]] and [[British Airways]]. [[America West Airlines]], which had selected the Pratt & Whitney engines, amended its A318 orders, opting instead for A319 or A320 aircraft. [[Trans World Airlines]] cancelled a significant order for fifty A318s after being acquired by [[American Airlines]], which did not operate any A320 family aircraft at the time (although neither did TWA when the order was originally placed). While Airbus was hoping to market the A318 as a [[regional jet]] alternative, laws in both the U.S. and Europe have kept it in the same class as larger aircraft for calculating charges such as landing fees, limiting the type's market potential.\n\nThe aircraft is powered by two CFM56-5 or Pratt & Whitney [[Pratt & Whitney PW6000|PW6000]] engines with maximum thrust ratings of between {{convert|96|and|106|kN|lbf|sigfig=3}}. Launch customers Frontier Airlines and [[Air France]] took deliveries in 2003, with Frontier receiving its aircraft in July of that year. The list price of an A318 ranges from $56 to $62&nbsp;million, and operating costs are between $2,500 and $3,000 for each flight hour.<ref>\n[http://www.ainonline.com/news/single-news-page/article/new-bizjets/ New Bizjets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504052609/http://www.ainonline.com/news/single-news-page/article/new-bizjets/ |date=4 May 2008 }}  Ainonline\n</ref>\n\nOrders for the A318 have been relatively slow, but slightly better than for its direct competitor the [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-600]]. At 30 September 2017, Airbus had received 80 orders for this model<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/> compared to 69 for the 737-600.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://active.boeing.com/commercial/orders/displaystandardreport.cfm?cboCurrentModel=737&optReportType=AllModels&cboAllModel=737&ViewReportF=View+Report |title=Boeing 737 Model Summary|work=boeing.com|date=30 September 2017|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> The sales pace has been influenced by the strong sales of the [[Bombardier CRJ900]] and [[Embraer E-Jets]] series. The biggest A318 customers at 30 September 2017 were Governments, Executive and Private Jets (20), Air France (18), [[Avianca Holdings]] (15), GECAS (12) and Frontier Airlines (9).<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n\n===Further developments===\nOn 10 November 2005 Airbus announced the '''A318 Elite'''. The Airbus A318 Elite is aimed at the medium-range market for flights of up to {{convert|4000|nmi|km|adj=on}} range, with a choice of two cabin layouts seating up to 18 passengers, and powered by CFM engines. [[Comlux Aviation]] became the launch customer by ordering three A318 Elite aircraft.\n\nIn September 2010, Airbus confirmed that from 2013 the Airbus A318 would become available with ''Sharklets'', [[wingtip device]]s which reduce [[lift-induced drag]] and improve efficiency through reduced fuel consumption.<ref name=Sharklets>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/23/347719/a318-to-be-available-with-sharklets-from-2013.html|title=A318 to be available with sharklets from 2013|author=Ostrower, Jon|work=Flightglobal|date=23 September 2010|accessdate=1 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925221316/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/23/347719/a318-to-be-available-with-sharklets-from-2013.html|archivedate=25 September 2010}}</ref> The optional devices, which will also be available on other Airbus A320 family models and are manufactured by [[Korean Air#Aerospace research and manufacturing|Korean Air Aerospace Division]], will increase the range of the aircraft to {{convert|5930|km|nmi}} \u2013 an increase of {{convert|185|km|nmi}} over a standard A318 with 107 seats in a two-class configuration.<ref name=Sharklets/>\n\n==Design==\nThe Airbus A318 is a small commercial, narrow-body (single-aisle) aircraft with a retractable tricycle [[landing gear]] and is powered by two wing pylon-mounted turbofan engines. Two suppliers provide turbofan engines for the A318, CFM International with the CFM56-5B engine and Pratt & Whitney with the PW6000 engine. It is a low-wing [[cantilever]] [[monoplane]] with a conventional [[Empennage|tail unit]] having a single [[vertical stabilizer]] and [[rudder]].\n\nOverall, the A318 is over six metres shorter and around {{cvt|3|t|lb}} lighter than the A320. To compensate for the reduced [[Moment (physics)|moment arm]], it has a larger [[vertical stabiliser]]. While initial concepts depicted the aircraft with a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-300]]-style dorsal fin extension,<ref>{{cite journal| last= Kingsley-Jones | first= Max |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1999/1999%20-%201737.html |title= Cut and Thrust|journal=[[Flight International]]| date= 9\u201315 June 1999 |volume = 155 |issue = 4680| pages = 150, 153\u2013154 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> the final design incorporated a fin tip extension, making it {{Convert|75|cm|in}} taller than the other A320 variants. Pilots who are trained on the other variants may fly the A318 with no further certification, since it features a common flight deck and the same type rating as its sister aircraft. The A318 is also referred to as the A318-100<ref>https://www.britishairways.com/en-us/information/about-ba/fleet-facts/airbus-318-100 Retrieved 29 June 2017.</ref>\n\nThe A318 is available with a variety of different [[maximum take-off weight]]s (MTOW) ranging from a {{convert|59|tonne|ton}}, {{convert|2750|km|nmi}} base model to a {{convert|68|tonne|ton}}, {{convert|6000|km|nmi}} version. When equipped with CFM56-5B8/P engines, the A318 is available with a 123,000 lb. MTOW or a 150,000 lb. MTOW. When equipped with CFM56-5B9/P engines, the A318 is available with a 130,000 lb. MTOW or a 150,000 lb. MTOW.<ref>https://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Advisory_Circular/AC%2036-1H%20Chg%201.pdf Retrieved 7 May 2017.</ref> The lower MTOW enables it to operate regional routes economically while sacrificing range and the higher MTOW allows it to complement other members of the A320 family on marginal routes. The lighter weight of the A318 gives it an operating range 10% greater than the A320, allowing it to serve some routes that the A320 would be unable to: London \u2013 New York, [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]]\u2013[[Auckland]] and Singapore\u2013Tokyo, for instance. Its main use for airlines, however, is on short, low-density hops between medium-sized cities.\n\n===Steep approach capability===\n[[File:British Airways (G-EUNA) Airbus A318 at London City Airport.jpg|thumb|left|British Airways Airbus A318 at [[London City Airport]].]]\n[[File:Airbus A318 of British Airways at J.F.K. International Airport New York (USA).jpg|thumb|right|British Airways Airbus A318 at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|J.F.K. International Airport New York]]]]\nIn March 2006, the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) certified a modified control software enhancement to the Airbus A318 designed to allow the aircraft to perform steep approaches.<ref name=LondonCity>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2006/05/13/206570/airbus-a318-makes-first-test-arrival-and-departure-at-london-city.html|title=Airbus A318 makes first test arrival and departure at London City Airport|author=Learmount, David|work=Flightglobal|accessdate=1 April 2015|date=13 May 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917072453/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2006/05/13/206570/airbus-a318-makes-first-test-arrival-and-departure-at-london-city.html|archivedate=17 September 2007}}</ref> The aircraft is the largest commercial aircraft certified by EASA for steep approach operations.<ref name=A318steep/> The software modifies the control laws of the aircraft when the steep approach function is selected by the crew, by automatically deploying some of the [[Spoiler (aeronautics)|spoiler]] panels to provide additional drag when the aircraft is in the landing configuration.<ref name=LondonCity/> It also provides alternative aural alerts to the crew and modifies spoiler deployment automatically below {{Convert|120|ft|m}} on landing.<ref name=LondonCity/> The A318 steep approach procedure allows the aircraft to perform approaches at descent angles of up to 5.5\u00b0, as opposed to the standard 3\u00b0 for a normal approach.<ref name=A318steep>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-operations/steep-approach|title=Steep approach|work=airbus.com|accessdate=1 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117185416/http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-operations/steep-approach/|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA test flight was conducted in May 2006 to prove the aircraft's steep approach and short runway performance by landing at [[London City Airport]], where such steep approaches are required. The test flight also confirmed the aircraft's compatibility with the limited manoeuvring and parking space at that airport.<ref name=LondonCity/> Subsequently, in August 2009<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kaminski-Morrow|first=David|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/first-british-airways-a318-arrives-at-london-gatwick-331567/|title=First British Airways A318 arrives at London Gatwick|date=29 August 2009|work=Flightglobal|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> Airbus delivered the first A318 with steep approach capability to [[British Airways]], which began operating the route the following month, eventually having two such aircraft capable of flights between London City Airport and [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in New York. On the westbound leg from London, a stopover is necessary for refueling, which occurs at [[Shannon Airport]], Ireland because weight restrictions are necessary in order to take off within the existing short runway length of London City Airport. On the eastbound leg from New York this limitation is not present and the aircraft can take all the fuel needed for the transatlantic route to London. As of November 2017, only one aircraft is serving the route, operated in a 32-seat all-business-class configuration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishairways.com/en-gb/information/travel-classes/business/club-world-london-city|title=Club World London City|work=britishairways.com}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nAlthough final assembly of A320 family aircraft takes place in Toulouse, France; Hamburg, Germany; Tianjin, China; and Mobile, Alabama, USA, final assembly of the Airbus A318 was in Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-manufacturing/final-assembly-lines/|title=Final assembly lines - Airbus, Commercial Aircraft|website=airbus|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222054429/http://www.airbus.com/innovation/proven-concepts/in-manufacturing/final-assembly-lines/|archivedate=22 February 2017}}</ref> The maiden flight of the Airbus A318 took place from Finkenwerder airfield in Hamburg on 15 January 2002.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/a318-takes-off-on-maiden-flight/|title=A318 takes off on maiden flight|publisher=Airbus|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708135216/http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/a318-takes-off-on-maiden-flight/|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref> The first customer delivery was on 22 July 2003 to Frontier Airlines.<ref name=\"Gunston p.223\">{{harvnb|Gunston|2009|p=223}}</ref>\nAs of 30 September 2017, 67 A318s remained in service with five airlines, in addition to governments, executive and private jets and undisclosed operators.<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/> Most A318 aircraft retired from airline service have been scrapped due to the engine and components being more valuable than whole aircraft. Frontier Airlines, the launch customer that acquired A318 aircraft between 2003 and 2007, had retired their last A318 by 2013.<ref>http://www.airlinereporter.com/2013/09/north-america-says-goodbye-to-the-babybus-airbus-a318/ Retrieved 6 May 2017.</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Airbus A318-121 (cn 1599) F-WWIA at FIDAE.jpg|Airbus A318, in Airbus corporate livery, at the FIDAE 2006 air show at [[Santiago International Airport|Santiago de Chile International Airport]].\nFile:Avianca Airbus A318 Ramirez.jpg|[[Avianca]] Airbus A318 landing\nFile:Tarom A318 YR-ASA.jpg|[[TAROM]] A318 landing at Frankfurt\nFile:Saudi Red Crescent Authority Airbus A318CJ Arroyo.jpg|[[Saudi Red Crescent]] Airbus A318 at [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn International Airport]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Operators==\n{{See also|List of Airbus A320 family operators}}\n\nAs of January 2020, Airbus A318 operators are:<ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/asset/24536|title=World Airline Census 2018|website=Flightglobal.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Operator\n!In Operation\n|-\n|[[France]]\n|[[Air France]]\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|[[Romania]]\n|[[TAROM]]\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|[[British Airways]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|[[Titan Airways]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|various\n|Governments, Executive and Private Jets\n|align=\"center\"|19\n|-\n|various\n|Undisclosed operators\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n!Totals||||65\n|}\n\n===Orders and deliveries===\n{{See also|List of Airbus A320 orders}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:96%\"\n|-\n! !!colspan=\"2\"|Orders!!colspan=\"16\"|Deliveries\n|-\n!Type!!Total!!Backlog!!Total!!2017!!2016!!2015!!2014!!2013!!2012!!2011!!2010!!2009!!2008!!2007!!2006!!2005!!2004!!2003\n|-\n!A318\n|80||\u2014||80||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||1||3||2||2||6||13||17||8||9||10||9\n|-\n|}\n<small>''Data through end of September 2017. Updated 7 October 2017.''</small><ref name=\"Airbus O&D\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:96%;\"\n|-\n|+ Airbus A318 specifications<ref name=\"A318 specifications\">{{cite web |url= http://www.airbus.com/aircraftfamilies/passengeraircraft/a320family/a318/specifications/ |title= A318 Dimensions & key data |publisher= Airbus}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n![[Cockpit]] crew\n| Tw